A.D.W. Atkins.name: A.D.W. Atkins
A.D.W. Atkins.description: Raised by Mr A.D.W. Atkins, Exmouth, Devon in about 1971. Fruits retain a good flavour when cooked.

Abbondanza.name: Abbondanza
Abbondanza.description: An Italian variety which was selected in 1896. Fruits have firm, cream flesh with a very strong vinous flavour.

Abondance.name: Abondance
Abondance.description: Thought to be of French origin. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947. Fruits have a rather coarse, dry, white flesh which soon discolours. Flavour is sweet to subacid.

Acklam Russet.name: Acklam Russet
Acklam Russet.description: Originated at Acklam, Yorkshire. Recorded in 1768. Fruits have a firm, greenish-white flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Acme.name: Acme
Acme.description: Raised in 1944 at Boreham, Essex by W. Seabrook & Sons Ltd. Fruits have firm, cream flesh with a slightly perfumed flavour.

Adams's Pearmain.name: Adams's Pearmain
Adams's Pearmain.description: Brought to notice in 1826 and introduced and exhibited by R. Adams from Herefordshire. A popular Edwardian and Victorian dessert apple. Fruits are juicy and a little sweet, with a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Adamsapfel Ostpreussischer.name: Adamsapfel Ostpreussischer
Adamsapfel Ostpreussischer.description: A German variety received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits are described as being sweet, crisp and very juicy.

Adersleber Calville.name: Adersleber Calville
Adersleber Calville.description: A German variety raised in about 1870 at Adersleben, Saxony by Lichtard. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with a subacid, sweet flavour.

Admiral.name: Admiral
Admiral.description: Raised at Upton, Norfolk by A.K. Watson in about 1921. Introduced by Watson in about 1937. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a sweet flavour.

Advance.name: Advance
Advance.description: Raised at Bedford by Laxton Bros. Ltd., in 1908 and introduced by them in 1929. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1932. Fruits have soft, fine flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour. Trees tend to be prone to mildew and canker.

Akane.name: Akane
Akane.description: Raised in 1937 at Morioka Experimental Station, Japan. Introduced in 1970. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a pleasant flavour.

Akero.name: Akero
Akero.description: Thought to have originated in Sweden. Known in the mid 1700s and brought to notice by pomologist Eneroth in about 1850. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a sweet to subacid aromatic flavour.

Aldenham Blenheim.name: Aldenham Blenheim
Aldenham Blenheim.description: Triploid. Believed to be a coloured sport of Blenheim Orange. It was discovered before 1929 at Aldenham House, Hertfordshire by Edwin Beckett. Fruits have creamy white, somewhat coarse-textured, rather dry flesh with a rich, characteristic aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

Alderman.name: Alderman
Alderman.description: Thought to have originated in Scotland before 1923. Fruits have firm flesh with an acid flavour. Cooks well.

Aldwick Beauty.name: Aldwick Beauty
Aldwick Beauty.description: A seedling which arose in the garden of Mrs D.M. Alford, Aldwick, Bognor Regis, Sussex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1969. Fruits are sweet but tend to be rather dry.

Alexander.name: Alexander
Alexander.description: Thought to be Ukrainian. Known in the 1700s. Introduced to the UK in 1805. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, dry, acid flesh with very little flavour.

Alexis.name: Alexis
Alexis.description: A more highly coloured sport of McIntosh. Received via Scotland from Yugoslavia. It first fruited in Scotland in 1960.Fruits have rather soft, very juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant vinous flavour.

Alfa 68.name: Alfa 68
Alfa 68.description: Raised in 1937 at the Horticultural Research Station, Alnarp, Sweden. It was introduced in 1954. Fruits have firm, tender, juicy, acid flesh, with a good flavour.

Alfriston.name: Alfriston
Alfriston.description: Raised in the late 1700s by Mr Shepherd at Uckfield, Sussex and named Shepherd's Pippin. Re-named Alfriston in 1819. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1920. Fruits are soft, coarse-textured, not very juicy and acid. Cooks well.

Alice.name: Alice
Alice.description: Raised in 1943 at Balsgard Fruit Breeding Institute, Sweden. Introduced in 1962. Fruits are crisp and juicy but with little flavour.

Alkmene.name: Alkmene
Alkmene.description: Raised in 1930 at the former Kaiser Wilhelm Institute, Brandenburg, Germany. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a Cox like flavour.

All-Red Gravenstein.name: All-Red Gravenstein
All-Red Gravenstein.description: Triploid. A coloured sport of Gravenstein originating from the U.S.A. Fruits are crisp, coarse-textured and juicy with a distinct flavour.

Allen's Everlasting.name: Allen's Everlasting
Allen's Everlasting.description: Catalogued in 1864. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a fair flavour.

Allington Pippin.name: Allington Pippin
Allington Pippin.description: Raised by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire before 1884. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1894 under its original name, 'Brown's South Lincoln Beauty'. Renamed in 1894 and introduced by Bunyard of Maidstone in 1896. Once a commercial dessert variety. Fruits have a distinct aromatic flavour.

Alnarps Favorit.name: Alnarps Favorit
Alnarps Favorit.description: Triploid. Raised in 1945 at the Horticultural Research Station, Alnarp, Sweden. Selected in 1967. Fruits have sweet, soft flesh.

Altlander Rosenapfel.name: Altlander Rosenapfel
Altlander Rosenapfel.description: Originated in the Altes Land, Germany. Known in about 1850. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with an acid flavour.

Alton.name: Alton
Alton.description: Raised in 1923 by Richard Wellington at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Introduced in 1938. Fruits are similar in flavour to McIntosh.

Amanishiki.name: Amanishiki
Amanishiki.description: Raised in 1936 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits are sweet and insipid - fails to ripen properly in Britain.

Ambassy.name: Ambassy
Ambassy.description: A more highly coloured clone of Delcorf. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Amber.name: Amber
Amber.description: Raised before 1936 at Chelmsford, Essex by W. Seabrook and Sons. Fruits have tender, firm, yellowish-white flesh.

Ambro.name: Ambro
Ambro.description: Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1998 from T. Visser, Wageningen, Netherlands. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

American Beauty.name: American Beauty
American Beauty.description: Originated in Sterling, Massachusetts, USA. Recorded in 1854. Fruits have softish flesh with a slightly aromatic flavour.

American Golden Russet.name: American Golden Russet
American Golden Russet.description: Originated in the late 1700s in Burlington County, New Jersey, USA. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a subacid, aromatic flavour.

American Grindling.name: American Grindling
American Grindling.description: Originated from U.S.A. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have soft, coarse, acid flesh.

American Summer Pearmain.name: American Summer Pearmain
American Summer Pearmain.description: Originated from U.S.A. First described in 1817. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet aromatic flavour.

Ames.name: Ames
Ames.description: Raised at Iowa Agricultural Experimental Station, Ames, Iowa, U.S.A by H.L. Lantz. It was introduced in the 1920s. Fruits have soft, fine, juicy flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Amorosa.name: Amorosa
Amorosa.description: A coloured sport of Aroma originating in Sweden. Fruits have very juicy, melting flesh with a good flavour.

Ananas Reinette.name: Ananas Reinette
Ananas Reinette.description: Thought to have originated in The Netherlands. Recorded in 1821. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a perfumed pineapple flavour.

Angyal Dezso.name: Angyal Dezso
Angyal Dezso.description: Thought to have originated in the 1900s from Hungary. Fruits have crisp, coarse flesh with a sweet to subacid and nutty flavour.

Anna Boelens.name: Anna Boelens
Anna Boelens.description: Originated either from The Netherlands or Germany. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Received the Certificate of Merit from The Netherlands Pomological Society. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a strong aniseed flavour.

Annie Elizabeth.name: Annie Elizabeth
Annie Elizabeth.description: Raised by Samuel Greatorex at Knighton, Leicester in about 1857 and named after his baby daughter who died in 1866. Introduced in about 1898. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1868. A fine, late-keeping cooking apple.

Antonovka.name: Antonovka
Antonovka.description: A Russian variety which arose in Kursk. Recorded in 1826. Fruits are crisp and juicy with an acid flavour. Cooks well.

Antonovka Grammovaya 600.name: Antonovka Grammovaya 600
Antonovka Grammovaya 600.description: Thought to be a sport of Antonovka. It was discovered by I.V. Michurin in Mogilev, Russia in 1888. Introduced in 1892. It produces larger fruit than Antonovka. Fruits have softish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Antonovka-kamenichka.name: Antonovka-kamenichka
Antonovka-kamenichka.description: Originated from Chernigov, Ukraine, Russia. Recorded in 1889.

Aori.name: Aori
Aori.description: Raised at Aomori Apple Experimental Station, Japan. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1977. Fruits are very sweet and tend to have a tough skin.

Api.name: Api
Api.description: Also known as Lady Apple. It is thought to have been found in the Forest of Apis, Brittany, France. Recorded in 1628. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with an aromatic flavour. Highly decorative fruits.

Api Noir.name: Api Noir
Api Noir.description: Originated in France. Known in the late 1700s. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with an aromatic flavour. Very similar to Api.

Appel van Paris.name: Appel van Paris
Appel van Paris.description: Raised in 1935 by Professor Sprenger at Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have a slightly scented flavour.

Ard Cairn Russet.name: Ard Cairn Russet
Ard Cairn Russet.description: Discovered by Baylor Hartland in Cork, Ireland in about 1890. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1910. Fruits are firm, sweet with little juice. Flavour is slightly aromatic.

Arkansas.name: Arkansas
Arkansas.description: Triploid. Originated near Rhea Mills, Arkansas, U.S.A. from seed sown in about 1833. Introduced in about 1868. Fruits have firm, cream flesh with a subacid flavour.

Arkcharm.name: Arkcharm
Arkcharm.description: Raised at the University of Arkansas, USA and received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1997. Fruits have juicy, softish flesh with a fairly pleasant flavour.

Arlet.name: Arlet
Arlet.description: Raised at the Federal Agricultural Research Station, Wadenswil, Switzerland. Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1995. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a slightly perfumed flavour.

Aroma.name: Aroma
Aroma.description: Raised in 1945 at Balsgard Fruit Breeding Institute, Sweden. Introduced in 1973. Fruits have very juicy, melting flesh with a good flavour.

Aromatic Russet (Scott).name: Aromatic Russet (Scott)
Aromatic Russet (Scott).description: An apple of UK origin. Introduced in about 1850. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Arthur Turner.name: Arthur Turner
Arthur Turner.description: Raised by Charles Turner at Slough, Bucks., and introduced by him in 1915. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912 as 'Turner's Prolific'. It was renamed in 1913. A large cooking apple with somewhat tough skin. Well known for its particularly attractive blossom, for which it received an Award of Garden Merit in 1945.

Arthur W. Barnes.name: Arthur W. Barnes
Arthur W. Barnes.description: Raised in 1902 at Eaton Gardens, Chester, by N.F. Barnes, head gardener to the Duke of Westminster. Introduced in 1928 by Clibrans of Altrincham. Cooks well.

Ascot.name: Ascot
Ascot.description: Raised in 1898 at the Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1913 by the Horticultural Division. Fruits have soft, juicy, sweet flesh.

Ashdown Seedling.name: Ashdown Seedling
Ashdown Seedling.description: Originated with the Ashdown and General Land Company, Horsted Keynes, Sussex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1966. Fruits are very similar to Discovery.

Ashmead's Kernel.name: Ashmead's Kernel
Ashmead's Kernel.description: Raised in about 1700 by Dr Ashmead, Gloucester. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1981. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a rich aromatic flavour.

Astillisch.name: Astillisch
Astillisch.description: Raised in 1929 at the former Kaiser-Wilhelm Institut, Muncheberg, Germany. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh and can be rather acid.

Astrachan Large Fruited.name: Astrachan Large Fruited
Astrachan Large Fruited.description: Found in the 1850s near Stockholm, Sweden by E. Lindgren and introduced by him in the early 1860s. Fruits have firm, cream flesh with a sweet and subacid flavour.

Astramel.name: Astramel
Astramel.description: Raised in 1993 at the Fruit Research Station, Jork, Hamburg, Germany. Fruits have sweet, rather melting flesh.

Atalanta (Netherlands).name: Atalanta (Netherlands)
Atalanta (Netherlands).description: Raised in 1935 by Professor Sprenger at Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have firm flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Atlas.name: Atlas
Atlas.description: Raised at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada from seed sown in 1898. Introduced in about 1924. Fruits have juicy, soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Auralia.name: Auralia
Auralia.description: Raised at the former Kaiser-Wilhelm Institut, Muncheberg, Germany. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1967. Fruits have a sweet subacid, aromatic and perfumed flavour.

Autumn Arctic.name: Autumn Arctic
Autumn Arctic.description: Originated from U.S.A. where it arose from a pile of chicken house litter on a farm in Vermont. Fruits have sweet, soft flesh with a little flavour. It is reputed to have some resistance to scab.

Autumn Harvest.name: Autumn Harvest
Autumn Harvest.description: Thought to have originated in Westmorland. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have firm, tender, coarse, dry flesh with a subacid flavour. Flesh tends to brown very quickly once cut.

Autumn Pearmain.name: Autumn Pearmain
Autumn Pearmain.description: Originated in England and known to have been in existence in the late 1500s. The trees at Brogdale are indistinguishable from Herefordshire Pearmain. A dessert apple of quite reasonable quality as a garden variety. Fruit has a pleasant, slightly aromatic flavour.

Averdal.name: Averdal
Averdal.description: A sport of Red King Delicious. Fruits have firm, juicy, very sweet flesh with a highly aromatic flavour.

Baker's Delicious.name: Baker's Delicious
Baker's Delicious.description: Found in Wales and introduced in 1932 by Bakers of Codsall, Wolverhampton. Fruits are firm, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.

Balder.name: Balder
Balder.description: Raised in 1950 by A.A. Schaap at the Institute of Horticultural Plant Breeding, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits are very similar to James Grieve.

Baldwin.name: Baldwin
Baldwin.description: Triploid. A chance seedling found on the farm of John Ball, Wilmington, Massachusetts, U.S.A. in about 1740. Introduced by Colonel Baldwin in about 1780. Fruits are coarse textured and juicy but lack flavour. It was once an important commercial variety in the U.S.A.

Ball's Pippin.name: Ball's Pippin
Ball's Pippin.description: Introduced in 1923 by J.C.Allgrove, Langley, Bucks. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1923. Fruits are sweet and crisp.

Ballarat Seedling.name: Ballarat Seedling
Ballarat Seedling.description: Found at Ballarat, Victoria, Australia in the garden of Mrs Stewart. Known in the early 1900s. Fruits have coarse, hard flesh with a subacid flavour.

Ballard Beauty.name: Ballard Beauty
Ballard Beauty.description: Raised in 1946 at Bedford by A. Norman. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Ballyfatten.name: Ballyfatten
Ballyfatten.description: Originated from Northern Ireland. First recorded in 1802. Fruits have firm, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Bancroft.name: Bancroft
Bancroft.description: Originated in Ottawa, Canada by the Division of Horticulture Experimental Farm. It was selected in 1930 and introduced in about 1935. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Banffy Pal.name: Banffy Pal
Banffy Pal.description: Thought to have probably originated in Hungary. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have a sweet to subacid flavour.

Banziger.name: Banziger
Banziger.description: An American variety which was introduced in about 1890 to Switzerland as 'Amerikaner'. Fruits have sweet, softish flesh.

Barchard's Seedling.name: Barchard's Seedling
Barchard's Seedling.description: Raised in Putney, London by Mr Higgs, gardener to R. Barchard. It was introduced in 1856 by A. Dancer. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1873. Fruits are crisp with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Barkley Red Rome.name: Barkley Red Rome
Barkley Red Rome.description: A more highly coloured clone of Rome Beauty which was discovered in 1944 by G.L. Barkley, Manson, Washington, U.S.A. Introduced in 1953. Fruits are rather coarse-textured, juicy but with little flavour.

Barnack Beauty.name: Barnack Beauty
Barnack Beauty.description: Raised at Barnack, Northamptonshire in about 1840 and introduced in about 1870 by Brown of Stamford. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899 and a First Class Certificate in 1909. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Barnack Beauty Sport.name: Barnack Beauty Sport
Barnack Beauty Sport.description: A more highly coloured sport of Barnack Beauty which was discovered in 1944 by George Lamb, Swanley, Kent. Fruits, like Barnack Beauty, are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Barnack Orange.name: Barnack Orange
Barnack Orange.description: Raised in 1904 at Belvoir Castle, England by W. H. Divers. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured flesh, with a little juice and a good aromatic flavour.

Barnhill Pippin.name: Barnhill Pippin
Barnhill Pippin.description: Originated from Northern Ireland. Recorded in 1934. Fruits are crisp with a subacid flavour.

Baron Ward.name: Baron Ward
Baron Ward.description: Raised at Elton Manor, Nottingham by Samuel Bradley in 1850. First exhibited in 1859. Fruits have soft, white flesh with an astringent flavour.

Barre.name: Barre
Barre.description: An apple of French origin. Described in 1948. Fruits are sweet, hard and juicy with white flesh.

Barry.name: Barry
Barry.description: Raised at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, U.S.A. Selected in 1936 and introduced commercially in 1957. Fruits are firm and sweet with an aromatic flavour.

Bascombe Mystery.name: Bascombe Mystery
Bascombe Mystery.description: Dessert. First recorded in 1831. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Bastien.name: Bastien
Bastien.description: Raised at Treilliere, France. Recorded in 1948. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Batul-alma.name: Batul-alma
Batul-alma.description: Thought to have originated in the early 1800s from Transylvania (Romania). Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Baumann's Reinette.name: Baumann's Reinette
Baumann's Reinette.description: Thought to have been raised in Belgium by Van Mons. It was dedicated to Baumann Brothers of Bouxwiller, Belgium. Recorded in 1811. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1878. Fruits are rather coarse textured, fairly juicy, a little acid with a faint aromatic flavour.

Baunen.name: Baunen
Baunen.description: A sport of King of the Pippins. Fruits have firm, juicy, slightly acid flesh with a slight aromatic flavour.

Baxter.name: Baxter
Baxter.description: Arose near Brockville, Canada. It was known in about 1800. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a rather insipid flavour.

Baxter's Pearmain.name: Baxter's Pearmain
Baxter's Pearmain.description: Introduced by G.Lindley of Norfolk, England in 1821. Fruits are a little coarse textured, rather dry and slightly acid, with a pleasant Blenheim-like flavour.

Beacon.name: Beacon
Beacon.description: Raised in 1908 at the University of Minnesota Experimental Breeding Farm, Excelsior, USA. Introduced in 1936. Fruits have sweet, softish flesh.

Beauty of Bath.name: Beauty of Bath
Beauty of Bath.description: Originated at Bailbrook, Bath, Somerset and introduced by Cooling of Bath in about 1864. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1887. This variety was once the most important early commercial apple in the U.K. Fruits are soft, juicy, sweet and a little acid, with a distinctive flavour.

Beauty of Bedford.name: Beauty of Bedford
Beauty of Bedford.description: Raised before 1913 by Laxton Bros. Ltd., in Bedford. Fruits have firm, yellow flesh with a sweet flavour.

Beauty of Blackmoor.name: Beauty of Blackmoor
Beauty of Blackmoor.description: Raised in 1947 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol by G.T. Spinks. It was originally called 'Apollo'. Fruits are very similar to Beauty of Bath, but have better colour and quality.

Beauty of Hants.name: Beauty of Hants
Beauty of Hants.description: Raised in the garden of Mrs Eyre Crabbe at Basset, Southampton prior to 1850. It is said to be a seedling from Blenheim Orange open-pollinated. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour similar to Blenheim Orange.

Beauty of Kent.name: Beauty of Kent
Beauty of Kent.description: Thought to be of English origin. Introduced in about 1820. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1901. Fruits are coarse textured, juicy and subacid, with a faint pleasant flavour.

Beauty of Moray.name: Beauty of Moray
Beauty of Moray.description: Originated from Scotland. It was recorded in 1883. Fruits have crisp, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Beauty of Stoke.name: Beauty of Stoke
Beauty of Stoke.description: Raised at Rufford Abbey, Nottinghamshire by Mr Doe and introduced by Veitch. Recorded in 1889. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1890. Fruits have coarse, dry flesh with a subacid flavour.

Bedfordshire Foundling.name: Bedfordshire Foundling
Bedfordshire Foundling.description: Thought to have originated in England in about 1800. Fruits are firm, juicy, a little coarse-textured and subacid. Cooks well.

Bedminster Pippin.name: Bedminster Pippin
Bedminster Pippin.description: Thought to have probably originated in Gloucestershire, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1952. Fruits have soft, coarse textured flesh with an acid to subacid flavour.

Bedwyn Beauty.name: Bedwyn Beauty
Bedwyn Beauty.description: Raised near Marlborough, Wiltshire by Mr Stone in about 1890. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Beeley Pippin.name: Beeley Pippin
Beeley Pippin.description: Raised in about 1880 by Rev. C. Sculthorpe at Beeley, Derbyshire. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, somewhat tough flesh. Juicy and sweet with a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Bel-El.name: Bel-El
Bel-El.description: A more highly coloured sport of Elstar. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Belle-Fille Normande.name: Belle-Fille Normande
Belle-Fille Normande.description: Originated from Normandy, France. Known in the late 1700s. Cooks well.

Belle de Boskoop.name: Belle de Boskoop
Belle de Boskoop.description: Triploid. Thought to be a bud sport of Reinette de Montfort. Found by K.J.W. Ottolander, Boskoop, The Netherlands in 1856. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1897. Fruits have firm, coarse textured flesh with a pleasant, aromatic flavour. Also cooks well.

Belle de Longue.name: Belle de Longue
Belle de Longue.description: Originated with Lefant of Longue, France. And introduced by Leroy in 1889. First fruited in about 1884. Fruits have soft, white flesh with a rather insipid flavour.

Belle de Magny.name: Belle de Magny
Belle de Magny.description: This apple is of French origin. It was recorded in 1888. Fruits have fine, softish flesh with a rich and subacid flavour.

Belle des Buits.name: Belle des Buits
Belle des Buits.description: Originated on the property of M. Guyot de la Rochere, Vienne, France. It was known in the mid 1800s. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh.

Belle-Fleur de France.name: Belle-Fleur de France
Belle-Fleur de France.description: Thought to be of French origin. Recorded in 1954. Fruits have firm, creamy white, tinged green flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Bellefleur Krasny.name: Bellefleur Krasny
Bellefleur Krasny.description: This apple is of Russian origin. It was raised in 1914. Fruits have sweet, firm but rather dry flesh.

Bellida.name: Bellida
Bellida.description: Raised at IVT, Wageningen, Netherlands. Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1994. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Belvoir Seedling.name: Belvoir Seedling
Belvoir Seedling.description: Raised by W.H. Divers, probably at Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1935. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Ben's Red.name: Ben's Red
Ben's Red.description: Raised by Benjamin Roberts at Trannack, Cornwall, England in about 1830. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits have firm, dry, somewhat coarse textured flesh with a sweet, pleasant flavour.

Benenden Early.name: Benenden Early
Benenden Early.description: Raised in about 1945 at Southampton by J.J. Gibbons, and introduced in 1952 by Stuart Low Ltd., Benenden, Kent. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Benoni.name: Benoni
Benoni.description: Raised in about 1830 on the farm of Mr Mason Richards, Dedham, Massachusetts, U.S.A. Introduced to England by Rivers of Sawbridgeworth. Fruits have tender, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant, moderately aromatic flavour.

Beregi Sovari.name: Beregi Sovari
Beregi Sovari.description: Believed to be a sport of Nemes Sovari Alma. This apple is of Hungarian origin. It was recorded in 1900. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet flavour.

Berna.name: Berna
Berna.description: Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1993 from Belgium.

Berner Rosen.name: Berner Rosen
Berner Rosen.description: Discovered by nurseryman Daepp of Oppligen, Switzerland. First fruited in 1888. Fruits have fine, greenish white tinged red flesh with a subacid, aromatic flavour.

Bess Pool.name: Bess Pool
Bess Pool.description: Discovered in a wood in Nottinghamshire by Bess Pool. It was first recorded in 1824 and introduced by nurseryman, Pearson, of Chilwell, Nottinghamshire. This apple flowers very late and is therefore useful in areas prone to frost. Fruits have rather dry, slightly coarse-textured flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Bessemyanka Michurina.name: Bessemyanka Michurina
Bessemyanka Michurina.description: Raised in 1912 by I.V. Michurin at Michurinsk, Russia. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Betsey.name: Betsey
Betsey.description: This variety is of UK origin. It was recorded in 1842. Fruits have fine, greenish yellow flesh with a sweet flavour.

Betty Geeson.name: Betty Geeson
Betty Geeson.description: Thought to have originated from Worcestershire, England. It was introduced in 1854. Fruits have firm, tender flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Beverly Hills.name: Beverly Hills
Beverly Hills.description: Raised in 1939 by Dr W.H. Chandler, University of California, USA. Introduced in 1945. Fruits have soft, tender white flesh with a sweet subacid, scented flavour.

Bielaar.name: Bielaar
Bielaar.description: A darker red sport of Belle de Boskoop. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Biesterfelder Renette.name: Biesterfelder Renette
Biesterfelder Renette.description: Originated at Castle of Biesterfelder, Lippe, Germany. Introduced in 1905. Fruits have fairly coarse, soft creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Biggs's Nonsuch.name: Biggs's Nonsuch
Biggs's Nonsuch.description: Raised by Mr A. Biggs, gardener to Isaac Swainson, Twickenham, Middlesex. Fruits have yellow, tender, juicy flesh.

Birgit Bonnier.name: Birgit Bonnier
Birgit Bonnier.description: Raised in Sweden and named after the wife of publisher Albert Bonnier. Fruits have a pleasant flavour. This variety has some resistance to scab and mildew.

Bismarck.name: Bismarck
Bismarck.description: This apple was named after Prince Bismarck the German Chancellor. Its origin is variously reported as Bismarck, Tasmania; Carisbrooke, Australia; and Canterbury, New Zealand. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1887.Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with an acid flavour. Cooks well.

Black Ben Davis.name: Black Ben Davis
Black Ben Davis.description: A coloured sport of Ben Davis. It arose in about 1880 on the farm of M. Black, Washington County, Arkansas, USA. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh with little flavour.

Black McIntosh.name: Black McIntosh
Black McIntosh.description: An earlier colouring sport of McIntosh. Selected in 1928 by H. Simpson, Oliver, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in 1930. Fruits have melting, juicy flesh with a vinous flavour.

Black Mickey.name: Black Mickey
Black Mickey.description: A sport of McIntosh, having a more solid flush. It was found in 1929 by I.C.Rogers in Dansville, New York, USA. Introduced in about 1930. Fruits have melting, juicy flesh with a vinous flavour.

Blackjon.name: Blackjon
Blackjon.description: A coloured sport of Jonathan. Originally found in Tom Slack Orchard, Wenatchee, Washington, U.S.A. by C & O Nursery. It was selected in about 1927 and introduced in 1931. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Blaxtayman.name: Blaxtayman
Blaxtayman.description: A sport of Stayman Winesap having a more even and solid flush. It was discovered in 1926 by J.H. Dickey in Wenatchee, Washington, USA and introduced in 1930 by C & O Nursery, Washington. Fruits have softish flesh with a sweet flavour.

Blaze.name: Blaze
Blaze.description: Raised in 1939 at Illinois Agricultural Experiment Station, Urbana, USA and introduced in 1958. Fruits are crisp and sweet.

Blenheim Orange.name: Blenheim Orange
Blenheim Orange.description: Triploid. Discovered by Mr Kempster at Woodstock near Blenheim, Oxfordshire, England in about 1740. Distributed in about 1818. It received the Banksian medal from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1822. Fruits have creamy white, somewhat coarse-textured and rather dry flesh with a rich, characteristic aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

Bloody Butcher.name: Bloody Butcher
Bloody Butcher.description: Originated from Ireland. It was recorded in 1951. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid flavour.

Bloody Ploughman.name: Bloody Ploughman
Bloody Ploughman.description: Originated at Carse of Gowrie, Scotland. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have crisp, tender flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Blue Pearmain.name: Blue Pearmain
Blue Pearmain.description: Thought to have originated in U.S.A. It was known in the early 1800s. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1893 and a First Class Certificate in 1896. Fruits have somewhat dry, rather soft, coarse-textured flesh with a sweet, pleasant aromatic flavour.

Blushing Golden.name: Blushing Golden
Blushing Golden.description: Discovered by R. Griffith, Cobden, Illinois, USA. Introduced in 1968 by Stark Bros. Fruits have firm, yellow, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Bodikers Gold-Reinette.name: Bodikers Gold-Reinette
Bodikers Gold-Reinette.description: Raised by Bodiker, Meppen, Hannover, Germany. Recorded in 1875. Fruits have fine, tender white flesh with a sweet, vinous almost spicy flavour.

Bodil Neergaard.name: Bodil Neergaard
Bodil Neergaard.description: Discovered in about 1850 by nurseryman Anderson at Flintinge, Lolland, Denmark. Fruits have a sweet, aromatic/vinous flavour.

Bohemia.name: Bohemia
Bohemia.description: A coloured sport of Rubin. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Bohnapfel.name: Bohnapfel
Bohnapfel.description: Triploid. Originated in the late 1700s in the Rhineland, Germany. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid to slightly sweet flavour.

Boiken.name: Boiken
Boiken.description: Raised in Bremen, Germany and named after Dikewarden Boike. Known since 1828. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy, acid flesh with very little flavour.

Bondon.name: Bondon
Bondon.description: Originated from France. Recorded in 1948. Fruits have soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Bonne Hotture.name: Bonne Hotture
Bonne Hotture.description: Thought to have originated at Maine-et-Loire, France. Recorded in 1867. Fruits have crisp, sweet flesh.

Bonnet Carre.name: Bonnet Carre
Bonnet Carre.description: Originated from France. Recorded in 1948. Fruits are sweet with a perfumed flavour.

Bosbury Pippin.name: Bosbury Pippin
Bosbury Pippin.description: Thought to have originated in the West of England. Recorded in 1920. Fruits have firm, pale yellow flesh with a sweet flavour.

Botden.name: Botden
Botden.description: A dark red sport of Belle de Boskoop. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, sweet and acid flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Bountiful.name: Bountiful
Bountiful.description: Raised in 1964 at East Malling Research Station. It is resistant to apple mildew. When cooked, Bountiful has a delicious flavour.

Bouquepreuve.name: Bouquepreuve
Bouquepreuve.description: Originated from the Mediterranean region of France. Recorded in 1884. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet flavour.

Bovarde.name: Bovarde
Bovarde.description: Originated from Switzerland. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have tender, rather dry flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Bow Hill Pippin.name: Bow Hill Pippin
Bow Hill Pippin.description: Raised by A.S.White, Bow Hill, Maidstone, Kent and introduced in about 1893 by G. Bunyard Ltd., Maidstone. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1893. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Brabant Bellefleur.name: Brabant Bellefleur
Brabant Bellefleur.description: Thought to be of either Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to notice in the late 1700s. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1901. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Braddick Nonpareil.name: Braddick Nonpareil
Braddick Nonpareil.description: Raised by John Braddick at Thames Ditton, Surrey. First exhibited in 1818. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Braeburn.name: Braeburn
Braeburn.description: Discovered on the property of O.Moran, Waiwhero, Upper Moutere, New Zealand and was first grown commercially by William Bros. at Braeburn orchard, Upper Moutere in 1952. I Fruits have crisp, firm flesh with a perfumed flavour, although fruits usually fail to mature fully in the U.K.

Braintree Seedling.name: Braintree Seedling
Braintree Seedling.description: Raised in 1930 by Mrs Humphreys, Braintree, Essex. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Bramley's Seedling.name: Bramley's Seedling
Bramley's Seedling.description: Triploid. Raised by Mary Ann Brailsford, Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England between 1809 and 1813 and introduced in 1865 by nurseryman H. Merryweather. First exhibited in 1876. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1893. The most popular cooking apple grown in the UK.

Bramshott Rectory.name: Bramshott Rectory
Bramshott Rectory.description: Thought to have originated in the garden of Bramshott Rectory, Liphook, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in about 1938. Fruits have crisp, rather coarse flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Breedon Pippin.name: Breedon Pippin
Breedon Pippin.description: Raised in about 1801 by Rev. J. Symonds Breedon, Pangbourne, Berkshire from seed found in cider pommace. Fruits have fairly tender flesh with a subacid vinous flavour.

Breitling.name: Breitling
Breitling.description: Thought to be of German origin. It was introduced in about 1879 to England by Thomas Rivers. Fruits are very sweet.

Brenchley Pippin.name: Brenchley Pippin
Brenchley Pippin.description: Raised in Brenchley, Kent. Recorded in 1884. Fruits have tender flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Bridgewater Pippin (of Cheal).name: Bridgewater Pippin (of Cheal)
Bridgewater Pippin (of Cheal).description: Thought to have probably originated in Bridgewater, Somerset. Recorded in 1665. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid flavour.

Britemac.name: Britemac
Britemac.description: Raised in 1934 by Prof. M.A. Blake at New Jersey Agricultural Experiment Station, U.S.A. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a flavour similar to McIntosh.

Broad-Eyed Pippin (of Bultitude).name: Broad-Eyed Pippin (of Bultitude)
Broad-Eyed Pippin (of Bultitude).description: Raised in England. It was recorded in the late 1600s. Fruits have moderately firm, coarse-textured flesh and are juicy and acid.

Brookes's.name: Brookes's
Brookes's.description: Originated from Shropshire, England. It was recorded in 1820. Fruits have a sweet, rich, aromatic flavour.

Brown Kenting.name: Brown Kenting
Brown Kenting.description: An apple of UK origin. Recorded in 1831. Fruits have sweet, firm flesh.

Brown's Seedling.name: Brown's Seedling
Brown's Seedling.description: Raised before 1874 by Brown, a nurseryman at Stamford, Lincolnshire. Fruits have softish flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Brownlees' Russet.name: Brownlees' Russet
Brownlees' Russet.description: Raised in England and introduced by William Brownlees of Hemel Hempstead in about 1848. Fruits are juicy and somewhat acid, with a pleasant nutty flavour.

Burchardt's Reinette.name: Burchardt's Reinette
Burchardt's Reinette.description: Raised by Von Hartwiss, Director of the Royal Garden at Nikita, Crimea, Russia. Recorded in 1863. Fruits have crisp, white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Burgundy.name: Burgundy
Burgundy.description: Raised at the New York State Agricultural Experimental Station, Geneva, U.S.A. Introduced in 1974. Fruits have sweet, crisp flesh which is often heavily stained with pink.

Burn's Seedling.name: Burn's Seedling
Burn's Seedling.description: Raised by Henry Burn, near Marlborough, Wiltshire. Recorded in 1831. Fruits have very sweet, coarse flesh.

Burr Knot.name: Burr Knot
Burr Knot.description: An apple of UK origin. First recorded in 1818. The fruits are of no particular merit but the trees produce numerous burrs, and roots freely from cuttings. Fruits have soft, coarse-textured rather dry flesh.

Bushey Grove.name: Bushey Grove
Bushey Grove.description: Raised in 1897 by Mrs Good, Bushey Grove, Hertfordshire and introduced in about 1926 by G.W. King, Sidcup, Kent. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1922. This variety is very prone to apple scab. Fruits have very soft, coarse-textured, juicy flesh which is rather acid. Cooks well.

Byeloborodovka.name: Byeloborodovka
Byeloborodovka.description: An apple of Russian origin. Recorded in 1842. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Byfleet Seedling.name: Byfleet Seedling
Byfleet Seedling.description: Raised in 1915 by George Carpenter at West Hall, Byfleet, Surrey. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a slightly acid, aromatic flavour. Cooks very well.

Byford Wonder.name: Byford Wonder
Byford Wonder.description: An apple of UK origin. Recorded in 1893. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1893. Fruits have coarse, tender flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Cacanska Pozna.name: Cacanska Pozna
Cacanska Pozna.description: Raised in Yugoslavia at the Institut za Vocarstvo, Cacak, Srbija. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1975. Fruits have fairly soft flesh with a strong flavour.

Cagarlaou.name: Cagarlaou
Cagarlaou.description: Originated from Lozere, France. Described in 1947. Fruits have a sweet, perfumed flavour.

Calville Blanc d'Hiver.name: Calville Blanc d'Hiver
Calville Blanc d'Hiver.description: Raised in Europe, probably France or Germany. Recorded in 1598. Fruits have a rather soft, fine-textured juicy flesh with a rich, sweet, aromatic flavour. Fruits fail to ripen fully in the UK.

Calville d'Aout.name: Calville d'Aout
Calville d'Aout.description: A chance seedling originating in 1925 from France. Fruits have rather sharp white flesh. Cooks well.

Calville d'Oullins.name: Calville d'Oullins
Calville d'Oullins.description: Discovered by nurseryman A. Jaboulay, Oullins, Lyon, France in about 1850. Fruits have crisp, acid flesh.

Calville d'Ulzen.name: Calville d'Ulzen
Calville d'Ulzen.description: Thought to be of German origin although this particular variety was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from France. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Calville de Maussion.name: Calville de Maussion
Calville de Maussion.description: Originated from France. Recorded in 1870. Fruits have a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Calville de Saint-Sauveur.name: Calville de Saint-Sauveur
Calville de Saint-Sauveur.description: Originated in about 1839 as a chance seedling found on the property of M. Despreaux, Saint-Sauveur, Oise, France. Introduced by nurseryman Jamin. Cooks well.

Calville des Femmes.name: Calville des Femmes
Calville des Femmes.description: Found in 1850 in the garden of Comice Horticole, Angers, France. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Calville Duquesne.name: Calville Duquesne
Calville Duquesne.description: Raised at Mons-Pont-Canal, Belgium by nurseryman Duquesne. It was known to be in existence in 1895. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Calville Rouge d'Automne (Barnes).name: Calville Rouge d'Automne (Barnes)
Calville Rouge d'Automne (Barnes).description: Thought to have originated in Auvergne, France. First recorded in 1670. Fruits have tender, coarse flesh with a subacid perfumed flavour. Flesh is sometimes tinged red under the skin.

Calville Rouge d'Hiver.name: Calville Rouge d'Hiver
Calville Rouge d'Hiver.description: Thought to have possibly originated in Brittany, France. Recorded in about 1600. Fruits have rather soft, moderately juicy flesh with a somewhat sweet flavour.

Calville Rouge du Mont d'Or.name: Calville Rouge du Mont d'Or
Calville Rouge du Mont d'Or.description: Found at Champagne-au-Mont-d'Or, France and propagated by horticulturist M. Laperriere. Described in 1934. Fruits have soft, rather coarse flesh with a sweet subacid to acid flavour.

Cambusnethan Pippin.name: Cambusnethan Pippin
Cambusnethan Pippin.description: Raised in about 1750 either by Paton the gardener at Cambusnethan House, Stirlingshire, Scotland or at the Cambusnethan Monastery. Fruits have fine textured flesh with little juice and a sweet, faintly perfumed flavour.

Camelot.name: Camelot
Camelot.description: Originated from Somerset, England. Exhibited in 1934. Fruits have very acid, astringent flesh.

Campanino.name: Campanino
Campanino.description: Thought to have originated at Modena, Italy. Described in 1950. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a rather acid flavour.

Canada Blanc de la Creuse.name: Canada Blanc de la Creuse
Canada Blanc de la Creuse.description: Thought to have arisen at Creuse, France. Described in 1947. Fruits have softish flesh with an insipid flavour.

Captain Kidd.name: Captain Kidd
Captain Kidd.description: A more highly coloured sport of Kidd's Orange Red. Originated in 1962 in the orchard of Mr Robin Osborne at Twyford, Hawkes Bay, New Zealand. Introduced in 1969. Fruits are crisp, sweet and juicy with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Caravel.name: Caravel
Caravel.description: Raised at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada and introduced in 1964. A biennial cropper. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a rather insipid flavour.

Carlisle Codlin (of Bultitude).name: Carlisle Codlin (of Bultitude)
Carlisle Codlin (of Bultitude).description: Thought to have arisen from Carlisle, England. Known before 1830. Fruits have rather soft, a little coarse-textured juicy flesh which is slightly acid.

Carlton.name: Carlton
Carlton.description: Raised in 1912 by Richard Wellington at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Caroli d'Italie.name: Caroli d'Italie
Caroli d'Italie.description: Originated in Piedmont, Italy. It was described in 1876 but thought to be much older. Fruits have fine, tender white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Caroline.name: Caroline
Caroline.description: Originated in Lord Suffield's garden, Blickling, Norfolk. It was known to already be fruiting in 1822. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Caroline Hopkins.name: Caroline Hopkins
Caroline Hopkins.description: Found growing wild at Worcester, Cape of Good Hope, South Africa. It was sent to the National Fruit Trials in 1956. Fruits have crisp, acid, slightly astringent flesh. This variety is said to root from cuttings and in South Africa is said to bloom and fruit twice in a year.

Carrey.name: Carrey
Carrey.description: Originated at Basses Pyrenees, France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Carswell's Honeydew.name: Carswell's Honeydew
Carswell's Honeydew.description: Raised in 1939 by J.W. Carswell at Ashtead, Surrey. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a sweet, almost honeyed flavour.

Carswell's Orange.name: Carswell's Orange
Carswell's Orange.description: Raised in 1938 by Mr J.W. Carswell at Ashtead, Surrey. Fruits are rather coarse-textured and juicy with a pleasant, aromatic flavour.

Cartaut.name: Cartaut
Cartaut.description: Originated at Puy de Dome, France. Described in 1934. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh.

Carter's Blue.name: Carter's Blue
Carter's Blue.description: Originated at Mount Meigs, near Montgomery, Alabama, U.S.A. Described in 1869. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a rich, sweet subacid, aromatic flavour.

Carter's Pearmain.name: Carter's Pearmain
Carter's Pearmain.description: Thought to be of UK origin. Exhibited in 1934. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Case Wealthy.name: Case Wealthy
Case Wealthy.description: A sport of Wealthy having a darker red flush. It was discovered in 1933 in Sodus, New York, USA by James G. Case. Introduced in 1940. Fruits have rather soft, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet, faint vinous flavour.

Castle Major.name: Castle Major
Castle Major.description: Originated in Kent. Described in 1875. Fruits have soft flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Catshead.name: Catshead
Catshead.description: Originated in England and known in the 1600s. A distinctly angular and somewhat ugly apple. Fruits are coarse-textured and rather dry with a subacid flavour.

Caudal Market.name: Caudal Market
Caudal Market.description: It was raised by F.W. Wastie at Eynsham, Oxford. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1953. Fruits have crisp, coarse flesh with an acid flavour.

Ceeval.name: Ceeval
Ceeval.description: A red sport of Alkmene. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Cellini.name: Cellini
Cellini.description: Raised by Leonard Phillips, a nurseryman at Vauxhall, London. Introduced in about 1828. Fruits have rather soft, juicy, coarse-textured flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Celt.name: Celt
Celt.description: Raised in 1943 by David Harris at Melksham, Wiltshire. Fruits have fine, sweet flesh.

Chad's Favourite.name: Chad's Favourite
Chad's Favourite.description: Raised by M.B. Crane at the John Innes Horticultural Institute, Merton, London. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1939 and named in 1952. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a sweet subacid, aromatic flavour.

Champ-Gaillard.name: Champ-Gaillard
Champ-Gaillard.description: Originated in Basses-Alpes, France. Described in 1868. Fruits have a sweet-subacid aromatic flavour.

Channel Beauty.name: Channel Beauty
Channel Beauty.description: Raised by C.H. Evans, Swansea, Wales. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1922. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid almost bitter flavour.

Chantecler.name: Chantecler
Chantecler.description: Raised in 1958 at INRA, Angers, France. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a rich, sweetish flavour.

Chantegrise.name: Chantegrise
Chantegrise.description: Originates from France. A russetted clone of Chantecler. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a rich, sweetish flavour.

Charden.name: Charden
Charden.description: Raised in France in 1959. Fruits are fairly crisp and juicy with a sweet flavour.

Charles Eyre.name: Charles Eyre
Charles Eyre.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Welford Park, Newbury, Berkshire. Introduced by Pope Brothers of Wokingham in about 1911. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1911. Fruits are soft, coarse-textured, rather dry and acid.

Charles Ross.name: Charles Ross
Charles Ross.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Welford Park Gardens, Newbury, Berkshire. It was first exhibited in 1890 as Thomas Andrew Knight but renamed Charles Ross at the request of his employer, Captain Carstairs in 1899. Received an Award of Merit and a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits are rather coarse-textured, juicy and sweet with a moderate flavour.

Charlotte.name: Charlotte
Charlotte.description: Raised in 1975 and selected in 1982 at the Institute of Horticultural Research, East Malling, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits are crisp, tart and sweet. Cooks well, requiring little sugar.

Chataignier.name: Chataignier
Chataignier.description: Originated from Normandy, France. It was known in 1200. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a fairly sweet, subacid flavour.

Chaux.name: Chaux
Chaux.description: It is thought to have probably originated in Haute Vienne, France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm flesh with a somewhat subacid, aromatic flavour.

Chaxhill Red.name: Chaxhill Red
Chaxhill Red.description: Raised by Mr Bennett of Chaxhill, Westbury-on-Severn. Recorded in 1873. Received a First Class Certificate for cider in 1873 at Gloucester. Fruits have tender flesh with a mild subacid flavour.

Cheddar Cross.name: Cheddar Cross
Cheddar Cross.description: Raised in 1916 by G.T.Spinks at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. Introduced in 1949. Fruits have firm, fine-textured flesh which is somewhat acid with little flavour.

Chehalis.name: Chehalis
Chehalis.description: Discovered in 1955 by Lloyd Lonborg of Oakville, Washington, U.S.A. near to the Chehalis river. Fruits are sweet and juicy with a melting flesh.

Chelmsford Wonder.name: Chelmsford Wonder
Chelmsford Wonder.description: Raised near Chelmsford, Essex in about 1870 and introduced in 1890 by Saltmarsh. Received an Award of Merit and a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1891. Fruits have firm, fine-textured flesh which is juicy and subacid.

Chenango Strawberry.name: Chenango Strawberry
Chenango Strawberry.description: Originated either in Lebanon, Madison County, New York or brought into Chenango County from Connecticut. It has been known since about 1850. Fruits have tender, fairly firm flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Cherry Cox.name: Cherry Cox
Cherry Cox.description: A sport of Cox's Orange Pippin having a darker red skin. Discovered by Mr Roed in Kjer's Orchard, Linved, Hjallese, Denmark in about 1942 and introduced to England in 1951 by High Weald Nurseries, Crowborough, Sussex. Fruits, like Cox's Orange Pippin, have a rich aromatic flavour.

Chieftain.name: Chieftain
Chieftain.description: Raised in 1917 by S.A. Beach at Iowa Experimental Station, Ames, U.S.A and introduced in 1967. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Chips.name: Chips
Chips.description: Raised in about 1867 by Mr Sturgeon of Kent. Fruits have a distinct Cox-like flavour.

Chivers Delight.name: Chivers Delight
Chivers Delight.description: Raised by John Chivers Farms Ltd., at Histon, Cambridgeshire in 1936. It is rather susceptible to apple canker. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a pleasant flavour.

Chorister Boy.name: Chorister Boy
Chorister Boy.description: Found in a garden in Wiltshire. First recorded in 1890. Introduced by Keynes, Williams & Co., Salisbury. Fruits are soft, juicy and slightly acid with very little flavour.

Christmas Pearmain.name: Christmas Pearmain
Christmas Pearmain.description: Raised by Mr Manser and first recorded in 1893. It was introduced by G. Bunyard & Co., Maidstone, Kent. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Chusenrainer.name: Chusenrainer
Chusenrainer.description: Found in about 1852 by Joh. Waller, growing wild in Chusenrain - Sempach, Switzerland. It was named in 1891 by R. Stalder of Meggen. Fruits have soft flesh with an insipid flavour.

Cinq Cotes.name: Cinq Cotes
Cinq Cotes.description: Originated from France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Cissy.name: Cissy
Cissy.description: Raised between 1750 and 1800 by Mr Tamplin or Tampling of Malpas, Newport, Monmouthshire and distributed by his sister Cissy. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1902 as Tamplin. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Citron d'Hiver (Swiss).name: Citron d'Hiver (Swiss)
Citron d'Hiver (Swiss).description: Originated from Valais, Switzerland. Described in 1925. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Clark's Seedling.name: Clark's Seedling
Clark's Seedling.description: Thought to have originated in the UK. Recorded in 1936. Fruits have soft, coarse, creamy yellow flesh with a subacid flavour.

Clarke's Royal.name: Clarke's Royal
Clarke's Royal.description: A full red coloured clone of Cox's Orange Pippin. Originally selected in 1984 by Mr P. Clarke. Trees are more precocious than Cox and also less vigorous. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Claygate Pearmain.name: Claygate Pearmain
Claygate Pearmain.description: Discovered by John Braddick at Claygate, Surrey and exhibited to the Horticultural Society in 1821. It received an Award of Merit in 1901 and a First Class Certificate in 1921 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, rather coarse textured juicy flesh with a rich aromatic flavour.

Clear Gold.name: Clear Gold
Clear Gold.description: A sport of Golden Delicious. Originated in Worley's Nursery, York Springs, PA, U.S.A. Fruits have fairly crisp, juicy flesh with a good flavour.

Clearheart.name: Clearheart
Clearheart.description: Originated in Ireland. Described in 1951. Fruits have firm flesh with an acid flavour.

Cleeve.name: Cleeve
Cleeve.description: Known to have been raised before 1930 by Sir Stanley Machin, from seed of an imported Canadian apple at Cleeve, Weybridge, Surrey. Fruits are crisp with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Climax.name: Climax
Climax.description: Acquired by the National Fruit Trials in 1921 from M. B. Crane, John Innes Institute, Merton, London. Fruits have very soft, mealy flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Clivia.name: Clivia
Clivia.description: Raised by Prof. M. Schmidt at the Agricultural Research Station, Munchenberg, Brandenburg, Germany. Introduced in 1961. Fruits have a flavour very like Cox's Orange Pippin.

Cloden.name: Cloden
Cloden.description: Raised at the Station de Recherches d'Arboriculture Fruitiere, Angers, France. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Clopton Red.name: Clopton Red
Clopton Red.description: Raised in 1946 by Justin Brooke at Clopton Hall, Wickhambrook, Suffolk and introduced in 1961. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, rich flavour.

Close.name: Close
Close.description: Triploid. Raised by C.S. Close at Arlington, Virginia, U.S.A. It was selected in about 1925 and introduced in 1938. Fruits have soft flesh with little juice and a sweet but poor flavour.

Cludius Herbstapfel.name: Cludius Herbstapfel
Cludius Herbstapfel.description: Raised by Supt. Cludius of Hildesheim, Hannover, Germany. It was recorded in the 1850s. Fruits have a sweet, vinous flavour.

Cockle Pippin.name: Cockle Pippin
Cockle Pippin.description: Raised in about 1800 by Mr Cockle at Godstone, Surrey. Fruits have firm, fine-textured somewhat dry flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Cockpit.name: Cockpit
Cockpit.description: Originated in Yorkshire. First recorded in 1831. Fruits have coarse flesh with a slightly acid, almost astringent flavour.

Coeur de Boeuf.name: Coeur de Boeuf
Coeur de Boeuf.description: An apple of French origin. Known since 1200s. Fruits have soft, greenish veined pink flesh with a sweet subacid, aromatic flavour.

Cola.name: Cola
Cola.description: An Italian variety known since the early 1900s. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Cola Gelata.name: Cola Gelata
Cola Gelata.description: Originated in the early 1900s in the Giarrita-Petralia region of Italy. Fruits have slightly dry flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Colapuy.name: Colapuy
Colapuy.description: Said to have been brought to France from the Crimea by a soldier called Nicolas Puy in the mid 1800s. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh with a distinctive flavour.

Collogget Pippin.name: Collogget Pippin
Collogget Pippin.description: Originated in Cornwall, England. First described in 1920. Fruits have firm, yellow flesh with an acid flavour.

Colonel Vaughan.name: Colonel Vaughan
Colonel Vaughan.description: Originated in Kent. It was known in the late 1600s. Fruits have firm, white, sometimes stained red flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Colonel Yate.name: Colonel Yate
Colonel Yate.description: Raised in 1905 probably by W.H. Divers, Surbiton, Surrey. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Comrade.name: Comrade
Comrade.description: Thought to have been raised by George Carpenter, Byfleet, Surrey, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1932. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Cooper's Seedling.name: Cooper's Seedling
Cooper's Seedling.description: Originated from Kent. Known to have been in existence in 1946. Fruits have rather soft flesh.

Cornish Aromatic.name: Cornish Aromatic
Cornish Aromatic.description: Originally found growing in Cornwall. It was brought to notice in 1813 but thought to be many centuries old. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Cornish Gilliflower.name: Cornish Gilliflower
Cornish Gilliflower.description: Found in a cottage garden near Truro, Cornwall. It was introduced by Sir Christopher Hawkins in 1813. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with a sweet and rich aromatic flavour.

Cornish Pine.name: Cornish Pine
Cornish Pine.description: Thought to be a seedling of Cornish Gilliflower. It was raised at Exminster, Devon. First described in 1920. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Coronation.name: Coronation
Coronation.description: Raised at Buxted Park, Sussex by H.C. Princep and introduced by Pyne, Topsham, Devon. First recorded in 1902. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1902 as Edward's Coronation. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Corry's Wonder.name: Corry's Wonder
Corry's Wonder.description: Raised in 1917 at Eynsham, Oxford by E. Corry Hanks. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet but acid flavour.

Cortland.name: Cortland
Cortland.description: Raised in 1898 by S.A. Beach at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Fruits have moderately juicy, slightly coarse-textured flesh with a sweet, refreshing flavour. Skin is tough.

Cottenham Seedling.name: Cottenham Seedling
Cottenham Seedling.description: Raised by Robert Norman at Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England and introduced by H.J. Gautrey. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1924. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, juicy flesh which is distinctly acid.

Coul Blush.name: Coul Blush
Coul Blush.description: Raised by Sir George Mackenzie, Coul, Ross-shire, Scotland. It first fruited in 1827. Fruits have fine, soft flesh which is slightly sweet and slightly subacid.

Court of Wick.name: Court of Wick
Court of Wick.description: Originated at Court of Wick, Yatton, Somerset and introduced in 1790 by Wood of Huntingdon. Fruits are crisp with a rich and subacid flavour.

Court Pendu Plat.name: Court Pendu Plat
Court Pendu Plat.description: This variety originated in Europe. It was first described in about 1613 but believed to be much older than this. It was also called 'Wise Apple' because it flowers late and escapes spring frost damage. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh which is sweet with a pleasant, slightly aromatic flavour.

Courtagold.name: Courtagold
Courtagold.description: A spur type clone of Golden Delicious. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Cox La Vera.name: Cox La Vera
Cox La Vera.description: A clone of Cox's Orange Pippin.

Cox's Early Export.name: Cox's Early Export
Cox's Early Export.description: Raised by Ivorys Ltd., at Rangiora, New Zealand. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950. Fruits are crisp with a subacid flavour.

Cox Rouge des Flandres.name: Cox Rouge des Flandres
Cox Rouge des Flandres.description: A more highly coloured sport of Cox's Orange Pippin. Discovered in the late 40's early 50's by Dr G. Heem at the Centre Fruitier des Flandres, Herzeele, near Dunkerque, France. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a rich, aromatic, nutty flavour.

Cox's Orange Pippin.name: Cox's Orange Pippin
Cox's Orange Pippin.description: Raised in about 1825 by Richard Cox at Colnbrook Lawn, Slough, Buckinghamshire and introduced by Charles Turner in about 1850. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1962. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a rich, aromatic, nutty flavour.

Cox's Orange Pippin Red Sport (Potter).name: Cox's Orange Pippin Red Sport (Potter)
Cox's Orange Pippin Red Sport (Potter).description: A red sport of Cox's Orange Pippin. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1957. Originated with Mr C.A. Potter, Howletts Farm, Molash, Canterbury, Kent. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Cox's Orange Pippin Spur Type Alof.name: Cox's Orange Pippin Spur Type Alof
Cox's Orange Pippin Spur Type Alof.accession name: Cox's Orange Pippin spur type (Alof M27)

Cox's Pomona.name: Cox's Pomona
Cox's Pomona.description: Believed to be a sister seedling of Cox's Orange Pippin. It was raised in about 1825 by Richard Cox at Colnbrook Lawn, Slough, Buckinghamshire and introduced by Smale, Colnbrook Nursery, Slough. Fruits have softish, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet, subacid, fine flavour.

Cravert.name: Cravert
Cravert.description: A chance seedling discovered in about 1870 or earlier, either in a field of the Depigny family or in the forest of Allogny, France. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet flavour.

Cravert Rouge.name: Cravert Rouge
Cravert Rouge.description: A more highly coloured sport of Cravert. Originated in Cher, France. Fruits have a sweet subacid flavour.

Crawley Beauty.name: Crawley Beauty
Crawley Beauty.description: Found in a cottage garden in Crawley, Sussex in about 1870 and introduced in 1906 by nurserymen J. Cheal & Sons of Crawley. It appears to be identical with French variety Novelle France. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912. Fruits have slightly coarse-textured, rather dry flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Crawley Reinette.name: Crawley Reinette
Crawley Reinette.description: Introduced by J. Cheal & Sons, Crawley, Sussex. Recorded in 1902. Fruits have soft flesh with an acid to subacid flavour.

Crimson Beauty (Canada).name: Crimson Beauty (Canada)
Crimson Beauty (Canada).description: Originated in about 1880 in New Brunswick, Canada. Fruits have rather soft flesh with a subacid to acid flavour.

Crimson Beauty of Bath.name: Crimson Beauty of Bath
Crimson Beauty of Bath.description: A more highly coloured clone of Beauty of Bath. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a distinctive slightly acid flavour.

Crimson Bramley.name: Crimson Bramley
Crimson Bramley.description: A more highly coloured sport of Bramley's Seedling. Originated in Southwell, Nottinghamshire. Catalogued in 1913. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with an acid flavour. Cooks well.

Crimson Cox.name: Crimson Cox
Crimson Cox.description: A crimson coloured clone of Cox's Orange Pippin. Discovered in about 1913 by John Harris of Haynes Farm, Carey, Herefordshire. Introduced in 1928. Fruit flavour is reputed to be inferior to Cox's Orange Pippin.

Crimson King.name: Crimson King
Crimson King.description: Exhibited from Somerset in 1934. First recorded in 1895. Triploid. The large fruits are sometimes used for cooking as well as for cider production. Produces a vintage, acidic juice with no astringency and a light, fruity, good quality cider.

Crimson Newton.name: Crimson Newton
Crimson Newton.description: A more highly coloured sport of Newton Wonder being almost entirely flushed dull dark crimson. Originated in 1921 with C.H. Dicker, Holwell Bury Fruit Farm, Hertfordshire. Fruits cook very well.

Crimson Peasgood.name: Crimson Peasgood
Crimson Peasgood.description: A more highly coloured sport of Peasgood's Nonsuch. It was planted at the National Fruit Trials in 1931. Fruits cook well.

Crimson Queening.name: Crimson Queening
Crimson Queening.description: First recorded in 1831 but thought to probably be much older. Fruits have soft, dryish flesh which soon becomes mealy. Moderate flavour.

Crimson Spy.name: Crimson Spy
Crimson Spy.description: Thought to be a bud mutation of Northern Spy having an almost solid crimson skin. Originated in Ontario, Canada and introduced in 1931. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Crimson Superb.name: Crimson Superb
Crimson Superb.description: A more highly coloured sport of Laxton's Superb. It originated with J. Anderson, School House, Hutton Cranswick, Driffield, Yorkshire. First exhibited in 1950. Fruits have firm, fine-textured juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Criterion.name: Criterion
Criterion.description: Discovered in 1968 by Francis Cites in his Parker Heights orchard, near Wapato, Washington, USA. Fruits are firm, crisp and sweet with a good flavour.

Crowngold.name: Crowngold
Crowngold.description: A more highly coloured sport of Jonagold having a more solid bright red colour. It was selected at the National Fruit Trials. Fruits have sweet, juicy, melting flesh.

Cure.name: Cure
Cure.description: Originated in Normandy, France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have fine, hard flesh with a subacid, slightly bitter flavour.

Curl Tail.name: Curl Tail
Curl Tail.description: Originated from Surrey, England. First recorded in 1872. Fruits have soft, coarse-textured, dry flesh with a subacid flavour.

Cutler Grieve.name: Cutler Grieve
Cutler Grieve.description: Raised in Edinburgh, Scotland probably by James Grieve of Redbraes Nursery and introduced in about 1912 by David Storrie. Fruits have crisp, fine flesh with a sweet flavour.

D'Arcy Spice.name: D'Arcy Spice
D'Arcy Spice.description: Found in the garden of The Hall, Tolleshunt d'Arcy, Essex in about 1785, but may have earlier origins. It was introduced by John Harris, a nurseryman of Broomfield, as Baddow Pippin in 1848. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a characteristic aromatic flavour.

d'Eylau.name: d'Eylau
d'Eylau.description: Said to have been brought to France in about 1812 from Eylau, Russia, by a soldier of the Grand Army. Fruits have soft, dry flesh with an insipid flavour.

Dalice.name: Dalice
Dalice.description: Raised between 1933 and 1937 by A.C. Nash, Scutes Farm, Hastings, Sussex. Fruits have coarse, soft, dry flesh with a subacid to sweet, insipid flavour.

Daliest.name: Daliest
Daliest.description: A more highly coloured clone of Elstar. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Danziger Kantapfel.name: Danziger Kantapfel
Danziger Kantapfel.description: Thought to have arisen from the Danzig area, Poland. It was first mentioned in 1760. Fruits have fairly firm flesh with a sweet subacid, slightly aromatic flavour. Flesh is often stained red under the skin.

Dark Red Staymared.name: Dark Red Staymared
Dark Red Staymared.description: Triploid. A more highly coloured sport of Stayman's Winesap. It originated with B.C. Moomaw Jr., in Barber County, Virginia, USA. It was introduced in 1927. Fruits are juicy with a light aromatic flavour.

Daru Sovari.name: Daru Sovari
Daru Sovari.description: Originated from Hungary. It was described in 1875. Fruits have a slightly sweet, slightly aromatic flavour.

Davey.name: Davey
Davey.description: Discovered in 1928 by S. Lothrop Davenport in North Grafton, Massachusetts, USA. Introduced in 1950. Fruits have firm, slightly coarse flesh with a slightly sweet and perfumed flavour.

Dawn.name: Dawn
Dawn.description: Thought to have been raised by R. Staward, Ware Park Gardens, Hertfordshire. It was exhibited in 1940. Fruits have crisp, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

de Flandre.name: de Flandre
de Flandre.description: Originated from France. It was described in 1876. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

de Jaune.name: de Jaune
de Jaune.description: Thought to have originated in about 1700 in Sarthe, France. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

de l'Estre.name: de l'Estre
de l'Estre.description: It is believed to have originated before 1786 in Limousin, France and introduced by Jean-Baptiste Cabanis. Fruits have fine, firm flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

de Vendue l'Eveque.name: de Vendue l'Eveque
de Vendue l'Eveque.description: A variety of French origin. Described in 1948. Fruits have crisp, fine flesh with an acid flavour.

Decio.name: Decio
Decio.description: This variety is said to date from the time of Attila (c. 450 AD) and to have been brought to England by Roman general Ezio from Latium, Italy. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Decosta.name: Decosta
Decosta.description: A slightly striped, dark red clone of Jonagold. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1988 from Mr H. Decoster, Belgium. Fruits have juicy, sweet flesh with a good, rich flavour.

Dekker's Glory.name: Dekker's Glory
Dekker's Glory.description: The origin of this variety is unknown. Fruits have soft, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Delcorf.name: Delcorf
Delcorf.description: Raised in the 1960s by nurseryman G. Delbard at Malicorne, France. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1973. Fruits are fairly crisp and juicy and very sweet.

Delectable.name: Delectable
Delectable.description: A chance seedling originating with Mr Trayhorne in Berkshire. It was introduced in 1952 by Pope Bros., of Wokingham. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a vinous flavour.

Delgoton.name: Delgoton
Delgoton.description: Raised at Delbard Nursery, Malicorne, France.

Delgrared.name: Delgrared
Delgrared.description: Raised by nurseryman G. Delbard, Malicorne, France and introduced in the early 1990s. Fruits have sweet flesh with a slightly perfumed flavour.

Starkspur Supreme.name: Starkspur Supreme
Starkspur Supreme.description: A more highly coloured and spur type clone of Delicious. Originated in Henry Stem orchard in Zillah, Washington, USA. Fruits are firm, juicy and very sweet with a highly aromatic flavour.

Richared Delicious.name: Richared Delicious
Richared Delicious.description: A more highly coloured sport of Delicious. Discovered in about 1915 by J.L. Richardson, in Monitor, Washington, USA. Introduced in 1927 and trademarked by C & O Nursery Company. Fruits have very firm, very sweet, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Deljeni.name: Deljeni
Deljeni.description: Raised in the 1960s by nurseryman George Delbard, Malicorne, France. Fruits are crisp, sweet and juicy and very similar to Golden Delicious.

Deljorom.name: Deljorom
Deljorom.description: Raised by nurseryman George Delbard, Malicorne, France.

Delkistar.name: Delkistar
Delkistar.description: Registered as Regali. Raised in 1978 by nurseryman George Delbard, Malicorne, France. Fruits have sweet, slightly acid flesh with a very good flavour.

Delnimb.name: Delnimb
Delnimb.description: Raised in the 1960s by nurseryman George Delbard, Malicorne, France. Fruits have rather coarse, but juicy flesh with a fairly rich, sweet subacid flavour.

Delorgue.name: Delorgue
Delorgue.description: Raised by nurseryman G. Delbard, Malicorne, France and introduced in the late 1990s. Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh with a slightly perfumed flavour.

Delorina.name: Delorina
Delorina.description: Raised in 1985 by nurseryman G. Delbard, Malicorne, France and introduced in the mid 1990s.Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh.

Delprim.name: Delprim
Delprim.description: Raised in the late 1960s by nurseryman George Delbard, Malicorne, France. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a medium-weak aromatic flavour.

Delprivale.name: Delprivale
Delprivale.description: Raised by nurseryman G. Delbard, Malicorne, France in the 1960s. Introduced in the late 1990s. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Delvale.name: Delvale
Delvale.description: Raised by nurseryman G. Delbard, Malicorne, France. And introduced during the 1990s. Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh with a good flavour.

Democrat.name: Democrat
Democrat.description: Discovered in about 1900 growing in the orchard of J.D. Duffy near Hobart, Tasmania, Australia. It is known as Tasma in New Zealand. Fruits have very firm, coarse-textured, juicy, sweet flesh but lacks in flavour. In Australia it is said to have been stored for over twelve months.

Dermen McIntosh.name: Dermen McIntosh
Dermen McIntosh.description: Tetraploid. A sport of McIntosh. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1966 from the New York State Agriculture Experiment Station, Geneva, New York. Fruits have rather soft, very juicy, sweet flesh with a pleasant vinous flavour.

Dermen Winesap.name: Dermen Winesap
Dermen Winesap.description: Tetraploid. A sport of the American variety Winesap. Fruits have firm, tender, coarse flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Devonshire Buckland.name: Devonshire Buckland
Devonshire Buckland.description: Originated from Devon, England. First recorded in 1803. Fruits have soft flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Devonshire Quarrenden.name: Devonshire Quarrenden
Devonshire Quarrenden.description: Thought to have arisen in Devon, but may have originally come from France. First recorded in 1678. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a distinctive aromatic flavour.

Dewdney's Seedling.name: Dewdney's Seedling
Dewdney's Seedling.description: Raised at Barrowby, Grantham, Lincolnshire by Mr Dewdney in about 1850. Fruits have moderately firm, juicy and very acid flesh.

Diamond Jubilee.name: Diamond Jubilee
Diamond Jubilee.description: Raised in about 1889 by Mr Thomas, Rainham, Kent. It received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1901. Fruits have fine, firm, crisp flesh with a subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Dick's Favourite.name: Dick's Favourite
Dick's Favourite.description: Thought to have been raised in the late 1800s by Carless, foreman at Rowe's Nurseries, Worcester. Fruits are crisp with an acid flavour. Cooks well.

Directeur van de Plassche.name: Directeur van de Plassche
Directeur van de Plassche.description: Raised in 1935 at the Institute for Horticultural Plant Breeding, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits are juicy with a slightly subacid flavour.

Discovery.name: Discovery
Discovery.description: Raised in about 1949 by Mr Drummer, a workman on an Essex fruit farm. It was first named 'Thurston August' but renamed Discovery in 1962 and introduced by nurseryman J. Matthews, Thurston, Suffolk. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a fairly sweet and pleasant flavour.

Doctor Clifford.name: Doctor Clifford
Doctor Clifford.description: A chance seedling rootstock which originated with William Ingall, Grimoldby, Lincolnshire in about 1898. It was introduced in 1911. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Doctor Hogg.name: Doctor Hogg
Doctor Hogg.description: Raised by Sidney Ford, gardener at Leonardslee, Horsham, Sussex. Introduced in about 1880 by W. Paul & Son. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1878. Fruits have tender flesh with a sweet and subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Dodd.name: Dodd
Dodd.description: Arose in a pasture lane, over the fence from a Tolman Sweet orchard owned by Howard Dodds of Heuvelton, New York, USA. Fruits have a fine subacid flavour with a banana-like aroma.

Domino.name: Domino
Domino.description: Thought to have originated in the Midlands. First described in 1883. Fruits have soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Domnesc.name: Domnesc
Domnesc.description: Thought to be from Iasi, Moldavia, Romania. First recorded in 1831. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a fairly acid flavour.

Doree de Tournai.name: Doree de Tournai
Doree de Tournai.description: Raised by Joseph de Gaest de Braffe at Tournai, Belgium in 1817. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid rich aromatic flavour.

Dorsett Golden.name: Dorsett Golden
Dorsett Golden.description: Originated in the Bahamas in 1953 at the home of Mrs Irene Dorsett, Nassau, New Providence Islands. It was introduced in 1964. Fruits are sweet and juicy with a light aromatic flavour.

Double Red Northern Spy.name: Double Red Northern Spy
Double Red Northern Spy.description: A sport of Northern Spy having a solid, bright red flush. It was discovered in about 1895 by William S. Greene, Victor, New York, USA. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Double Red Rome Beauty.name: Double Red Rome Beauty
Double Red Rome Beauty.description: Tetraploid. A sport of Rome Beauty being flatter in shape and being almost entirely flushed with bright crimson and darker streaks. It was discovered in about 1920 by Earle E. Cowin, Wapato, Washington, USA. Fruits have rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh but tends to lack flavour.

Double Rose.name: Double Rose
Double Rose.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from France. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a fairly acid flavour.

Double-Red Baldwin.name: Double-Red Baldwin
Double-Red Baldwin.description: A brighter coloured sport of Baldwin. It was discovered in 1924 by E.N. Sawyer in Salisbury, New Hampshire, USA. Introduced in 1927. Fruits have coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Doud Golden Delicious.name: Doud Golden Delicious
Doud Golden Delicious.description: Tetraploid. A sport of Golden Delicious having much larger fruit. It was discovered by Lorne J. Doud, Wabash, Indiana, USA. Recorded in 1952. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.

Downton Pippin.name: Downton Pippin
