Downton Pippin.description: Raised by Thomas Andrew Knight at Wormsley Grange, Hereford. It was first exhibited in 1806. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid, vinous flavour.

Dredge's Fame.name: Dredge's Fame
Dredge's Fame.description: Introduced by William Dredge, Wishford, Salisbury. First recorded in 1802. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

Duchess of Bedford.name: Duchess of Bedford
Duchess of Bedford.description: Raised by Laxton Bros. Ltd., at Bedford. First exhibited in 1918. Fruits have rather soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Duchess of Oldenburg.name: Duchess of Oldenburg
Duchess of Oldenburg.description: Known in Russia in the 1700s or earlier but first known in the UK in about 1817. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a subacid and fair flavour.

Duchess's Favourite.name: Duchess's Favourite
Duchess's Favourite.description: Raised in about 1800 by Mr Cree, a nurseryman of Addlestone, Surrey. Fruits have crisp, yellow flesh with a brisk and pleasant flavour.

Dugamel.name: Dugamel
Dugamel.description: A more highly coloured clone of Melrose. It arose with nurseryman Charles Andre, France. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a pleasant, faintly aromatic flavour.

Dukat Spur.name: Dukat Spur
Dukat Spur.description: A spur type clone of Dukat, producing larger fruit. Selected by A. Dvorak at the Plant Breeding Station, Techobuzice, Czechoslovakia. Fruits are sweet with rather coarse-textured flesh.

Duke of Devonshire.name: Duke of Devonshire
Duke of Devonshire.description: Raised in 1835 by Wilson, gardener to the Duke of Devonshire at Holker Hall, Lancashire. It was introduced in about 1875. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a rich, nutty flavour.

Dulmener Rosenapfel.name: Dulmener Rosenapfel
Dulmener Rosenapfel.description: Raised in about 1870 by schoolmaster Jager at Dulmen, Westphalia, Germany. Fruits are sweet and juicy with an aromatic flavour.

Dumelow's Seedling.name: Dumelow's Seedling
Dumelow's Seedling.description: Raised by Mr Dumelow (or Dumeller) at Shakerstone, Leicestershire. The original tree was growing in 1800. It was exhibited as Dumelow's Crab in 1818, and renamed Wellington in 1819 or 1820. Fruits have very firm, crisp, juicy flesh which is extremely acid. Cooks well.

Dunn's Seedling.name: Dunn's Seedling
Dunn's Seedling.description: Said to have been raised by Mr Condor at Kew, Melbourne, Australia. First recorded in the UK in 1890. It was introduced by Mr Munroe. Fruits have crisp, hard flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Dunning.name: Dunning
Dunning.description: Raised in 1923 by Richard Wellington at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York. It was introduced in 1938. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet and faintly perfumed flavour.

Durello.name: Durello
Durello.description: An apple of Italian origin. It was described in 1949 but is thought to be much older. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, subacid, slightly perfumed flavour.

Dutch Codlin.name: Dutch Codlin
Dutch Codlin.description: Thought to have originated in The Netherlands. It was brought to notice in about 1783. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Dutch Mignonne.name: Dutch Mignonne
Dutch Mignonne.description: Thought to have been raised in The Netherlands. It was brought to England in about 1771 by Thomas Harvey of Catton, Norwich. It was introduced in about 1820 by George Lindley as Dutch Mignonne as its true name was not known. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with slightly acid, little sweet, faint aromatic flavour.

Eady's Magnum.name: Eady's Magnum
Eady's Magnum.description: Raised in about 1908 by Miss D.A. Eady at Wellingborough, Northants. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a rather acid flavour. An excellent cooker.

Early Julyan.name: Early Julyan
Early Julyan.description: Thought to have originated in Scotland. It was known before 1800. Fruits have crisp flesh with an acid flavour.

Early McIntosh.name: Early McIntosh
Early McIntosh.description: Raised by Richard Wellington at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York from seed sown in 1909. It was introduced in 1923. Fruits have crisp, white flesh which is often tinged pink beneath the skin, with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Early Strawberry (of Great Malvern).name: Early Strawberry (of Great Malvern)
Early Strawberry (of Great Malvern).description: Thought to have originated near New York, USA. First recorded in 1838. Fruits have firm, cream flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

East Lothian Pippin.name: East Lothian Pippin
East Lothian Pippin.description: Thought to have originated from Scotland. It was first described in 1883. It is indistinguishable from Hill's Seedling in the National Apple Collection. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with an acid flavour.

Eastbourne Pippin.name: Eastbourne Pippin
Eastbourne Pippin.description: Raised in 1930 at Eastbourne, Sussex, by E.A. Lindley. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Easter Orange.name: Easter Orange
Easter Orange.description: Introduced by nurserymen, Hillier & Sons, Winchester. It was first recorded in 1897 in which year it also received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have crisp, firm flesh with a sweet and aromatic flavour.

Eccleston Pippin.name: Eccleston Pippin
Eccleston Pippin.description: Raised by Mr Barnes, Head Gardener to the Duke of Westminster at Eaton Hall, Cheshire. It was first described in 1883. Fruits have coarse, but tender flesh with a subacid flavour.

Ecklinville.name: Ecklinville
Ecklinville.description: Said to have been raised by gardener Logan at Ecklinville, Portaferry, Belfast, Ireland. It was known in 1800. Fruits have rather soft, fine-textured, juicy flesh, with a very acid flavour. Cooks well.

Ed Gould Golden.name: Ed Gould Golden
Ed Gould Golden.description: A large russet free clone of Golden Delicious. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1971 from Italy. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.

Edelborsdorfer.name: Edelborsdorfer
Edelborsdorfer.description: Thought to be of German origin, either from Borsdorf in Meissen or near Leipzig. Recorded as early as the 1500s. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Eden.name: Eden
Eden.description: Raised in 1948 by Mr E.J. Ingleby, Forest and Orchard Nurseries, Falfield, Gloucestershire. It was introduced in 1957 by Matthews Fruit Trees Ltd., Thurston, Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk. Fruits have fine flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Edgar (Canada).name: Edgar (Canada)
Edgar (Canada).description: Originated at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada. It was selected in 1929. Fruits have soft, sweet and juicy flesh.

Edith Hopwood.name: Edith Hopwood
Edith Hopwood.description: Raised in Essex by F.W. Thorrington. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have fairly firm, coarse, crisp flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Edmund Jupp.name: Edmund Jupp
Edmund Jupp.description: Originated near Horsham, Sussex. It was first recorded in 1862. Fruits have tender flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Edward VII.name: Edward VII
Edward VII.description: First recorded in 1902. It was introduced by Rowe of Worcester in 1908. Received Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1903. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, fairly juicy flesh with an acid flavour. An excellent cooker.

Edwards.name: Edwards
Edwards.description: Believed to have originated in Chatham County, North Carolina, USA. First described in 1869. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a sweet, subacid and astringent flavour.

Egremont Russet.name: Egremont Russet
Egremont Russet.description: Thought to have originated in England. It was first recorded in 1872. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a rich, nutty flavour. It is probably the most important commercial russet in the UK at the present time.

Elan.name: Elan
Elan.description: Raised at IVT, Wageningen, The Netherlands and received by the National Fruit Trials in 1983. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Elbee.name: Elbee
Elbee.description: A slightly coloured clone of Golden Delicious with less russet. Discovered in Switzerland by Leo Basser. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Elektra.name: Elektra
Elektra.description: Raised by Prof. M. Schmidt at the Agricultural Research Station, Munchenberg, Germany. Fruits have firm, juicy, sweet flesh with a good Cox-like flavour.

Elise Rathke.name: Elise Rathke
Elise Rathke.description: Raised either by Rathke of Pravst near Danzig or by A. Duhring of Elbinge, Germany. It was first recorded in 1884. Fruits have fine, soft flesh with a subacid and moderately sweet and spicy flavour.

Elize.name: Elize
Elize.description: Raised at the Institute for Horticultural Plant Breeding, Wageningen, Netherlands.

Ellison's Orange.name: Ellison's Orange
Ellison's Orange.description: Raised by Rev. C.C. Ellison at Bracebridge and Mr Wipf, gardener at Hartsholme Hall, Lincolnshire. First recorded in 1904. It was introduced by Pennells Nurseries, Lincs. in 1911. Received Award of Merit in 1911 and First Class Certificate in 1917 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a rich and strong aniseed flavour.

Elnica.name: Elnica
Elnica.description: A more highly coloured clone of Elstar. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Elshof.name: Elshof
Elshof.description: A clone of Elstar. Originated at Wageningen, Netherlands. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Elstar.name: Elstar
Elstar.description: Raised in 1955 by Dr T. Visser at IVT,Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Elton Beauty.name: Elton Beauty
Elton Beauty.description: Originated at Ince Orchards, Chester. It was introduced by 1952. Fruits have soft, fine flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Emneth Early.name: Emneth Early
Emneth Early.description: Raised by William Lynn, Emneth, Cambridgeshire. It was first recorded in 1899 and introduced by Cross of Wisbech. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits are crisp, firm and very acid. Cooks well.

Empire.name: Empire
Empire.description: Raised in 1945 at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York. It was named and introduced in 1966. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Encore.name: Encore
Encore.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Welford Park, Newbury, Berkshire. First recorded in 1906. It was introduced in 1908 by J. Cheal of Crawley, Sussex. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1906 and a First Class Certificate in 1908. Fruits have soft, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. An excellent cooker.

Endsleigh Beauty.name: Endsleigh Beauty
Endsleigh Beauty.description: Originated with Henry Whiteley, Endsleigh Place, Torquay, Devon. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1906. Fruits have hard, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Entz-Rosmarin.name: Entz-Rosmarin
Entz-Rosmarin.description: Originated with pomologist Entz, Hungary or could be older. It was named by Bereczki in 1860. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a subacid and sweet flavour.

Epicure.name: Epicure
Epicure.description: Raised in 1909 by Laxton Bros. at Bedford. Introduced in 1929. It received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1931. Fruits have moderately firm and juicy flesh with a refreshing flavour.

Epicurean.name: Epicurean
Epicurean.description: A more highly coloured sport of Epicure. It originated with G.A. Maclean, Kingston Bagpuize, Berkshire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1953. Fruits have moderately firm and juicy flesh with a refreshing flavour.

Erich Neumanns Roter James Grieve.name: Erich Neumanns Roter James Grieve
Erich Neumanns Roter James Grieve.description: A sport of James Grieve having a darker flush and stripes. It originated in 1953 with Erich Neumann of Germany. Fruits have rather soft, very juicy flesh with a good refreshing flavour.

Erlijon.name: Erlijon
Erlijon.description: Originated with R. Banta, Carroll township, Arkansas, USA. It was introduced in 1968 by M.J.Lucas, Green Forest Nursery, Arkansas. Fruits have soft, white flesh with a vinous flavour.

Ernst Bosch.name: Ernst Bosch
Ernst Bosch.description: Raised by D. Uhlhorn, Germany. It was first recorded in 1908. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Eros.name: Eros
Eros.description: Raised in 1947 by W.D. Seabrook at Boreham, Essex. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Esopus Spitzenburg.name: Esopus Spitzenburg
Esopus Spitzenburg.description: Originated at Esopus, Ulster County, New York, USA. Known before 1790. Fruits have crisp, tender flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Essching.name: Essching
Essching.description: A Belgium variety, local to West Flanders. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have crisp flesh, with an acid flavour.

Estiva.name: Estiva
Estiva.description: Raised in 1957 at INRA, Angers, France. Fruits are crisp, juicy and slightly acid with some perfumed flavour.

Etlins Reinette.name: Etlins Reinette
Etlins Reinette.description: Originally found on the Landenberg estate of pomologist Etlin, in Germany. It was new in 1866. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid, aromatic flavour.

Eustis.name: Eustis
Eustis.description: Originated in the late 1600s with Benjamin Smith at Wakefield, Massachusetts, USA. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Eva Lotta.name: Eva Lotta
Eva Lotta.description: Originated in Sweden. Fruits have white, juicy flesh with a slightly acid and good flavour.

Evagil.name: Evagil
Evagil.description: Found at Tielt, Belgium by Dr van der Espt. It was introduced in 1863 by Van Houtte & Sons. Fruits have crisp, tender flesh with an acid flavour.

Excelsior.name: Excelsior
Excelsior.description: Raised by W. Seabrook & Sons, Chelmsford, Essex and introduced by them in 1921. Fruits have soft flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Exeter Cross.name: Exeter Cross
Exeter Cross.description: Raised in 1924 by G.T. Spinks at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. It was named in 1953. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet and refreshing flavour.

Exquisite.name: Exquisite
Exquisite.description: Raised in 1902 by Laxton Bros. at Bedford, England. It received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1926. Fruits have firm, crisp and juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Eynsham Challenger.name: Eynsham Challenger
Eynsham Challenger.description: Raised in 1935 by F.W. Wastie, Eynsham, Oxford. Fruits have rather coarse flesh with an acid flavour.

Eynsham Dumpling.name: Eynsham Dumpling
Eynsham Dumpling.description: Raised by F.W.Wastie, Eynsham, Oxford. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1960. Fruits have firm flesh with a rather acid and a little rich flavour.

Fairie Queen.name: Fairie Queen
Fairie Queen.description: Originated with R. Staward, Ware Park Gardens, Hertfordshire. It was first recorded in 1937. Fruits have tender flesh with a sweet, subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Fall Harvey.name: Fall Harvey
Fall Harvey.description: Originated in Essex County, Massachusetts, USA. It was first recorded in 1838. Fruits have rather coarse, crisp flesh with a rich, subacid flavour.

Fall Pippin.name: Fall Pippin
Fall Pippin.description: Originated in the USA and first recorded in 1806. Fruits have moderately firm, fine, tender flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Fall Russet.name: Fall Russet
Fall Russet.description: The original tree of this variety was planted in about 1880 in the USA. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid and slightly rich flavour.

Falstaff.name: Falstaff
Falstaff.description: Raised in 1966 at East Malling Research Station, Kent. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a very good flavour.

Fameuse.name: Fameuse
Fameuse.description: Thought to be a Canadian variety and may have been raised from seed brought from France by early settlers. It was planted in the USA in about 1730. Fruits have rather soft, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a very sweet and vinous flavour - similar to McIntosh.

Fantazja.name: Fantazja
Fantazja.description: Raised in 1944 by A.Rejman, Warsaw Agricultural University, Poland. It was introduced in 1960. Fruits have fine, very juicy flesh with a rich and good flavour.

Faros.name: Faros
Faros.description: Originated in France. It was first described in 1776. Fruits have coarse flesh, with a subacid flavour.

Fearn's Pippin.name: Fearn's Pippin
Fearn's Pippin.description: Raised in Mr Bagley's garden at Fulham, London before 1780. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a slightly acid and pleasant aromatic flavour.

Fekete Tanyeralma.name: Fekete Tanyeralma
Fekete Tanyeralma.description: Originated in Transylvania Hungary. It was first described in 1909. Fruits have firm, tender flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Feltham Beauty.name: Feltham Beauty
Feltham Beauty.description: Raised and introduced by Veitch's Nursery, Langley, Bucks. First described in 1908. It received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1908. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid and sweet flavour.

Fenouillet de Ribours.name: Fenouillet de Ribours
Fenouillet de Ribours.description: Found in the garden of La Rouairie, Maine-et-Loire, France. Distributed by M. de la Perraudiere. It first fruited in 1840. Fruits have fine, white flesh with a sweet, subacid, aniseed perfumed flavour.

Fenouillet Gris.name: Fenouillet Gris
Fenouillet Gris.description: Originated at Anjou, France. It was first described in 1608. Fruits have fine, crisp, white flesh with a sweet and aniseed flavour.

Fenouillet Rouge.name: Fenouillet Rouge
Fenouillet Rouge.description: Thought to have originated in France. First recorded in 1667. Fruits have fine, soft, dry flesh with a sweet flavour.

Feuillemorte.name: Feuillemorte
Feuillemorte.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid and distinctive flavour.

Fiessers Erstling.name: Fiessers Erstling
Fiessers Erstling.description: Raised before 1904 by gardener Fiesser of Baden Baden, Germany. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with an acid flavour.

Fiesta.name: Fiesta
Fiesta.description: Raised in 1972 at East Malling Research Station, Kent. It received an Award of Merit in 1987 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a Cox-like flavour.

Fil Jaune.name: Fil Jaune
Fil Jaune.description: Originated from France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Filippa.name: Filippa
Filippa.description: Raised in about 1880 by Filippa Johannsen of Hundstrup, South Fyn Island, Denmark. Received a First Class Certificate by the Danish Horticultural Society. Fruits have fine, tender flesh, with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Fillingham Pippin.name: Fillingham Pippin
Fillingham Pippin.description: Originated from seed sown or cuttings received from America by Mr Fillingham, Swanland, Yorkshire. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1923. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with an acid flavour. Can be propagated from cuttings.

Finkenwerder Prinz.name: Finkenwerder Prinz
Finkenwerder Prinz.description: Originated in about 1860 on the island of Finkenwerder in the Elbe near Hamburg, Germany. Fruits have fairly firm, fairly fine flesh with a sweet, subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Fireside.name: Fireside
Fireside.description: Originated at Minnesota Agricultural Experiment Station, Excelsior, USA, by Charles Haralson. It was selected in 1917 and introduced commercially in 1943. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet subacid, aromatic flavour.

Firmgold.name: Firmgold
Firmgold.description: A chance seedling found growing among some Starkspur Golden Delicious and Starkrimson Red Delicious trees, in Zillah, Washington, USA, by Z.B. Howell. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Fisher Fortune.name: Fisher Fortune
Fisher Fortune.description: A more highly coloured sport of Fortune. It was discovered in about 1960 on the farm of A.M. Fisher, Holmlea Farms Ltd., Elverland, Faversham, Kent. Fruits have moderately firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Flame.name: Flame
Flame.description: Raised in 1925 at Boreham, Essex by W. Seabrook & Sons Ltd. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Fletcher's Prolific.name: Fletcher's Prolific
Fletcher's Prolific.description: Assumed to be of UK origin. It was first recorded in 1888. Fruits have soft, fine flesh with a little subacid and sweet flavour.

Florence Bennett.name: Florence Bennett
Florence Bennett.description: Raised by Mrs Florence Bennett, Crosby Green, West Derby, Liverpool as a result of some apple cores being thrown on a garden rubbish heap. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1971. Fruits have fairly firm, juicy flesh with a sweet and lemon flavour.

Florianer Rosenapfel.name: Florianer Rosenapfel
Florianer Rosenapfel.description: Originated in Germany. It was first described in 1776 and named in 1859. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Florina.name: Florina
Florina.description: Complex parentage involving Rome Beauty, Golden Delicious, Starking, Simpsons Giant Limb and Jonathan. A scab resistant variety raised at the Station de Recherches d'Arboriculture Fruitiere, Angers, France. Fruits tend to be rather tart and acid.

Flower of the Town.name: Flower of the Town
Flower of the Town.description: Originated in Yorkshire, England. It was first described in 1831. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid flavour.

Fon's Spring.name: Fon's Spring
Fon's Spring.description: Raised in 1948 by Ernest J. Ingleby, Milbury Heath, Falfield, Gloucestershire. Fruits have firm, fairly juicy flesh with a sweet, subacid, faint Cox-like flavour.

Forester.name: Forester
Forester.description: Originated in Herefordshire, England. First described in 1883. Fruits have coarse, soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Forge.name: Forge
Forge.description: Said to have originated at a Forge Farm in Sussex or near one of the old forges in the iron district near East Grinstead, Sussex. It was described in 1851 when it was already well known. Fruits have crisp, very juicy flesh with a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Fortune.name: Fortune
Fortune.description: Raised in 1904 by Laxton Brothers Ltd. at Bedford, England and introduced in 1931. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1948. Fruits have fairly firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Foster's Seedling.name: Foster's Seedling
Foster's Seedling.description: Originated in the UK. It was introduced in about 1893 by G. Bunyard, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits have tender flesh with an acid and vinous flavour.

Foulkes' Foremost.name: Foulkes' Foremost
Foulkes' Foremost.description: Raised by F. Foulkes, Headington, Oxford from seed sown in 1938. Fruits have rather soft flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Fraise de Buhler.name: Fraise de Buhler
Fraise de Buhler.description: Thought to have originated from Buhl near Baden, Germany. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from Switzerland. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Framboise.name: Framboise
Framboise.description: First described by Knoop, a Dutch pomologist in 1771. Fruits have sweet, juicy, softish flesh with a raspberry like flavour.

Francis (Thorrington).name: Francis (Thorrington)
Francis (Thorrington).description: Raised in Essex by F.W. Thorrington. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp flesh with a very sweet and aromatic flavour.

Frankettu.name: Frankettu
Frankettu.description: Said to have originated in the Melun area of France. It was first described in 1536. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet and acid flavour.

Fred Webb.name: Fred Webb
Fred Webb.description: Raised in about 1935 by F.W. Webb at Bunyard's Nursery, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a fair flavour.

Freedom (USA).name: Freedom (USA)
Freedom (USA).description: A disease resistant variety bred in 1958 at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA, from a complex parentage of Macoun, Antonovka, Golden Delicious, Rome Beauty and Malus floribunda.. Fruits have crisp, juicy, fairly coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Freiherr von Berlepsch.name: Freiherr von Berlepsch
Freiherr von Berlepsch.description: Raised in about 1880 in Grevenbroich, Rheinland, Germany by Diedrich Uhlhorn junior. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Fremy.name: Fremy
Fremy.description: Raised in about 1830-40 by farmer Fremy of Chere, France. Fruits have fine, firm flesh with a sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

French Crab.name: French Crab
French Crab.description: Thought to have originated in France. It was brought to England at the end of the 1700s. Fruits have white, distinctly green tinged flesh which is very firm, coarse-textured and a little juicy and acid. It cooks well, having a strong aroma when cooking.

Freyberg.name: Freyberg
Freyberg.description: Raised in 1934 by J.H.Kidd at Greytown, Wairarapa, New Zealand. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Friandise.name: Friandise
Friandise.description: Originated in The Netherlands. It was first described in 1760. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Friedrich der Grosse.name: Friedrich der Grosse
Friedrich der Grosse.description: Thought to be of German origin but received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from France. Fruits have fine, rather hard flesh with a sweet, subacid, nutty flavour.

Frogmore Prolific.name: Frogmore Prolific
Frogmore Prolific.description: Raised in about 1865 by Mr Ingram at The Royal Gardens, Frogmore, Windsor, England. Fruits are soft, fine-textured, acid and a little juicy, with no particular flavour.

Fuji.name: Fuji
Fuji.description: Raised in 1939 by H. Niitsu at the Horticultural Research Station, Nakahara, Japan. It was named in 1962. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a slightly subacid flavour. Fruits often fail to mature fully in the UK.

Fukunishiki.name: Fukunishiki
Fukunishiki.description: Raised in 1933 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1949. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, almost 'pear drop' flavour.

Fukutami.name: Fukutami
Fukutami.description: Raised in 1933 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a fairly sweet and subacid flavour.

Fyriki.name: Fyriki
Fyriki.description: Originated from Greece, native to Mount Pelion. Fruits have softish, sweet flesh with an aromatic flavour. Some resistance to scab.

Gala.name: Gala
Gala.description: Raised in about 1934 by J.H.Kidd at Greytown Wairarapa, New Zealand. It was named in 1965. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Galantine.name: Galantine
Galantine.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1934. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Galaxy.name: Galaxy
Galaxy.description: A darker red, stripey clone of Gala. Discovered in 1985 by K.W. Kiddle, Hawkes Bay, New Zealand. Introduced in 1988. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Galeuse.name: Galeuse
Galeuse.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1934. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Galloway Pippin.name: Galloway Pippin
Galloway Pippin.description: Believed to have come from Wigtown, Galloway, Scotland. It was first brought to notice in 1871 but is thought to be much older. Received First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1871. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Galton.name: Galton
Galton.description: Raised by W.T.Macoun, Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1915. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet flavour.

Gambafina.name: Gambafina
Gambafina.description: Thought to have originated in about 1900 near Carraglio, province of Cuneo, Italy. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Garden Royal.name: Garden Royal
Garden Royal.description: Originated on the farm of Mr Bowker, Sudbury, Massachusetts, USA. It was described in 1847. Fruits have fine, tender, yellow flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Garnet.name: Garnet
Garnet.description: Raised by W.Seabrook & Sons Ltd., Boreham, Essex. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1936. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Gascoyne's Scarlet.name: Gascoyne's Scarlet
Gascoyne's Scarlet.description: Raised by Mr Gascoyne at Bapchild Court, Sittingbourne, Kent. It was introduced in 1871 by nurseryman G. Bunyard & Co., Maidstone, Kent. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1887. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, slightly juicy, sweet flesh with very little flavour.

Gavin.name: Gavin
Gavin.description: Raised in 1956 by A.G. Brown at John Innes Institute, Bayfordbury, Hertfordshire. Fruits have crisp, fairly juicy flesh with a fairly sweet flavour.

Geeveston Fanny.name: Geeveston Fanny
Geeveston Fanny.description: Thought to have originated at Geeveston, Tasmania, Australia where the oldest known tree grew in the orchard of James Evans in 1880. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Geheimrat Breuhahn.name: Geheimrat Breuhahn
Geheimrat Breuhahn.description: Originated in 1895 at the Fruit, Vine and Horticulture Research Station, Geisenheim, Germany. It was introduced in 1934. Fruits have fine, moderately firm flesh with a sweet and subacid flavour.

Geheimrat Doktor Oldenburg.name: Geheimrat Doktor Oldenburg
Geheimrat Doktor Oldenburg.description: Raised in 1897 at the Vine, Fruit & Horticulture Station, Geisenheim, Germany. Fruits have fine, softish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Gene Pitney.name: Gene Pitney
Gene Pitney.description: Raised in 1962 at the request of one of Gene Pitney's fans, Miss Juliah Couper, at the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, Havelock North, New Zealand. It was introduced in 1964. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Geneva Ontario.name: Geneva Ontario
Geneva Ontario.description: Tetraploid. A sport of Ontario having larger fruit. It was found in the orchard of New York state Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Fruits have rather coarse, soft flesh with a subacid and sweet flavour.

Gennet Moyle (of Taylor).name: Gennet Moyle (of Taylor)
Gennet Moyle (of Taylor).description: Assumed to be of UK origin. It was known to be widely grown by the 17th Century. It produces a light cider and is also used for cooking.

George Carpenter.name: George Carpenter
George Carpenter.description: Raised in 1902 by George Carpenter at West Hall Gardens, Byfleet, Surrey. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a good aromatic flavour somewhat like Blenheim Orange.

George Cave.name: George Cave
George Cave.description: Raised in 1923 by George Cave at Dovercourt, Essex. It was acquired by Seabrook & Sons Ltd., Boreham, Essex and named in 1945. Fruits have a little soft, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a little acid, slightly aromatic and pleasant flavour.

George Neal.name: George Neal
George Neal.description: Raised in 1904 by Mrs Reeves at Otford, Kent and introduced by R. Neal & Sons, Wandsworth, London in 1923. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1923. Fruits have rather soft, juicy and acid flesh. It cooks well, breaking up almost completely.

Gibbon's Russet.name: Gibbon's Russet
Gibbon's Russet.description: Originated from Cork, Ireland. It was recorded in 1897. Fruits have firm, tender, fine flesh with a sweet, slightly aromatic flavour.

Gladstone.name: Gladstone
Gladstone.description: Thought to have originated in about 1780. It was re-discovered by Jackson, at Blakedown Nursery, Kidderminster, Worcestershire and introduced in 1868 as Jackson's Seedling. It was renamed Mr Gladstone after receiving a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1883. Fruits are crisp and juicy becoming rather soft, with a pleasant, aromatic flavour.

Glasbury.name: Glasbury
Glasbury.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1872. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1979 from Norfolk. Fruits have good flavour when cooked but can soon become insipid.

Glass Apple.name: Glass Apple
Glass Apple.description: Originated from the Tamar Valley, Cornwall. It was known in 1934. Fruits have crisp, slightly coarse flesh with a slightly sweet and acid flavour.

Glebe Gold.name: Glebe Gold
Glebe Gold.description: Raised by James Walker, Ham, Surrey. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have soft, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Glengyle Red.name: Glengyle Red
Glengyle Red.description: A more highly coloured sport of Rome Beauty. It originated in 1914 at Balhannah, South Australia. Fruits have creamy white, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh but with little flavour. Skin tends to be tough.

Glenton.name: Glenton
Glenton.description: Raised at Ottawa Central Experimental Farm, Ontario, Canada. It was named in 1911 and introduced in 1946. Fruits have softish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Glogerovka.name: Glogerovka
Glogerovka.description: Thought to have originated either in Lithuania or Russia. It was described in 1903 as Pepinka Litovskaya. Fruits have very tender, loose textured flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Gloria Mundi.name: Gloria Mundi
Gloria Mundi.description: Though to have been raised either in Germany or USA. It was first recorded in the USA in 1804. Fruits have rather soft, coarse-textured, dry flesh with a subacid flavour.

Glorie van Holland.name: Glorie van Holland
Glorie van Holland.description: Raised in about 1890 by Hazelbag at Rockanje, The Netherlands. Fruits have slightly acid, slightly sweet flesh.

Gloster 69.name: Gloster 69
Gloster 69.description: Raised in 1951 at the Fruit Research Station, Jork, Hamburg, Germany. Fruits have fine-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a briskly pleasant flavour.

Gloucester Cross.name: Gloucester Cross
Gloucester Cross.description: Raised in 1913 by G.T.Spinks at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. Fruits have soft, coarse, subacid flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Gloucester Royal.name: Gloucester Royal
Gloucester Royal.description: Raised in about 1930 at Dursley, Gloucestershire, by J.W. Thornhill. It was introduced in 1956 by Matthews Fruit Trees Ltd., Thurston, Bury St. Edmunds, Suffolk. Fruits have coarse flesh with a sweet and insipid flavour.

Golco.name: Golco
Golco.description: Received at Brogdale from nurseryman J. Nicolai, Belgium. Fruits are sweet and juicy with a good flavour.

Gold Medal.name: Gold Medal
Gold Medal.description: Raised by Troughton, a nurseryman at Preston, Lancashire. Its original name was Ryland Surprise. It was introduced in about 1882. Fruits have soft, white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Gold Reinette.name: Gold Reinette
Gold Reinette.description: Its origin is unknown but is thought to probably be continental Europe. It has been known in England since the mid 1600s. Fruits have crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Golden Auvilspur.name: Golden Auvilspur
Golden Auvilspur.description: A spur type clone of Golden Delicious. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.

Golden Bounty.name: Golden Bounty
Golden Bounty.description: Raised in about 1940 by A.C. Nash, Scutes Farm, Hastings. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a rich and subacid flavour.

Golden Delicious.name: Golden Delicious
Golden Delicious.description: A chance seedling found in 1890 by A.H. Mullins, Clay County, West Virginia, USA. It was introduced in 1914 by Stark Brothers. Fruits have crisp, sweet, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Golden Delicious Russet.name: Golden Delicious Russet
Golden Delicious Russet.description: A sport of Golden Delicious being entirely covered in russet. It originated from Stuttgart, Germany. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1968. Fruits have fairly crisp, juicy flesh with a good flavour.

Golden Harvey.name: Golden Harvey
Golden Harvey.description: Thought to have originated in the 1600s in Herefordshire. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet, rich, aromatic flavour.

Golden Knob.name: Golden Knob
Golden Knob.description: Originated at Enmore Castle, Somerset. It has been grown since the late 1700s. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet and nutty flavour.

Golden Melon.name: Golden Melon
Golden Melon.description: Raised in 1931 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits have soft but moderately firm flesh with a sweet and insipid flavour.

Golden Morspur.name: Golden Morspur
Golden Morspur.description: A spur type clone of Golden Delicious.

Golden Noble.name: Golden Noble
Golden Noble.description: Discovered by Patrick Flanagan, head gardener to Sir Thomas Harr, Stowe Hall, Downham, Norfolk. It was mentioned by William Forsyth in 1803. It was introduced by Patrick Flanagan to the Horticultural Society of London in 1820. Fruits are a little soft, fairly fine-textured, very juicy, and acid. Cooks extremely well, breaking up completely.

Golden Nugget.name: Golden Nugget
Golden Nugget.description: Raised in 1932 by C.J. Bishop, Kentville, Nova Scotia, Canada. It was introduced in 1964. Fruits have a sweet, rich flavour.

Golden Pippin.name: Golden Pippin
Golden Pippin.description: Originated in England. It was recorded in 1629. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid and rich flavour.

Golden Reinette.name: Golden Reinette
Golden Reinette.description: Thought to have originated in Europe. It has been known in England since the mid 1600s. Fruits have crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Golden Russet of Western New York.name: Golden Russet of Western New York
Golden Russet of Western New York.description: Thought to be of English origin. It has been known since the mid 1700s. Fruits have fine-textured, firm, rather dry flesh with a sweet and pleasant nutty flavour.
Golden Russet of Western New York.accession name: Golden Russet of Western New York

Golden Spire.name: Golden Spire
Golden Spire.description: Found in about 1850 in Lancashire by Richard Smith of Worcester who also introduced it. Fruits have coarse, crisp flesh with an acid and astringent flavour.

Goldensheen.name: Goldensheen
Goldensheen.description: A less russetted clone of Golden Delicious. Discovered by M.Ancian, Agen, France. Fruits are very sweet, crisp and juicy.

Goldjon.name: Goldjon
Goldjon.description: Raised by Professor Carlone, Turin University, Italy. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Goldspur.name: Goldspur
Goldspur.description: A spur type clone of Golden Delicious. It was discovered in 1960 by Grady Auvil, Sundale Orchards, Roosevelt, Washington, USA. It was introduced in 1963. Fruits have crisp, sweet, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Gooseberry.name: Gooseberry
Gooseberry.description: Raised in England, probably Kent. It was first recorded in 1831. Fruits have coarse-textured, fairly juicy flesh with a very acid and rather astringent flavour.

Goro.name: Goro
Goro.description: Raised in 1951 at the Swiss Federal Research Station, Wadenswil. Named and released in 1973. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Grand'mere.name: Grand'mere
Grand'mere.description: Originated from France. It was recorded in 1915. Fruits have tender, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Grange's Pearmain.name: Grange's Pearmain
Grange's Pearmain.description: Raised before 1829 by James Grange, market gardener at Kingsland, Middlesex. It was introduced by Dickson of Chester. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Granny Giffard.name: Granny Giffard
Granny Giffard.description: Exhibited in 1858 at Minster, near Margate, Kent. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a subacid flavour.

Granny Smith.name: Granny Smith
Granny Smith.description: Raised by Mrs Thomas Smith, Ryde, New South Wales, Australia. Trees were known to be fruiting in 1868. Mrs Smith was born in Peasmarsh, Sussex in 1800 and emigrated to Australia in 1838. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a subacid and refreshing flavour.

Grantonian.name: Grantonian
Grantonian.description: First recorded in 1883. It was introduced by Pearson of Nottingham. Received a second class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1883. Fruits have coarse, mealy, soft flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Graue Herbstrenette.name: Graue Herbstrenette
Graue Herbstrenette.description: Thought to have originated in England or Europe. It was first described in 1670. Fruits have fine, soft flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Gravenstein.name: Gravenstein
Gravenstein.description: Triploid. Said to have originated either in the garden of the Duke of Augustenberg, Castle of Graefenstein, Schleswig-Holstein or in Italy or Southern Tyrol and sent to Schleswig-Holstein, or scions from Italy sent home by a brother of Count Chr. Ahlefeldt of Graasten Castle, South Jutland. It is thought to have arrived in Denmark in about 1669. Fruits have crisp, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a pleasant mixture of sweetness and acidity with a distinctive flavour.

Greasy Pippin (Northern Ireland).name: Greasy Pippin (Northern Ireland)
Greasy Pippin (Northern Ireland).description: Originated from Ireland. It was described in 1951. Fruits become very greasy. Flesh is firm and crisp and has a sweet flavour.

Great Expectations.name: Great Expectations
Great Expectations.description: Originated from Ireland. It was described in 1951. Fruits become very greasy. Flesh is firm and crisp and has a sweet flavour.

Green Purnell.name: Green Purnell
Green Purnell.description: Originated in Worcestershire. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945 but is believed to be much older. Fruits have fine, creamy white flesh with a slightly sweet and subacid flavour.

Green Roland.name: Green Roland
Green Roland.description: Originated in Norfolk. It was described in 1945. Fruits have hard flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Greensleeves.name: Greensleeves
Greensleeves.description: Raised in 1966 by Dr Alston, East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. A prolific and precocious variety. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a mild, refreshing flavour.

Greenup's Pippin.name: Greenup's Pippin
Greenup's Pippin.description: Found in the garden of shoemaker Greenup in Keswick and introduced in the late 1700s by nurserymen Clarke & Atkinson, Keswick. Fruits have tender, yellowish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Grenadier.name: Grenadier
Grenadier.description: First recorded in 1862 and introduced to commerce in about 1875. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1883. The most widely grown early commercial cooking apple in the UK. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy fle

Grey Pippin.name: Grey Pippin
Grey Pippin.description: Discovered in about 1980 by fruit grower J. Tann, Essex. Fruits are sweet with a pleasant flavour.

Grimes Golden.name: Grimes Golden
Grimes Golden.description: Raised by Thomas Grimes, Brook County, West Virginia, USA. It was first known in 1804. Fruits have crisp, juicy, fine-textured flesh with a sweet and moderate flavour.

Groninger Kroon.name: Groninger Kroon
Groninger Kroon.description: Originated in The Netherlands. It was introduced to England by Newman Collard, Liss, Hampshire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1944. Fruits have very fine, very firm flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Gronsvelder Klumpke.name: Gronsvelder Klumpke
Gronsvelder Klumpke.description: Grown in The Netherlands and Belgium. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Gros Croquet.name: Gros Croquet
Gros Croquet.description: Thought to have originated in the Ardennes, France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have tender, fine flesh with a sweet, subacid and perfumed flavour.

Gros-Locard.name: Gros-Locard
Gros-Locard.description: Originated in France and known before 1849. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet and slightly acid flavour.

Gros-Api.name: Gros-Api
Gros-Api.description: Said to have originated in the Forest of Api in Brittany, France. It was recorded in 1628. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with a sweet, subacid and perfumed flavour.

Gros-Fenouillet Gris.name: Gros-Fenouillet Gris
Gros-Fenouillet Gris.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1667. Fruits have fine, compact, tender flesh with a sweet flavour.

Gros-Hopital.name: Gros-Hopital
Gros-Hopital.description: Triploid. Originated long before 1864 at Seine-Inferieure (Maritime), France. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Groseille.name: Groseille
Groseille.description: Originated in France. Although dual purpose, this variety is mainly used for cooking.

Grosse Mignonnette d'Herbassy.name: Grosse Mignonnette d'Herbassy
Grosse Mignonnette d'Herbassy.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1934. Fruits have fairly firm flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Grosse Rouge.name: Grosse Rouge
Grosse Rouge.description: Originated in the Lot region of France. It was described in 1947. Fruits are very sweet with a perfumed flavour.

Grosse Saulette.name: Grosse Saulette
Grosse Saulette.description: A sport of Saulette, a French apple from Germany. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with an acid flavour.

Guelph.name: Guelph
Guelph.description: Raised by W. Pope at Welford Gardens, Newbury, Berkshire. It received an Award of Merit in 1912 and a First Class Certificate in 1913 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, fine-textured flesh which is a little juicy and rather lacking in flavour.

Guldborg.name: Guldborg
Guldborg.description: Originated in Denmark. It was known in the 1870s. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Gustavs Dauerapfel.name: Gustavs Dauerapfel
Gustavs Dauerapfel.description: Raised by Lobner, Wadenswil, Switzerland. It was first described in 1899. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid and perfumed flavour.

Gyllenkroks Astrakan.name: Gyllenkroks Astrakan
Gyllenkroks Astrakan.description: Found in Fogelvik, north Tjust, Sweden. It was introduced by E. Lindgren, in 1863, although it is thought to have been known in the early 1800s. Fruits have fine, loose, white flesh with a subacid flavour. Flesh bruises easily.

Gyogyi piros.name: Gyogyi piros
Gyogyi piros.description: Thought to have originated either in Romania or Hungary. It was recorded in 1860. Fruits have fairly firm, fine flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Halberstadter Jungfernapfel.name: Halberstadter Jungfernapfel
Halberstadter Jungfernapfel.description: Originated in the Harz area of Germany. It was recorded in 1885. Fruits have firm, rather coarse flesh with a moderately sweet and subacid flavour.

Hambledon Deux Ans.name: Hambledon Deux Ans
Hambledon Deux Ans.description: Originated in Hambledon, Hampshire, England in about 1750. Fruits have very firm, coarse-textured, rather dry flesh, which is a little sweet and slightly acid with a faint aromatic flavour. Rather prone to bitter pit.

Hambling's Seedling.name: Hambling's Seedling
Hambling's Seedling.description: Raised by Major W.J. Hambling, Dunstable, Bedfordshire and introduced in 1894 by Bunyard, Maidstone. It received a First Class Certificate from the RHS in 1893. Fruits have a subacid flavour.

Hannan Seedling.name: Hannan Seedling
Hannan Seedling.description: Raised in 1928 by Mrs I. Hannan, Walton-on-Thames, Surrey from seed of an Australian apple. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Hanwell Souring.name: Hanwell Souring
Hanwell Souring.description: Said to have been raised at Hanwell near Banbury, Oxfordshire. It was recorded in 1820. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with an acid flavour.

Happisburgh.name: Happisburgh
Happisburgh.description: Name updated to 'Happisburgh' (April 2019) to be correct for the reported town of origin and as listed at the time of accession (was later changed in NFC listings and listed as 'Hapsburg' by Smith, 1971)

Haralson.name: Haralson
Haralson.description: Originated in Excelsior, Minnesota, USA by the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm. Selected in 1913 and introduced in 1923. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Harberts Reinette.name: Harberts Reinette
Harberts Reinette.description: Thought to have originated in Westphalia, Germany. It was known before 1828. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Hared.name: Hared
Hared.description: Sport of Oregon Spur Delicious. Originated in France. Fruits have firm, juicy, very sweet flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Harling Hero.name: Harling Hero
Harling Hero.description: Raised by Mr Claxton, a gardener of East Harling, Norfolk. Fruits have juicy, melting flesh.

Harvest Festival.name: Harvest Festival
Harvest Festival.description: Raised in about 1955 by Mrs Helen Lloyd of Lytham St. Annes, Lancashire. Fruit quality is not as good as Grenadier. It cooks reasonably well but has little flavour.

Harvey.name: Harvey
Harvey.description: Originated in Norfolk and was named after Dr Gabriel Harvey of Cambridge. It was mentioned in 1629 by Parkinson. Fruits have firm, coarse textured, very dry flesh with a subacid and perfumed flavour.

Hatsuaki.name: Hatsuaki
Hatsuaki.description: Raised in 1939 at the Fruit Tree Research Station, Japan. Introduced in 1976. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Hawthornden.name: Hawthornden
Hawthornden.description: Originated in Scotland. It was first catalogued in 1780. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Hazen.name: Hazen
Hazen.description: Raised in Mandan, North Dakota, USA by Neal S. Holland at the Department of Horticulture, North Dakota State University, Fargo, and USDA. Introduced in 1980. It was named after the nearby town Hazen and Dean Arlon Hazen, the Director of North Dakota Experiment Station. Fruits have fairly firm, slightly coarse, juicy flesh with a mild, subacid flavour. Said to be fairly resistant to Fireblight.

Hector MacDonald.name: Hector MacDonald
Hector MacDonald.description: Raised at Welford Park, Newbury, Berkshire, by Charles Ross and introduced in 1906 by Pearson of Nottingham. It was awarded an Award of Merit by the RHS in 1904. Fruits have very crisp, juicy, acid flesh. A good cooker.

Helios.name: Helios
Helios.description: Raised at the Institute for Agriculture and Horticulture, Munchenberg-Mark, Germany. Introduced in 1969. Fruits have a rich, sweet flavour.

Henry Clay.name: Henry Clay
Henry Clay.description: Originated in the USA. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Herceg Batthyanyi alma.name: Herceg Batthyanyi alma
Herceg Batthyanyi alma.description: Originated in Hungary. It was recorded in 1876. Fruits have fairly crisp flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Hereford Cross.name: Hereford Cross
Hereford Cross.description: Raised in 1913 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol by G.T. Spinks. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a fairly sweet and subacid flavour.

Herefordshire Beefing.name: Herefordshire Beefing
Herefordshire Beefing.description: Raised in Herefordshire, England. It was known in the late 1700s. Fruits have firm, fine-textured flesh with a moderately acid flavour.

Herefordshire Russet.name: Herefordshire Russet
Herefordshire Russet.description: Raised in 1975 by Mr Hugh Ermen, Faversham, Kent. Introduced in 2003 by Frank P. Matthews Ltd., Tenbury Wells, Worcestershire. Fruits are crisp with a sweet subacid flavour

Herma.name: Herma
Herma.description: Raised in the 1930s at the former Kaiser Wilhelm Institut, Muncheberg, Brandenburg, Germany. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1977. Fruits are crisp and juicy. Skin can be tough.

Herring's Pippin.name: Herring's Pippin
Herring's Pippin.description: Thought to have been raised by Mr Herring of Lincoln. It was first recorded in 1908. Introduced by Pearson of Nottingham. Fruits have moderately firm, rather coarse-textured juicy flesh with a good aromatic almost aniseed flavour.

Heusgen's Golden Reinette (Bultitude).name: Heusgen's Golden Reinette (Bultitude)
Heusgen's Golden Reinette (Bultitude).description: Raised by Pastor Konrad Henzen at Elsen, Germany. It was named after pomologist Peter Heusgen and introduced in about 1877. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Hibbs Seedling.name: Hibbs Seedling
Hibbs Seedling.description: A chance seedling found by A. Moody of Southampton, Hampshire and received by the National Fruit Trials in 1961. Fruits have fine, crisp, tender flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Hibernal.name: Hibernal
Hibernal.description: Either Russian or originated in the USA and sent to Russia. It is said to have gone to Russia in 1870 and recorded in the USA in 1880. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with an acid and astringent flavour.

Hidala.name: Hidala
Hidala.description: An earlier ripening clone of Braeburn. Discovered in 1981 in New Zealand. Introduced in 1990. Fruits have very firm, crisp flesh with a perfumed flavour.

High View Pippin.name: High View Pippin
High View Pippin.description: Raised in 1911 by Frederick Fitzwater at Ernest Hill, Weybridge, Surrey. It received an Award of Merit from the RHS in 1928. Fruits have firm, fine-textured juicy flesh with a sweet, pleasant, aromatic flavour.

Histon Favourite.name: Histon Favourite
Histon Favourite.description: Raised by John Chivers at Histon, Cambridgeshire, England. It was first recorded in 1883. Fruits have rather soft, fine textured, juicy flesh which is a little sweet and with a faint flavour.

Hoary Morning.name: Hoary Morning
Hoary Morning.description: Thought to have been raised in Somerset, England. It was first recorded in 1819. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, dry flesh which is not particularly acid and with no flavour.

Hocking's Green.name: Hocking's Green
Hocking's Green.description: Raised at Illand Farm, Coads Green, near Callington, Cornwall. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1984. Fruits have firm, sharp flesh.

Hodge's Seedling.name: Hodge's Seedling
Hodge's Seedling.description: Originated in the West of England. It was known in 1876. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Hog's Snout.name: Hog's Snout
Hog's Snout.description: Originated in the UK. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947. Fruits have soft, creamy white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Holiday.name: Holiday
Holiday.description: Raised in 1940 by F.S. Howlett at Ohio Agricultural Experiment Station, Wooster, Ohio, USA. It was named and introduced in 1964. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a slight vinous flavour.

Holland Pippin.name: Holland Pippin
Holland Pippin.description: Originated in Holland, Lincolnshire, England. It was recorded in 1729. Fruits have soft, coarse, mealy flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Hollandbury.name: Hollandbury
Hollandbury.description: Originated in England. It was recorded in 1799. Fruits have soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Holstein.name: Holstein
Holstein.description: Triploid. Raised or discovered by Vahldik, a teacher in Eutin, Holstein, Germany in about 1918. Fruits have firm, slightly coarse-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a little acidity and a rich aromatic flavour.

Honey Pippin.name: Honey Pippin
Honey Pippin.description: Raised by J. Brooke, Newmarket, Suffolk, England. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1981. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Honeygold.name: Honeygold
Honeygold.description: Raised in 1935 at the University of Minnesota, Horticultural Research Centre. It was introduced in 1969. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Hood's Supreme.name: Hood's Supreme
Hood's Supreme.description: Raised in 1924 by Miss B.Y. Hood at Duriehill, Edzell, Angus, Scotland. Fruits have very coarse, soft flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Hope Cottage Seedling.name: Hope Cottage Seedling
Hope Cottage Seedling.description: Raised in 1900 by Mrs Oakey at Hope Cottage, Rochford, Tenbury Wells, Worcestershire. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Horei.name: Horei
Horei.description: Raised in 1931 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Introduced in 1949. Fruits have very firm flesh with a fairly sweet flavour.

Hormead Pearmain.name: Hormead Pearmain
Hormead Pearmain.description: Thought to have been raised at Hormead, Hertfordshire, England. It was first recorded in1826. Fruits have moderately firm, slightly coarse-textured flesh which is juicy and very acid. No distinctive flavour.

Horneburger Pfannkuchen.name: Horneburger Pfannkuchen
Horneburger Pfannkuchen.description: Triploid. Originated in Germany. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have fairly soft, coarse-textured acid flesh. Cooks quite well.

Horsford Prolific.name: Horsford Prolific
Horsford Prolific.description: Thought to have originated in about 1900. It was found in 1913 in a garden at Horsford, Norwich. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet flavour.

Horskreiger.name: Horskreiger
Horskreiger.description: Origin unknown but recorded in 1831. Fruits have tender, crisp, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Houblon.name: Houblon
Houblon.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Welford Park, Newbury, Berkshire, England. First recorded in 1901 when it received an Award of Merit from the RHS. Fruits have firm, slightly coarse-textured, moderately juicy flesh which is a little acid with a good aromatic, slightly aniseed flavour.

Hounslow Wonder.name: Hounslow Wonder
Hounslow Wonder.description: Introduced by Spooner, nurseryman of Hounslow, Middlesex. It was recorded in 1910 when it also received an Award of Merit from the RHS. Fruits have fine, firm, crisp flesh with an acid flavour.

Howgate Wonder.name: Howgate Wonder
Howgate Wonder.description: Raised in 1915-16 by G. Wratton at Howgate Lane, Bembridge, Isle of Wight. It was introduced in 1932 by Stuart Low Co. Received an Award of merit from the RHS in 1929. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh which is quite sweet when ripe with a faint aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

Hubbard's Pearmain.name: Hubbard's Pearmain
Hubbard's Pearmain.description: Originated in Norfolk, England. It was known before 1800. Fruits have coarse, soft, dry flesh with a slightly sweet and rich flavour.

Hubbardston Nonsuch.name: Hubbardston Nonsuch
Hubbardston Nonsuch.description: Originated in Hubbardston, Massachusetts, USA. It was first recorded in 1832. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Hume.name: Hume
Hume.description: Raised in 1898 at the Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It was selected in 1916 and introduced in 1921. Fruits have soft, white tinged pink flesh with a sweet flavour.

Hunt's Duke of Gloucester.name: Hunt's Duke of Gloucester
Hunt's Duke of Gloucester.description: Raised by Dr Fry at Gloucester. It was introduced in 1820 by Thomas Hunt of Stratford-on-Avon. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a slightly subacid and nutty flavour.

Hunt's Early.name: Hunt's Early
Hunt's Early.description: Originated in the UK. It was described in 1884. Fruits have firm, coarse, crisp flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Hunter Melba.name: Hunter Melba
Hunter Melba.description: A tetraploid form of Melba. Fruits have fairly firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a refreshing vinous flavour.

Hunter Ottawa.name: Hunter Ottawa
Hunter Ottawa.description: A tetraploid form of Ottawa. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1977 from Canada.

Hunter Sandow.name: Hunter Sandow
Hunter Sandow.description: A tetraploid form of Sandow. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, tender flesh with a sweet to fairly acid flavour.

Hunter Spartan.name: Hunter Spartan
Hunter Spartan.description: A tetraploid form of Spartan. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a refreshing vinous flavour.

Hunter's Majestic.name: Hunter's Majestic
Hunter's Majestic.description: Raised before 1914 by Miss E. Balding at Upwell, Wisbech, Cambridgeshire. It was introduced in about 1928 by W. Hunter of Wisbech. Fruits have softish, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Huntingdon Codlin.name: Huntingdon Codlin
Huntingdon Codlin.description: Introduced by Wood and Ingram of Huntingdon, England. It was described in 1883. Fruits have tender flesh with a subacid and perfumed flavour.

I.B. Reid.name: I.B. Reid
I.B. Reid.description: Said to have originated at Hutton near Lancaster, England. It was described in 1851. Fruits have firm, crisp, white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Idagold.name: Idagold
Idagold.description: Raised by Leif Verner, Idaho Agricultural Experiment Station, Moscow, Idaho, USA. It was selected in 1939 and introduced in 1944. Fruits have fine, soft flesh with a subacid flavour.

Idaho Delicious.name: Idaho Delicious
Idaho Delicious.description: A tetraploid form of Delicious. Received by the National Fruit Trials from U.S.A. in 1965. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured juicy flesh which is very sweet with a highly aromatic flavour. Very tough skin.

Idajon.name: Idajon
Idajon.description: Raised by Leif Verner at Idaho Agricultural Experiment Station, Moscow, Idaho, USA. It was introduced in 1949. Fruits have fine, crisp, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Idared.name: Idared
Idared.description: Raised by Leif Verner at Idaho Agricultural Experiment Station, Moscow, Idaho, USA. It was introduced in 1942. Fruits have white, tinged green, firm, crisp, fine-textured flesh with a sweet and pleasant vinous flavour.

Iduna.name: Iduna
Iduna.description: Raised at the Federal Agricultural Research Station, Wadenswil, Switzerland. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Ildrod Pigeon.name: Ildrod Pigeon
Ildrod Pigeon.description: Thought to have originated on the Island of Fyn, Denmark. It was known to have been in existence in 1840. Introduced by Mathiesens nursery in about 1873. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine white flesh with a sweet, subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Imperial Gala.name: Imperial Gala
Imperial Gala.description: A much darker red clone of Tenroy. Fruits are very sweet and juicy.

Improved Ashmead's Kernel (of Bunyard).name: Improved Ashmead's Kernel (of Bunyard)
Improved Ashmead's Kernel (of Bunyard).description: First recorded in 1883. It was awarded the Award of Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1892. Fruits have firm, pale yellow flesh with a pleasant subacid flavour.

Improved Cockpit.name: Improved Cockpit
Improved Cockpit.description: A larger form of Cockpit, first recorded in 1902. Fruits have fairly soft, coarse flesh with a subacid and a little sweet, insipid flavour.

Indo.name: Indo
Indo.description: Originated in Japan. It was recorded in 1930. Fruits have firm, greenish yellow flesh which is very sweet.

Ingall's Pippin.name: Ingall's Pippin
Ingall's Pippin.description: Raised in 1915 by William Ingall at Grimoldby, Lincolnshire. It was introduced in 1928. Fruits have soft, loose, white flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Ingall's Red.name: Ingall's Red
Ingall's Red.description: Raised by William Ingall, Grimoldby, Lincolnshire. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1930. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish-white flesh with a sweet and slightly aromatic flavour.

Ingol.name: Ingol
Ingol.description: Raised in 1954 at Jork Fruit Research Station, Hamburg, Germany. Fruits have soft but juicy flesh with a good rich flavour.

Ingrid Marie.name: Ingrid Marie
Ingrid Marie.description: Raised on the island of Fyn, Denmark in about 1910. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a fair flavour. Cracks around the eye in some seasons.

Irish Peach.name: Irish Peach
Irish Peach.description: Raised in Ireland, possibly in Sligo. It was introduced to England in 1820. Fruits have white, moderately firm, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Iron Pin.name: Iron Pin
Iron Pin.description: Thought to have originated in Dorset, England. It was described in 1884. Fruits have firm, tender, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Isaac Newton's Tree.name: Isaac Newton's Tree
Isaac Newton's Tree.description: Originated from a tree growing in Isaac Newton's garden at Woolsthorpe Manor, near Grantham, Lincs in 1660. It appears identical to Flower of Kent. Fruits have soft, coarse-textured flesh with a subacid flavour. A very shy cropper.

Ivette.name: Ivette
Ivette.description: Raised in 1950 by A.A. Schaap at the Institute of Horticultural Plant Breeding, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Introduced in 1966. Fruits are crisp, sweet, subacid with an aromatic flavour

Ivo.name: Ivo
Ivo.description: Originated in America. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1952. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a sweet and aromatic flavour. Flesh tends to brown rapidly when cut.

Jacques Lebel.name: Jacques Lebel
Jacques Lebel.description: Raised in about 1825 by Jacques Lebel at Amiens, France. Fruits are crisp, juicy and acid.

Jacquet.name: Jacquet
Jacquet.description: Originated from Indre, France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have tender flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Jacquin.name: Jacquin
Jacquin.description: Raised by Boisbunel, France. Recorded in 1872. Received a First Class Certificate from the RHS in 1893. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a moderately sweet flavour.

Jafra.name: Jafra
Jafra.description: Found in 1971 by P. van Dueren den Hollander, The Netherlands. Fruits have juicy flesh with a rich flavour.

Jamba 69.name: Jamba 69
Jamba 69.description: Raised in 1954 by Dr E. Loewel, Jork, Hamburg, Germany. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a reasonable flavour.

James Grieve.name: James Grieve
James Grieve.description: Raised by James Grieve in Edinburgh, Scotland and introduced by his employers, Dickson's nurserymen. It was first recorded in 1893. Received Award of Merit in 1897 and First Class Certificate in 1906 from RHS. Fruits have rather soft but very juicy flesh with a good refreshing flavour.

James Grieve Lired.name: James Grieve Lired
James Grieve Lired.description: A sport of James Grieve having a brighter, more solid flush. It originated with A van Liere en Zonen, Kapelle-Biezalinge. Fruits have rather soft but juicy flesh with a good refreshing flavour.

James Lawson.name: James Lawson
James Lawson.description: Exhibited in 1918 by Cannell of Eynsford, Kent. Received an Award of Merit from RHS in 1918. Fruits have fairly coarse flesh with a subacid to slightly sweet flavour.

Jan Steen.name: Jan Steen
Jan Steen.description: Raised at the Plant Breeding Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1955. Fruits have fairly crisp, fine flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Jansen von Welten.name: Jansen von Welten
Jansen von Welten.description: Raised by Jansen at Welten, near Aachen, Germany. Fruit was received by Diel, a German pomologist in 1823. Fruits have fairly firm, fine flesh with a sweet, aromatic, nutty flavour.

Jaszvadoka.name: Jaszvadoka
Jaszvadoka.description: Originated in Hungary. Referred to as old in 1909. Fruits have firm, sweet, dry flesh.

Jean Tondeur.name: Jean Tondeur
Jean Tondeur.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have soft, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Jeanne Hardy.name: Jeanne Hardy
Jeanne Hardy.description: Raised in 1878 by M. Hardy at the School of Horticulture, Versailles, France and named after Jeanne Hardy, his daughter. Fruits have soft, juicy, sweet flesh with no particular flavour.

Jefferis.name: Jefferis
Jefferis.description: Originated in about 1830 with Isaac Jefferies, Newlintownship, Chester County, Pennsylvania, USA and named by Pennsylvania Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid to slightly sweet flavour.

Jennifer.name: Jennifer
Jennifer.description: Raised by F.W. Wastie at Eynsham, Oxford. Fruits have firm, chewy flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Jennifer Wastie.name: Jennifer Wastie
Jennifer Wastie.description: Raised by F.W. Wastie at Eynsham, Oxford. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have firm, chewy flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Jersey Black.name: Jersey Black
Jersey Black.description: Thought to have originated in New Jersey, USA. It was recorded in 1817. Fruits have crisp, rather coarse flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Jerseymac.name: Jerseymac
Jerseymac.description: Raised in 1956 at Rutgers University, New Brunswick, New Jersey, USA. Introduced in 1972. Fruits have tender, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour similar to McIntosh.

Jester.name: Jester
Jester.description: Raised in 1966 by Dr F.H. Alston, East Malling Research Station, Kent. Introduced in 1981. Fruits are crisp and juicy with good texture and flavour.

Jewett's Fine Red.name: Jewett's Fine Red
Jewett's Fine Red.description: Said to have originated in Hollis, New Hampshire, USA. First recorded in 1842. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Jim-Brian.name: Jim-Brian
Jim-Brian.description: Originated in South Africa. Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1995. Fruits have crisp, firm flesh with a sharp flavour similar to Granny Smith.

Joaneting.name: Joaneting
Joaneting.description: Thought to be of English origin. Known before 1600. Fruits have crisp, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

John Divers.name: John Divers
John Divers.description: Raised in 1905 possibly by nurseryman W.H. Divers, Surbiton, Surrey. Fruits have firm, fine, fairly tender flesh with a somewhat acid flavour.

John Huggett.name: John Huggett
John Huggett.description: Raised in 1940 by John Huggett, Grange-over-Sands, Lancashire. Fruits have fairly firm flesh with a sweet and aromatic flavour.

John Standish.name: John Standish
John Standish.description: Believed to have been raised by John Standish at Ascot, Berkshire, England in about 1873. Introduced by Isaac House in 1921. It was Highly Commended by the RHS in 1921 and received an Award of Merit in 1922. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured juicy flesh which is moderately acid and refreshing.

John Waterer.name: John Waterer
John Waterer.description: Introduced in 1920 by Waterer Sons & Crisp, Twyford, Berkshire. Fruits have fairly firm, fine, tender flesh with a subacid and insipid flavour.

Johnson McIntosh.name: Johnson McIntosh
Johnson McIntosh.description: A tetraploid form of McIntosh. Fruits have white, rather soft, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant vinous flavour.

Jomured.name: Jomured
Jomured.description: A darker flushed, non-striped clone of Jonagold. Received by the National Fruit Collection, Brogdale in 1989 from nurseryman J. Nicolai, Belgium. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Jonadel.name: Jonadel
Jonadel.description: Raised in 1923 by H.L. Lantz, Iowa Agricultural Experiment Station, Ames, Iowa, USA. It was introduced in 1958. Fruits have firm, tender, fine yellowish flesh with a sweet subacid and slightly rich flavour.

Jonafree.name: Jonafree
Jonafree.description: Complex parentage which includes Crandall's Rome X M. floribunda, Jonathan, Gallia Beauty, Red Spy and Golden Delicious. Raised in 1965 by Rutgers, Purdue and Illinois universities, USA. Introduced in 1979. Fruits are crisp and juicy. Scab resistant.

Jonagold.name: Jonagold
Jonagold.description: Triploid.Raised in 1943 at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, USA. It was introduced in 1968. Fruits have creamy white, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good rich flavour.

Jonagold Boerekamp.name: Jonagold Boerekamp
Jonagold Boerekamp.description: A darker red and earlier ripening clone of Jonagold. Received by Brogdale in 1993 from the Netherlands. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Jonagored.name: Jonagored
Jonagored.description: A more highly coloured sport of Jonagold. Originated at Halen, Belgium, by Jos Morren. It was introduced in 1985. Fruits have creamy white, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good rich flavour.

Jonagored Supra.name: Jonagored Supra
Jonagored Supra.description: A clone of Jonagored. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Jonalicious.name: Jonalicious
Jonalicious.description: A chance seedling discovered in 1933 by Anna Morris Daniels in Abilene, Texas, USA. It was introduced in 1960 by Stark Bros. Nurseries, Louisiana, Missouri. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Jonamac.name: Jonamac
Jonamac.description: Raised in 1944 by Roger D. Way, New York State Agricultural Experiment Station. It was introduced in 1972. Fruits have white, semi firm flesh with a good flavour.

Jonared.name: Jonared
Jonared.description: A more highly coloured sport of Jonathan. It was discovered in 1930 by William Uecher at Peshastin, Washington,USA and introduced in 1934. Fruits have soft, fine-textured, fairly juicy flesh with a sweet and faintly pleasant flavour.

Jonathan.name: Jonathan
Jonathan.description: Originated on the farm of Philip Rick, Woodstock, Ulster County, New York, USA. It was first described in 1826 by Judge Buel who named the apple after Jonathan Hasbrouck. Fruits have soft, fine-textured, fairly juicy flesh with a sweet and fairly pleasant flavour.

Jongrimes.name: Jongrimes
Jongrimes.description: Raised by Roland S. Rogers, Bloomfield, Indiana, USA. It was introduced in the 1920s. Fruits have cream, sweet flesh.

Jonica.name: Jonica
Jonica.description: A red fruited mutation of Jonagold. It originated in Germany. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Jorayca.name: Jorayca
Jorayca.description: A red flushed, earlier ripening clone of Jonagold. Received by Brogdale from C. Carolus, Belgium in 1996. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Jored.name: Jored
Jored.description: A red fruited mutation of Jonagold having 80-90% red blush colour. It was discovered in 1985 by Johann Nicholai, St Truiden, Belgium. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

Josegold.name: Josegold
Josegold.description: A clone of Jonagold. Originated in the Netherlands.

Joseph Musch.name: Joseph Musch
Joseph Musch.description: Originally found by Joseph Musch, Belgium. Recorded in 1872. Fruits are sweet to eat and also cook well. Good resistance to scab and mildew.

Josephine Kreuter.name: Josephine Kreuter
Josephine Kreuter.description: Originated in Saint-Florian, Austria. It was first described in 1889. Fruits have rather dry flesh with a subacid flavour.

Joybells.name: Joybells
Joybells.description: Raised by Will Tayler at Godalming, Surrey. Records show that trees were grafted in about 1914. It received an Award of Merit from the RHS in 1922. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Joyce.name: Joyce
Joyce.description: Raised in 1898 at the Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It was introduced in 1924. Fruits have soft, coarse, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Jubile.name: Jubile
Jubile.description: Registered name is Delbard Jubile. Raised in 1962 by Delbard Nurseries, France. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a light aromatic flavour.

Jubile d'Argovie.name: Jubile d'Argovie
Jubile d'Argovie.description: Originated in Switzerland. It was described in 1934. Fruits have tender, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Julgrans.name: Julgrans
Julgrans.description: Thought to have originated in Sweden. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1921. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid to acid flavour.

Julyred.name: Julyred
Julyred.description: Raised by G.W. Schneider at New Jersey Agricultural Experiment Station, New Brunswick, USA. Fruits have soft, white, juicy flesh with a vinous flavour.

Jumbo Ohrin.name: Jumbo Ohrin
Jumbo Ohrin.description: Raised in 1985 by Mr Sukekuro Taninai, Nakajima Tenkohen Fruit Nurseries, Japan. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

June Crewdson.name: June Crewdson
June Crewdson.description: Originated with Bernard Crewdson, Limpsfield, Sussex. It first fruited in 1943. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp flesh with a sweet flavour.

Juno.name: Juno
Juno.description: Raised in Germany at the Institute of Agriculture and Horticulture. Introduced in 1971. Fruits have a slightly acid flavour.

Jupiter.name: Jupiter
Jupiter.description: Triploid. Raised in 1966 at East Malling Research Station, Kent. It was introduced in 1981. Fruits are sweet and juicy with a good texture and Cox-like flavour.

Kaiser Franz Joseph.name: Kaiser Franz Joseph
Kaiser Franz Joseph.description: Thought to have originated in Germany. It was known before 1876. Fruits have tender, fine, whitish flesh with a sweet, vinous, aromatic flavour.

Kaiser Wilhelm.name: Kaiser Wilhelm
Kaiser Wilhelm.description: Discovered in about 1800 by Head Teacher Hesselman in Witzhelden, Kreis Solingen, Germany. Introduced by the mid 1800s. Fruits have crisp, fine flesh with a subacid, sweet and spicy flavour.

Kalco.name: Kalco
Kalco.description: Raised at the former Kaiser-Wilhelm Institut, Muncheberg, Germany. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1967. Fruits have a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Kandil Sinap.name: Kandil Sinap
Kandil Sinap.description: Thought to have originated in the early 1800s at Crimea, Russia. Fruits have crisp, snow-white flesh with a sweet, slightly vinous and perfumed flavour.

Kapai Red Jonathan.name: Kapai Red Jonathan
Kapai Red Jonathan.description: A more highly coloured sport of Jonathan. Discovered in 1929 by A. Tomlinson in Frimley, Hastings, Hawkes Bay, New Zealand. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Karmen.name: Karmen
Karmen.description: Originated in Czechoslovakia. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a good but rather acid flavour.

Karmijn de Sonnaville.name: Karmijn de Sonnaville
Karmijn de Sonnaville.description: Raised in 1949 by P. de Sonnaville at IVT, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was introduced in 1971. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Katja.name: Katja
Katja.description: Raised in 1947 at Balsgard Fruit Breeding Institute, Sweden. It was introduced in 1966. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a pleasant flavour.

Kemp.name: Kemp
Kemp.description: Originated in Ireland, possibly Ulster. It was known in 1837. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Kendall.name: Kendall
Kendall.description: Raised in 1912 at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, by Richard Wellington. It was introduced in 1932. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Kenneth.name: Kenneth
Kenneth.description: Raised in 1920 by Kenneth McCreadie at Rhyl, Wales. Fruits have somewhat coarse, soft flesh with a subacid and sweet flavour.

Kentish Fillbasket.name: Kentish Fillbasket
Kentish Fillbasket.description: Thought to have originated in Kent, England. It was known before 1820. Fruits have tender, greenish-white, acid flesh.

Kentucky Red Streak.name: Kentucky Red Streak
