Kentucky Red Streak.description: Originated in USA. It was known before 1864. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Kerry Pippin.name: Kerry Pippin
Kerry Pippin.description: Originated in Ireland. It was first recorded in 1802. Fruits have firm, crisp but rather dry flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Keswick Codlin.name: Keswick Codlin
Keswick Codlin.description: Found growing on a heap of rubbish at Gleaston Castle near Ulverston, Lancashire, England. It was recorded in 1793. Introduced by nurseryman John Sander at Keswick, Cumbria, England. Fruits have soft, rather coarse-textured, somewhat dry and acid flesh.

Khoroshavka alaya.name: Khoroshavka alaya
Khoroshavka alaya.description: Originated in Russia. It was known in 1892. Fruits have fine, crisp, pinkish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Kidd's Orange Red.name: Kidd's Orange Red
Kidd's Orange Red.description: Raised in 1924 at Greytown, Wairarapa, New Zealand by J.H.Kidd. It was introduced to the UK in about 1932. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy, sweet flesh with a rich aromatic flavour.

Kilkenny Pearmain.name: Kilkenny Pearmain
Kilkenny Pearmain.description: Originated in Ireland. It was recorded in 1831. Fruits have fine, tender, dry flesh with a sweet flavour.

Kim.name: Kim
Kim.description: Raised by P. Bergendal in 1946 at Agricultural College, Balsgard, Sweden. It was introduced in the late 1970s. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a sweet and acid flavour.

Kimball McIntosh.name: Kimball McIntosh
Kimball McIntosh.description: A larger fruited sport of McIntosh. Discovered in 1948 in Littleton, Massachusetts, USA by R. Kimball. Fruits have rather soft, fine-textured,very juicy flesh with a sweet and vinous flavour.

King Charles Pearmain.name: King Charles Pearmain
King Charles Pearmain.description: Originally received by Hogg in 1876 from nurseryman John Smith of Worcester. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet and rich flavour.

King Cole.name: King Cole
King Cole.description: Raised by R.G. Cole at Lang Lang, Victoria, Australia. It was first exhibited in 1912. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

King Cox.name: King Cox
King Cox.description: A more striped form of Cox's Orange Pippin. It was discovered by R.W. Giles at Perryfields, Bromsgrove, Worcestershire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1959. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a rich aromatic, nutty flavour.

King David.name: King David
King David.description: Discovered in 1893 in a hedgerow in Washington County, Arkansas, USA. It was introduced in 1902 by stark bros., Louisiana, USA. Fruits have rather coarse flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

King George V.name: King George V
King George V.description: Raised in about 1898 by Lady Thorncroft at Bembridge, Isle of Wight, England. It was introduced by J. Cheal & Sons, nurserymen, Crawley, Sussex. Received Award of Merit from RHS in 1928. Fruits have crisp, fine-textured, moderately juicy flesh with a subacid and good aromatic flavour.

King Jonagold.name: King Jonagold
King Jonagold.description: An even red flushed clone of Jonagold. Discovered in 1985 by nurseryman J. Nicolai, Belgium. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good rich flavour.

King of the Pippins.name: King of the Pippins
King of the Pippins.description: Origin confused but is identical to Reine des Reinettes grown in France. Introduced by Kirke of Brompton as King of the Pippins, but prior name appears to have been Golden Winter Pearmain. First recorded in 1800. Fruits are firm, juicy and subacid with a

King of Tompkins County.name: King of Tompkins County
King of Tompkins County.description: Triploid. Thought to have been raised near Washington, Warren County, New Jersey, USA. Brought to Tompkins County, New York in 1804 by Jacob Wycoff who named it King. It was renamed King of Tompkins County in about 1855. Fruits have somewhat soft, slightly juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

King Russet.name: King Russet
King Russet.description: A russetted form of King of the Pippins. It was discovered in the late 1950s at Rookery Farm, Bordon, Hampshire, England. Fruits have dry, quite sharp flesh with a distinct russet flavour.

King's Acre Bountiful.name: King's Acre Bountiful
King's Acre Bountiful.description: Introduced in 1904 by King's Acre Nurseries, Hereford. Received Award of merit from RHS in 1904. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh.

King's Acre Pippin.name: King's Acre Pippin
King's Acre Pippin.description: First recorded in 1897. Introduced by King's Acre Nurseries, Hereford in 1899. Received Award of Merit from RHS in 1897. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a rich aromatic flavour.

Kingston Black.name: Kingston Black
Kingston Black.description: Believed to be a Somerset apple and possibly raised at Kingston, near Taunton. This variety was introduced into Herefordshire c.1820 by Mr Palmer of Bollitree Estate, Weston-under-Penyard near Ross-on-Wye. Trees are of medium size and have a spreading habit. Susceptible to scab. Fruits are medium to small in size and produce a full bodied, excellent quality cider with a distinctive flavour.

Kinkead Red Spy.name: Kinkead Red Spy
Kinkead Red Spy.description: A more highly coloured sport of Northern Spy. It was received by the National Fruit Trials via Scotland from the Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Fruits have fairly firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Kinrei.name: Kinrei
Kinrei.description: Raised in 1932 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a moderately sweet flavour.

Kirke's Lord Nelson.name: Kirke's Lord Nelson
Kirke's Lord Nelson.description: A larger fruited clone of Kentish Fillbasket. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1960 from Australia. Fruits have tender, greenish-white, acid flesh.

Knobby Russet.name: Knobby Russet
Knobby Russet.description: Brought to notice in 1820 by Haslar Capron of Midhurst, Sussex, England. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with a fairly strong flavour.

Konigin Sophiensapfel.name: Konigin Sophiensapfel
Konigin Sophiensapfel.description: Originated in the mid-late 1700s probably in England. It was first distributed by Loddiges as Winter Queen and renamed by German pomologist Diel. Fruits have soft, dry, mealy flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Koningin Juliana.name: Koningin Juliana
Koningin Juliana.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was introduced in 1952. Fruits have firm, medium textured flesh with a subacid flavour.

Korei.name: Korei
Korei.description: Raised in 1935 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1949. Fruits have medium crisp, pale cream flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Korobovka.name: Korobovka
Korobovka.description: Originated in Russia. It was described in 1855. Awarded the Award of Merit from the RHS in 1896 under its synonym name 'Cardinal'. Fruits have soft, white flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Kortegaard Cox.name: Kortegaard Cox
Kortegaard Cox.description: A sport of Cox's Orange Pippin having no stripes. It was discovered in 1914 at Kortegard, Denmark by Otto Stowo. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a rich, aromatic, nutty flavour.

Kougetsu.name: Kougetsu
Kougetsu.description: Raised at Aomori Apple Experimental Station, Japan. Fruits have coarse cream flesh.

Krasnyi Shtandart.name: Krasnyi Shtandart
Krasnyi Shtandart.description: Raised in 1915 by I.V. Michurin at Michurinsk, Russia. Very attractive tree with red leaves, bark and blossom. The small dark red fruits have pink, sharp flesh.

Kronprinz Rudolf.name: Kronprinz Rudolf
Kronprinz Rudolf.description: Originated with I. Klochner, Steiermark, Austria from seed sown in 1863. Fruits have fine, soft flesh with a sweet subacid and perfumed flavour.

Kyokko.name: Kyokko
Kyokko.description: Raised in 1931 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits have fine, soft flesh with a sweet almost insipid flavour.

la Nationale.name: la Nationale
la Nationale.description: Raised by M. Roux at Sainte-Romain-au-Mont d'Or, Rhone, France. It first fruited in 1871. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh.

Lady Henniker.name: Lady Henniker
Lady Henniker.description: Raised by John Perkins, gardener to Lord Henniker, from a pip found in cider must at Thornham hall, Eye, Suffolk between 1840 and 1850. Introduced in 1873. It received a First Class Certificate from the RHS in 1873. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, rather dry flesh with a fairly acid but fair flavour.

Lady Hollendale.name: Lady Hollendale
Lady Hollendale.description: Originated in East Anglia. It was recorded in 1918. Fruits have rather tough flesh with a sharp flavour.

Lady Isabel.name: Lady Isabel
Lady Isabel.description: Found in 1939 by Mrs Reading at Guildford, Surrey. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lady Lambourne.name: Lady Lambourne
Lady Lambourne.description: A sport of Lord Lambourne claiming to have a much brighter colour. Found in about 1945 at Appleby Fruit Farm, Kingston Bagpuize, Berkshire. Fruits are juicy and sweet with a good aromatic flavour.

Lady of the Wemyss.name: Lady of the Wemyss
Lady of the Wemyss.description: Originated from Scotland. It was recorded in 1831. Fruits have hard, fine flesh with an acid flavour.

Lady Sudeley.name: Lady Sudeley
Lady Sudeley.description: Raised in about 1849 by a cottager called Jacob at Petworth, Sussex. Introduced in 1885 by G. Bunyard & Co., Maidstone, Kent. It received an Award of Merit from the RHS in 1884. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh which is a little acid and with good flavour.

Lady Williams.name: Lady Williams
Lady Williams.description: Originated as a chance seedling in Donnybrook, Western Australia, in about 1935. Parents unknown but thought to be Granny Smith and Jonathan. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh. It rarely reaches maturity in the UK.

Lady's Delight.name: Lady's Delight
Lady's Delight.description: Originated in England. It was first described in 1851. Fruits have crisp flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Lady's Finger of Offaly.name: Lady's Finger of Offaly
Lady's Finger of Offaly.description: Originated from Ireland. It was described in 1851. Fruits have softish flesh with some flavour.

Lake's Kernel.name: Lake's Kernel
Lake's Kernel.description: Brought to Ashleworth, Gloucestershire, England by Mr Lake. It was first exhibited in 1905. Fruits have firm flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lakeland.name: Lakeland
Lakeland.description: Raised at the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm, Excelsior. It was introduced in 1950. Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh.

Lamb Abbey Pearmain.name: Lamb Abbey Pearmain
Lamb Abbey Pearmain.description: Raised in 1804 by Mrs Mary Anne Malcolm at Lamb Abbey, Dartford, Kent. It received the Award of Merit from the RHS in 1901. Fruits have firm, pale yellow, sugary and rich flesh.

Lamb's Seedling.name: Lamb's Seedling
Lamb's Seedling.description: Raised 1866-1867 at Meynell Langley, Derby, by Joseph Lamb. Fruits have soft, coarse, slightly acid flesh.

Lancraig.name: Lancraig
Lancraig.description: A coloured clone of Delicious. Fruits have firm, juicy, very sweet flesh with a highly aromatic flavour.

Landsberger Reinette.name: Landsberger Reinette
Landsberger Reinette.description: Raised in about 1840 by Councillor Burchardt, Landsberg/Warthe, Brandenburg, Germany. It was awarded a First Class Certificate from the RHS in 1882. Fruits have soft, fine-textured very juicy flesh with a sweet and refreshing flavour.

Lane's Prince Albert.name: Lane's Prince Albert
Lane's Prince Albert.description: Thought to have been raised in about 1840 by Thomas Squire, Berkhamsted. It was introduced by John Lane in 1850. Received First Class Certificate from RHS in 1872. Fruits are very juicy and acid. Cooks well.

Langley Pippin.name: Langley Pippin
Langley Pippin.description: Raised by Veitch at Chelsea, London. First described in 1898. Introduced by Veitch. It received the Award of Merit from the RHS in 1898. Fruits have rather soft, juicy flesh with a moderate aromatic flavour.

Lappio.name: Lappio
Lappio.description: Thought to have originated in Sicily, Italy. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1958. Fruits have firm, yellowish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lass o' Gowrie.name: Lass o' Gowrie
Lass o' Gowrie.description: Originated from Scotland. It was described in 1883. Fruits have soft flesh with a subacid and sweet flavour.

Lavina.name: Lavina
Lavina.description: A chance seedling grown in the Modenese, Italy. Described in 1949 but thought to be much older. Fruits have firm, whitish flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Lawfam.name: Lawfam
Lawfam.description: Raised in 1898 by Horticulture Division, Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It was introduced in 1922. Fruits have firm, crisp, white flesh with a sweet vinous flavour.

Lawyer Nutmeg.name: Lawyer Nutmeg
Lawyer Nutmeg.description: Originated with David Lawyer, Plains, Montana, U.S.A. Fruits have a rich and definate nutmeg spice flavour.

Laxton's Early Crimson.name: Laxton's Early Crimson
Laxton's Early Crimson.description: Raised in 1908 at Bedford by Laxton Bros. and introduced by them in 1931. Fruits have rather coarse flesh with a sweet flavour.

Laxton's Favourite.name: Laxton's Favourite
Laxton's Favourite.description: Raised in 1925 at Bedford by Laxton Bros. and introduced by them in 1951. Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh.

Laxton's Herald.name: Laxton's Herald
Laxton's Herald.description: Raised in 1906 by Laxton Bros. at Bedford. Fruits have firm, crisp, slightly tough flesh with a fairly sweet flavour.

Laxton's Leader.name: Laxton's Leader
Laxton's Leader.description: Raised in 1905 by Laxton Bros., at Bedford. Fruits have fairly firm, fine flesh with a sweet and slightly acid flavour.

Laxton's Pearmain.name: Laxton's Pearmain
Laxton's Pearmain.description: Raised in 1897 at Bedford by Laxton Bros., and introduced by them in 1922. Received an Award of Merit in 1922 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet and slightly aromatic flavour.

Laxton's Peerless.name: Laxton's Peerless
Laxton's Peerless.description: Raised in 1900 at Bedford by Laxton Bros., and introduced by them in 1922. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1920. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour.

Laxton's Rearguard.name: Laxton's Rearguard
Laxton's Rearguard.description: Raised in 1907 at Bedford by Laxton Bros. Fruits have firm flesh with a slightly aromatic flavour.

Laxton's Reward.name: Laxton's Reward
Laxton's Reward.description: Raised in 1925 at Bedford by Laxton Bros. Fruits have crisp, coarse flesh with a sweet flavour.

Laxton's Royalty.name: Laxton's Royalty
Laxton's Royalty.description: Raised in 1908 at Bedford by Laxton Bros. and introduced by them in 1932. Fruits have hard, crisp flesh with a slightly sweet to subacid flavour.

Laxton's Superb.name: Laxton's Superb
Laxton's Superb.description: Raised in 1897 at Bedford by Laxton Bros., and introduced by them in 1922. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1919 and a First Class Certificate in 1921. Fruits have firm, very juicy flesh with a sweet, pleasant and refreshing flavour. Trees tend to be subject to biennial bearing.

Laxton's Triumph.name: Laxton's Triumph
Laxton's Triumph.description: Raised in 1902 at Bedford by Laxton Bros., and introduced by them in 1930. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid and highly aromatic flavour.

Laxton's Victory.name: Laxton's Victory
Laxton's Victory.description: Raised in 1926 at Bedford by Laxton Bros., and introduced by them in 1945. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Leather Jacket.name: Leather Jacket
Leather Jacket.description: Exhibited in 1883 from Harwich, Essex. Fruits tend to have very greasy skin. Cooks well.

Leathercoat Russet (Brotherston).name: Leathercoat Russet (Brotherston)
Leathercoat Russet (Brotherston).description: A synonym of Royal Russet. Originated in England. It was first recorded in 1597. Fruits have tender, greenish yellow flesh with a sweet-subacid flavour.

Leeder's Perfection.name: Leeder's Perfection
Leeder's Perfection.description: Exhibited in 1919 from Postwick, Norfolk. Fruits are sweet.

Legana.name: Legana
Legana.description: Raised in about 1940 by J. Bulman, Legana, Tasmania, Australia. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Lemon Pippin.name: Lemon Pippin
Lemon Pippin.description: Thought to be English or possibly of Norman origin. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, dry, slightly acid flesh with a faint aromatic flavour.

Leonie de Sonnaville.name: Leonie de Sonnaville
Leonie de Sonnaville.description: Raised by P. de Sonnaville, IVT, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1974. Fruits are sweet and juicy with an aromatic flavour.

Levering Limbertwig.name: Levering Limbertwig
Levering Limbertwig.description: A larger fruited mutation of Limbertwig. Originated in Ararat, Virginia, U.S.A. by S.R. Levering. Fruits have fairly firm flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lewis's Incomparable.name: Lewis's Incomparable
Lewis's Incomparable.description: Believed to have been raised in England. It was known at the end of the 1700s. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, rather dry, subacid flesh with very little flavour.

Liberty.name: Liberty
Liberty.description: Raised at the New York State Agricultural Experimental Station, Geneva, New York, U.S.A. It was introduced in 1978. Fruits have crisp, juicy, slightly coarse textured flesh with a good flavour. Trees are resistant to scab, cedar apple rust, fireblight and powdery mildew.

Lille.name: Lille
Lille.description: Originated in France. Described in 1948. Fruits have fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lily Boxall.name: Lily Boxall
Lily Boxall.description: Raised in 1952 by T.H. Boxall at Bromley, Kent. Fruits have dry, rather soft flesh with an acid flavour.

Limelight.name: Limelight
Limelight.description: Raised by Mr H. Ermen, Faversham, Kent in about 1985. Introduced in 2000. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a fairly sweet and pleasant flavour. Good resistance to scab and mildew.

Limoncella.name: Limoncella
Limoncella.description: First described in 1831. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1973 from Italy. Fruits have tough flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Linda.name: Linda
Linda.description: Raised at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It first fruited in 1908 and introduced in about 1925. Fruits have fairly crisp, tender, white flesh with a sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

Lindel.name: Lindel
Lindel.description: Raised in 1939 at the Smithfield Experimental Farm, Ontario, Canada. It was introduced in 1971. Fruits have juicy, cream-coloured flesh which is slightly coarse but firm in texture. Moderate acidity.

Lipton.name: Lipton
Lipton.description: Raised at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Fruits have creamy white, rather loose textured, moderately juicy, sweet flesh with a fair flavour.

Lobo.name: Lobo
Lobo.description: Raised in 1898 at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It was introduced in Canada in 1910. Fruits have rather soft, fairly fine-textured, juicy flesh with a pleasant vinous flavour.

Loddington.name: Loddington
Loddington.description: Said to have been brought by a niece of Robert Stone from Bath to Loddington, near Maidstone, Kent in about 1820. It was distributed by Robert Stone. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1877. Fruits have soft, a little coarse textured, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour.

Lodgemore Nonpareil.name: Lodgemore Nonpareil
Lodgemore Nonpareil.description: Raised in about 1808 by Mr Cook of Lodgemore, Stroud, England. It was introduced by Clissold. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Lodi.name: Lodi
Lodi.description: Raised in 1911 by R. Wellington at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, U.S.A. It was introduced in 1924. Fruits have soft, loose-textured, slightly juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks quite well.

Lombarts Calville.name: Lombarts Calville
Lombarts Calville.description: Raised in 1906 by P. Lombarts, Zundert, The Netherlands. It was introduced by the Lombarts family in 1911. Fruits have firm, fairly coarse, soft flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

London Pearmain.name: London Pearmain
London Pearmain.description: Known to have been in existence in 1842. Fruits have crisp, tender flesh with a rich, acid flavour.

London Pippin.name: London Pippin
London Pippin.description: Originated in either Essex or Norfolk. It was recorded in 1580. Fruits have crisp, white, acid flesh.

Longstart.name: Longstart
Longstart.description: Originated in Westmorland, England. It was described in 1851. Fruits have tender, white flesh which browns quickly when cut. Flavour is subacid.

Loop Spy.name: Loop Spy
Loop Spy.description: A tetraploid bud mutation of Northern Spy. It was discovered in 1925 in an orchard of A.I. Loop, North East, Pennsylvania, U.S.A. Fruits are larger, softer and more subject to bitter pit than its parent.

Loop Wealthy.name: Loop Wealthy
Loop Wealthy.description: A tetraploid bud sport of Wealthy producing larger fruits. Originated in the orchard of G.C. Smith & Sons, Pennsylvania, U.S.A. The parent tree was planted in about 1909 and acquired in 1947 by New York Agricultural Experiment Station. Fruits have rather soft but juicy flesh with a sweet and faint vinous flavour.

Lord Burghley.name: Lord Burghley
Lord Burghley.description: Raised at Burghley, Stamford, Lincolnshire. First fruited in 1834. It was introduced by Matheson, gardener in 1865 and distributed by the House of Peterborough. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1865. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a sweet and rich aromatic flavour.

Lord Clyde.name: Lord Clyde
Lord Clyde.description: Raised by B.W. Witham, Reddish, Stockport, Cheshire. It was catalogued in 1866. Fruits have soft, fine, greenish-white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Lord Derby.name: Lord Derby
Lord Derby.description: Raised by Witham, Stockport, Cheshire. It was first recorded in 1862. Fruits are rather coarse textured, somewhat dry with a subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Lord Derby Spur Type.name: Lord Derby Spur Type
Lord Derby Spur Type.description: Originated at the Hilltop Fruit Farm, Ledbury, Herefordshire on trees planted in 1968. Trees are of a spur type habit. Fruits are rather coarse-textured, somewhat dry and with a subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Lord Grosvenor.name: Lord Grosvenor
Lord Grosvenor.description: The origin of this apple is unknown but it was believed to be new in 1872. Fruits have soft, white, juicy and acid flesh. Cooks well.

Lord Hindlip.name: Lord Hindlip
Lord Hindlip.description: Raised in Worcestershire, England. It was first recorded in 1896 and was introduced by Watkins of Hereford. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1896 and a First Class Certificate in 1898. Fruits have fairly firm, very fine-textured, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Lord Lambourne.name: Lord Lambourne
Lord Lambourne.description: Raised in 1907 by Laxton Bros. Ltd. at Bedford, England and introduced by them in 1923. It received the Bunyard Cup from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1921 and an Award of Merit in 1923. Fruits have slightly coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Lord Rosebery.name: Lord Rosebery
Lord Rosebery.description: Said to have been raised by Storrie of Glencarse, Scotland. It was described in 1934. Fruits have crisp, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Lord Stradbroke.name: Lord Stradbroke
Lord Stradbroke.description: Originally found at Henham Hall, Suffolk, England in about 1900. It was awarded the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1905. Fruits have rather hard, tough, greenish-white flesh with an acid flavour.

Lord Suffield.name: Lord Suffield
Lord Suffield.description: Raised by Thomas Thorpe, a Weaver, from Middleton, near Manchester, England. It was first distributed in about 1836. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with an acid flavour. Cooks well, breaking up completely.

Louiton.name: Louiton
Louiton.description: Originated in France. It was described in 1947. Fruits have firm flesh with a fairly sweet and subacid flavour.

Lovacka Reneta.name: Lovacka Reneta
Lovacka Reneta.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials from Scotland. It first fruited in Scotland in 1961. Fruits have very little flavour.

Love Beauty.name: Love Beauty
Love Beauty.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials from Scotland. It first fruited in Scotland in 1962. Fruits have very little flavour.

Lowland Raspberry.name: Lowland Raspberry
Lowland Raspberry.description: Originated in Russia. It was recorded before 1870. Fruits have fine, tender, white tinged red flesh, with a sweet to subacid, perfumed flavour.

Lucombe's Pine.name: Lucombe's Pine
Lucombe's Pine.description: Raised in about 1800 by Lucombe, Pince & Co., Exeter. Fruits have tender, yellowish white flesh with a rich, aromatic, pineapple-like flavour.

Lucombe's Seedling.name: Lucombe's Seedling
Lucombe's Seedling.description: Raised by Lucombe, Pince & Co., Exeter. It was described in 1831. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a subacid and spicy flavour.

Lucullus.name: Lucullus
Lucullus.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was introduced in 1955. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Lundbytorp.name: Lundbytorp
Lundbytorp.description: A chance seedling grown in a garden in Lundbytorp, Denmark. It was described in 1913. Fruits have fine, fairly soft, cream flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Luntersche Pippeling.name: Luntersche Pippeling
Luntersche Pippeling.description: Originated in either The Netherlands or Belgium. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947. Fruits have firm, hard, tough flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Luxemburger Renette.name: Luxemburger Renette
Luxemburger Renette.description: Originated in Luxemburg. It was recorded in 1856. Fruits have fine, fairly firm, greenish or yellowish white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Lynn's Pippin.name: Lynn's Pippin
Lynn's Pippin.description: Raised in 1942 by William Lynn, Emneth, Cambridgeshire, England. It was named in 1953. Fruits have crisp, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Lysgolden.name: Lysgolden
Lysgolden.description: An irradiated mutation of Golden Delicious having some resistance to russet. It was developed at the National Institute of Agricultural Research, Angers, France and was introduced in 1977. Fruits have crisp, sweet, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Mabbott's Pearmain.name: Mabbott's Pearmain
Mabbott's Pearmain.description: Raised in Kent, England. It was first described in 1883. Introduced by Lewis Killick of Langley. Fruits have fairly crisp, a little coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a slightly acid, pleasant aromatic flavour.

Maclean's Favourite.name: Maclean's Favourite
Maclean's Favourite.description: Raised in about 1820 by Dr Allan Maclean of Sudbury, England. Fruits have yellowish flesh with a sweet and rich flavour.

Macoun.name: Macoun
Macoun.description: Raised at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA by Richard Wellington. It was first described in 1918. Introduced in 1923. Fruits have crisp, tender, white flesh with a sweet, scented flavour.

Macross.name: Macross
Macross.description: Raised at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1927. Fruits have fairly firm, coarse, crisp, tender, white tinged pink flesh with a subacid flavour.

Macwood.name: Macwood
Macwood.description: Raised in 1936 at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Fruits have firm, somewhat coarse flesh, with a sweet, perfumed flavour.

Macy.name: Macy
Macy.description: Raised by H.L. Lantz at Iowa Agricultural Experiment Station, Ames, Iowa, USA. It was introduced in the 1920s. Fruits have soft, cream flesh with a subacid to sweet flavour.

Madoue Rouge.name: Madoue Rouge
Madoue Rouge.description: Originated in Nieul (Haute-Vienne), France. Described in 1947. Fruits have tough, yellowish flesh with sweet subacid flavour.

Madresfield Court.name: Madresfield Court
Madresfield Court.description: Thought to have been raised by William Crump. First exhibited in 1915. It was introduced by J. Carless of Worcester, England. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1915. Fruits have firm, a little coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant aromatic flavour. Tends to be a rather shy cropper.

Magdalene.name: Magdalene
Magdalene.description: Found in about 1890 at Magdalen, Norfolk by H. Bridge. Introduced in 1924 by H. Goude. Fruits have fairly firm, fine, cream, slightly tinged green flesh with a sweet and slightly acid flavour.

Maggie Grieve.name: Maggie Grieve
Maggie Grieve.description: Raised at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1928. Fruits have soft but somewhat crisp, pinkish flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Maglemer.name: Maglemer
Maglemer.description: Thought to have originated at Maglemer, near Maribo in Lolland, Denmark. Introduced in about 1870 although known in the second half of the 1700s. Fruits have tender, white flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Magnolia Gold.name: Magnolia Gold
Magnolia Gold.description: Discovered in the 1960s by W.J. Wilson, Magnolia Farms, Fort Valley, Georgia, USA. Introduced in 1970. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Mahe.name: Mahe
Mahe.description: Raised in 1956 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Fruits are sweet with a perfumed flavour.

Maidstone Favourite.name: Maidstone Favourite
Maidstone Favourite.description: Raised by G. Bunyard & Co., Maidstone, Kent. It received an Award of Merit in 1913 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a pleasant distinctive flavour.

Maigold.name: Maigold
Maigold.description: Raised in 1944 at the Swiss Federal Agricultural Research Station, Wadenswil, Switzerland. It was introduced in 1964. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Maldon Wonder.name: Maldon Wonder
Maldon Wonder.description: Raised in about 1900 by A. Mynard at Heybridge, Essex. It was introduced in 1933 by H. Brewer of Maldon. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp, greenish white flesh with an insipid flavour.

Malling Kent.name: Malling Kent
Malling Kent.description: Raised in 1949 by H.M. Tydeman at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits have slightly coarse-textured and fairly juicy flesh with a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Maltster.name: Maltster
Maltster.description: Thought to have originated in England. It was known to be in existence in 1830. Fruits have soft, yellowish flesh with a sweet flavour.

Mandan.name: Mandan
Mandan.description: Raised by William A. Oitto, Northern Great Plains Research Center, Mandan, North Dakota, USA. It was introduced in 1965. Fruits have firm, crisp, very juicy, yellowish flesh with a mildly subacid and good flavour.

Manks Codlin.name: Manks Codlin
Manks Codlin.description: Raised by Mr Kewley at Ballanard, Isle of Man. It first fruited in 1815. Fruits have firm, white, acid flesh.

Mannington's Pearmain.name: Mannington's Pearmain
Mannington's Pearmain.description: Grown from seed found in cider pomace in the garden of Mr Turley, Uckfield, Sussex, England in about 1770. It was introduced by John Mannington in 1847. Fruits have greenish white, firm, fine-textured, moderately juicy flesh with a slightly aromatic flavour.

Mantet.name: Mantet
Mantet.description: Raised at Dominion Experimental Station, Morden, Manitoba, Canada. It was introduced in 1929. Fruits have tender, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

Mareda.name: Mareda
Mareda.description: Raised in 1926 at Scutes Farm near Hastings by A. C. Nash. Fruits have rather soft, creamy white tinged green flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Margaret.name: Margaret
Margaret.description: Originated in England. It was recorded in 1665. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Margaret Taylor.name: Margaret Taylor
Margaret Taylor.description: Found in a garden hedge at Witley, Surrey, England by F.E. Taylor. Exhibited in 1944. Fruits have coarse, rather dry flesh with an insipid flavour.

Margil.name: Margil
Margil.description: Thought to have originated in Europe. It was known in England before 1750. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with a sweet and rich aromatic flavour.

Margol.name: Margol
Margol.description: Originated at Obstbaliverslichsanstalt, Jork, Hannover, Germany.

Mariborka.name: Mariborka
Mariborka.description: Raised at the Institut Za Vocarstvo, Cacak, Yugoslavia. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Marie Doudou.name: Marie Doudou
Marie Doudou.description: Originated in France. Described in 1948. Fruits have fairly tough, white tinged green flesh with a subacid flavour.

Marie-Joseph d'Othee.name: Marie-Joseph d'Othee
Marie-Joseph d'Othee.description: Raised at Othee in the province of Liege, Belgium. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Marina.name: Marina
Marina.description: Raised at the Federal Agricultural Research Station, Wadenswil, Switzerland. Received at Brogdale in 1999. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a slightly perfumed flavour.

Marosszeki Piros Paris.name: Marosszeki Piros Paris
Marosszeki Piros Paris.description: Originated in Maros-Torda, Hungary. First recorded in 1598. Fruits have a subacid, aromatic flavour.

Marriage-Maker.name: Marriage-Maker
Marriage-Maker.description: Originated in England. It was described in 1883 but thought to be older. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Marstar.name: Marstar
Marstar.description: A more highly coloured clone of Melrose originating with Star Fruits, Vedene, France. Fruits have moderately firm, a little coarse-textured flesh with a juicy, sweet, pleasant flavour.

Marston Scarlet Wonder.name: Marston Scarlet Wonder
Marston Scarlet Wonder.description: A more highly coloured sport of Newton Wonder. Discovered in about 1909 by Mr Hughes, Marston, Herefordshire, England. Fruits have creamy white, rather coarse-textured flesh which is moderately juicy and subacid. Cooks very well.

Martini.name: Martini
Martini.description: Found in 1875 near Kollmar in Holstein, Germany. Fruits have firm, crisp, creamy white tinged green flesh with a subacid sweet flavour.

Maruba.name: Maruba
Maruba.description: Malus prunifolia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1981 from Japan.

Mary Barnett.name: Mary Barnett
Mary Barnett.description: Raised in about 1920 by Mrs Mary Jane Barnett at Steeple Ashton, Wiltshire, England. Fruits have fine, crisp, green flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Mary Green.name: Mary Green
Mary Green.description: Raised or discovered by D.E. Green, Send, Surrey, England. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Mauss Reinette.name: Mauss Reinette
Mauss Reinette.description: Raised by Mauss of Herrenhausen, Germany. Recorded in 1874. Fruits have fairly fine, tender, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid and aromatic flavour.

Maxton.name: Maxton
Maxton.description: A more regularly cropping sport of Laxton's Superb. Discovered in 1939 by R. Heseltine, Assington, Suffolk, England. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, very juicy flesh, with a pleasant refreshing flavour.

May Queen.name: May Queen
May Queen.description: Raised by Haywood of Worcester, England. First recorded in 1888. Introduced by Penwill's. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1892. Fruits have firm, compact, yellow flesh with an unusual, sometimes astringent flavour.

Maypole.name: Maypole
Maypole.description: Raised in 1976 at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits are excellent for crab apple jelly, cider and wine.

McIntosh.name: McIntosh
McIntosh.description: Discovered in 1796 by John McIntosh near Dundela, Dundas County, Ontario, Canada. Propagated by Allan McIntosh. It was introduced and named in about 1870. Fruits have white, rather soft, fine-textured, very juicy flesh with a sweet, pleasant vinous flavou

McLellan.name: McLellan
McLellan.description: Raised in about 1780 in a seedling orchard at Woodstock, Connecticut, USA. Fruits have fairly firm, fine, very tender flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

McSweet.name: McSweet
McSweet.description: Raised at the Central Experiment Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1927. Fruits have firm, crisp, white, tender, juicy flesh with a fairly sweet and distinctive moderate flavour.

Mead's Broading.name: Mead's Broading
Mead's Broading.description: Originated in England. Described in 1884. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with an acid flavour.

Medina.name: Medina
Medina.description: Raised in 1911 by Richard Wellington at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, USA. It was introduced in 1923. Fruits have firm, tender, fairly coarse flesh with a sweet subacid, aromatic and perfumed flavour.

Megumi.name: Megumi
Megumi.description: Raised in 1931 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. It was named in 1948. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a subacid flavour.

Meku.name: Meku
Meku.description: Raised in 1959 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Fruits are sweet and juicy.

Mela Carla.name: Mela Carla
Mela Carla.description: Said to have originated from Finale Ligure, Trentino or Calabria, Italy. First described in 1817 but thought to be considerably older. Fruits have fine, loose textured, melting, white flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Melba.name: Melba
Melba.description: Raised in 1898 by W.T. Macoun at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1909. It received the Silver Wilder Medal from the American Pomological Society in 1927. Fruits have firm, crisp, white, juicy flesh with a refreshing vinous flavour. Skin is aromatic.

Melmoth.name: Melmoth
Melmoth.description: Raised near Yeovil, Somerset, England by Florence Melmoth. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Melon.name: Melon
Melon.description: Originated in about 1800 with Heman Chapin, East Bloomfield, Ontario County, New York, USA from seed brought from Connecticut. Introduced in 1845. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp, tender, yellowish flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Melrose (2).name: Melrose (2)
Melrose (2).description: Raised by Freeman S. Howlett at Ohio Agricultural Experiment Station, Wooster, Ohio, USA. Selected in 1937 and introduced in 1944. Fruits have creamy white, moderately firm, a little coarse-textured, juicy flesh, with a pleasant sweet, subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Meran.name: Meran
Meran.description: Raised in 1966 by K. Zanon and F. Waldner, Meran (Bozen), Italy. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Merchant Apple.name: Merchant Apple
Merchant Apple.description: Originated in Somerset, England. First described in 1872. Fruits have soft, fine, greenish cream flesh with a subacid flavour.

Mere de Menage.name: Mere de Menage
Mere de Menage.description: Known in the late 1700s. Fruits have firm, greenish, rather coarse-textured and rather dry flesh with an acid flavour.

Meridian.name: Meridian
Meridian.description: Raised at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent by Dr Frank Alston. Introduced in 1999. Fruits have a Cox-like flavour.

Merlyn.name: Merlyn
Merlyn.description: Raised by nurseryman J. Nicolai, Belgium. Received by Brogdale in 1996. Fruits are fairly sweet with an aromatic flavour.

Merrigold.name: Merrigold
Merrigold.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1983 from France. Fruits are very sweet, crisp and juicy.

Merton Beauty.name: Merton Beauty
Merton Beauty.description: Raised in 1933 by M. B. Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a distinct aniseed flavour.

Merton Charm.name: Merton Charm
Merton Charm.description: Raised by M.B.Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. Released in 1962. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1960. Fruits have tender, fine-textured, very juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Merton Delight.name: Merton Delight
Merton Delight.description: Raised by M.B.Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. It was discarded in Britain in 1959. Fruits have tender, crisp, creamy flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Merton Joy.name: Merton Joy
Merton Joy.description: Raised in 1946 by M.B. Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. It was named in 1965. Fruits have firm, crisp, somewhat coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a slightly acid, pleasant aromatic flavour.

Merton Knave.name: Merton Knave
Merton Knave.description: Raised in 1948 by M.B.Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. It was named Merton Ace in 1968 but changed to Merton Knave in 1970. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Merton Pearmain.name: Merton Pearmain
Merton Pearmain.description: Raised in 1934 by M.B.Crane at John Innes Institute, Merton, England. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Merton Pippin.name: Merton Pippin
Merton Pippin.description: Raised at John Innes Horticultural Institute, Merton, England by M.B.Crane. Introduced in 1948 but discarded in Britain in 1959. Fruits have whitish cream flesh with a subacid flavour.

Merton Prolific.name: Merton Prolific
Merton Prolific.description: Raised in 1914 by M.B.Crane at the John Innes Horticultural Institute, Merton, England. It was named in 1947. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1950. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subaci

Merton Reinette.name: Merton Reinette
Merton Reinette.description: Raised in 1933 by M.B.Crane at the John Innes Horticultural Institute, Merton, England. Fruits have a pleasant aromatic flavour.

Merton Russet.name: Merton Russet
Merton Russet.description: Raised in 1921 at the John Innes Horticultural Institute, Merton, England by M.B.Crane. It was named in 1943. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Merton Worcester.name: Merton Worcester
Merton Worcester.description: Raised by M.B.Crane at the John Innes Institute, Merton, England in 1914. Named in 1947. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1950. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Michinoku.name: Michinoku
Michinoku.description: Originated in Japan. Fruits have crisp, juicy, sweet flesh with good flavour.

Miller's Seedling.name: Miller's Seedling
Miller's Seedling.description: Raised in 1848 by Mr James Miller at Newbury, Berkshire, England. It received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1906. Fruits have white, rather soft, very juicy flesh with a sweet and refreshing flavour. Bruises easily.

Millicent Barnes.name: Millicent Barnes
Millicent Barnes.description: Raised in about 1903 by N.F. Barnes at Eaton Gardens, Chester, England. Introduced by Clibrans. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, crisp, juicy flesh which is slightly acid and lacking flavour.

Milton.name: Milton
Milton.description: Raised in 1909 at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, USA. by Richard Wellington. Introduced by the N.Y.S. Fruit Testing Association in 1923. Fruits have soft, fine, very white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Mimi.name: Mimi
Mimi.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have fine, soft, yellow flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Minister von Hammerstein.name: Minister von Hammerstein
Minister von Hammerstein.description: Raised in 1882 in Geisenheim, Germany by R Goethe and named after the then Minister of Agriculture. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Minjon.name: Minjon
Minjon.description: Raised at the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm, Excelsior, USA. Introduced in 1942. Fruits have rather soft, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Minnehaha.name: Minnehaha
Minnehaha.description: Raised at the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm, Excelsior. Introduced in 1920. Fruits have rather soft, coarse flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Minnesota Russet.name: Minnesota Russet
Minnesota Russet.description: Originated in Minnesota, USA. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1975. Fruits are sweet with little flavour.

Minshull Crab.name: Minshull Crab
Minshull Crab.description: Originated in Minshull, Cheshire, England. The original tree was growing in 1777. Fruits have firm, crisp, white flesh with a very acid and bitter flavour.

Mio.name: Mio
Mio.description: Raised in 1932 at the Horticultural Research Station, Alnarp, Sweden by Emil Johansson. Fruits have soft, white tinged pink flesh with a rather insipid flavour.

Missing Link.name: Missing Link
Missing Link.description: Originated in U.S.A. It was recorded in 1897. Introduced by Shank and Clayton, USA. Fruits have soft, coarse, dry flesh with an insipid flavour.

Mitchelson's Seedling.name: Mitchelson's Seedling
Mitchelson's Seedling.description: Raised at Kingston-on-Thames, Surrey by Mitchelson. First described in 1851. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellowish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Mobbs Royal.name: Mobbs Royal
Mobbs Royal.description: Originated either in Australia or New Zealand. It was known in Australia in 1868. Fruits have firm, fine, very white tinged green flesh with an acid flavour.

Molleskov.name: Molleskov
Molleskov.description: Originally found in about 1860 by A. Brun at Molleskoven near Ringstad, Denmark. Fruits have firm, fine, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Mollie's Delicious.name: Mollie's Delicious
Mollie's Delicious.description: Raised in 1948 by G.W. Schneider, New Jersey Agricultural Experiment Station, New Brunswick, USA. Introduced in 1966. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a flavour similar to Golden Delicious.

Monarch.name: Monarch
Monarch.description: Raised in 1888. Introduced in 1918 by Seabrook Nurseries, Chelmsford, Essex. Fruits have rather soft, somewhat coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Bruises very easily.

Monroe.name: Monroe
Monroe.description: Raised in 1910 by Richard Wellington at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, New York, USA. Introduced in 1947. Fruits have fine, soft, cream flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Montfort.name: Montfort
Montfort.description: Raised in about 1928 at Woodford Green, Essex. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Morgenrot.name: Morgenrot
Morgenrot.description: Raised at Max-Planck Institut, Cologne, Germany. Fruits are crisp and fairly juicy with rather chewy flesh.

Morkrod.name: Morkrod
Morkrod.description: A sport of Gravenstein having red stripes. Originated in either Denmark or Sweden. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1960. Fruits have crisp, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a pleasant mixture of sweetness and acidity with a distinctive flavour.

Morley's Seedling.name: Morley's Seedling
Morley's Seedling.description: Raised by C. Morley, Ely, Cambridgeshire, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1928. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, white flesh with an astringent flavour.

Morris's Russet.name: Morris's Russet
Morris's Russet.description: Raised by Morris at Brentford, England. Described in 1851. Fruits have firm, tender flesh with a subacid, sweet, aromatic flavour.

Moss's Seedling.name: Moss's Seedling
Moss's Seedling.description: Raised in about 1955 at Chetwynd End Nurseries, Newport, Shropshire. Fruits are crisp and juicy with some Cox-like flavour.

Mother.name: Mother
Mother.description: Originated at Boston, Worcester County, Massachusetts, U.S.A. First recorded in 1844. Fruits have fairly firm, very juicy flesh with a sweet and distinctive good aromatic flavour.

Mount Rainier.name: Mount Rainier
Mount Rainier.description: Thought to be of Dutch origin. In existence in 1929. Fruits have fine, crisp, yellowish flesh with a very sweet, aromatic flavour.

Mrs. Barron.name: Mrs. Barron
Mrs. Barron.description: Exhibited in 1883 by The Royal Horticultural Society at the Fruit Conference. Fruits have soft, tender, dry, yellow tinged orange flesh with a sweet and subacid flavour.

Mrs. Lakeman's Seedling.name: Mrs. Lakeman's Seedling
Mrs. Lakeman's Seedling.description: Raised in about 1900 by Mrs Lakeman of Stocksfield, Northumberland. Introduced by William Fell & Co., of Hexham. Fruits have crisp, firm, rather coarse flesh with an acid and slightly sweet flavour.

Mrs. Phillimore.name: Mrs. Phillimore
Mrs. Phillimore.description: Raised by Charles Ross and introduced by Bunyard of Maidstone. First recorded in 1896. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits have crisp, tender flesh, with a sweet, fusty flavour.

Munster Tulip.name: Munster Tulip
Munster Tulip.description: Originated in Ireland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950. Fruits have firm, tender, fine, white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Murasaki.name: Murasaki
Murasaki.description: Raised in 1935 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Murfitt's Seedling.name: Murfitt's Seedling
Murfitt's Seedling.description: Originated in Cambridgeshire, England. Introduced in about 1883. Fruits have fine, crisp, white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Mutsu.name: Mutsu
Mutsu.description: Triploid. Raised in Japan in 1930 and first fruited in 1939. It was named 'Mutsu' in 1948 but renamed 'Crispin' in the UK for commercial reasons in 1968. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh which is a little sweet, somewhat acid with a refreshing, and pleasant flavour.

Nancy Jackson.name: Nancy Jackson
Nancy Jackson.description: Originated in England. Described in 1875. Fruits have coarse, soft, greenish-white flesh with an acid flavour.

Nanny.name: Nanny
Nanny.description: Raised in Surrey, England. Recorded in 1842. Fruits have fairly firm, rather dry, cream flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Nasona.name: Nasona
Nasona.description: Thought to have originated near Modena, Italy. It was described in 1949 but older than this. Fruits have fine, crisp, creamy white flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Nebuta.name: Nebuta
Nebuta.description: Raised in 1981 in Hirosaki, Aomori, Japan, by K. Maeda. Fruits have firm, pale yellow flesh with a somewhat acid flavour. Susceptible to water core.

Neild's Drooper.name: Neild's Drooper
Neild's Drooper.description: A weeping tree budded at Woburn 1915-16, the grafts having been taken from a tree planted at Woburn in 1894 labelled Calville Blanche d'Ete but does not resemble it. Fruits have greenish white, crisp, tender, watery flesh with an acid flavour.

Nemes Szercsika alma.name: Nemes Szercsika alma
Nemes Szercsika alma.description: Originated near the Drava River, Hungary. Described in 1883. Fruits have coarse, soft, dry flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Nemtesc cu Miezul Rosu.name: Nemtesc cu Miezul Rosu
Nemtesc cu Miezul Rosu.description: Originated in Romania. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948 but is believed to be much older. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

New Bess Pool.name: New Bess Pool
New Bess Pool.description: Raised before 1850 by J. Stevens at Stanton-by-Dale, Yorkshire. Fruits have crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

New Fuji.name: New Fuji
New Fuji.description: An improved clone of Fuji. Fruits are very sweet, crisp and juicy.

New German.name: New German
New German.description: Originated in Herefordshire, England. Fruits have somewhat soft, coarse, white tinged green flesh with a subacid flavour.

New Hawthornden.name: New Hawthornden
New Hawthornden.description: Introduced in 1847 by Rivers of Sawbridgeworth, England. Fruits have fairly tender, crisp, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

New Jonagold.name: New Jonagold
New Jonagold.description: A red fruited clone of Jonagold, ripening earlier than Jonagold. Discovered by M. Saito, Aomori Prefecture, Japan. Fruits have fine-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a good rich flavour.

New Rock Pippin.name: New Rock Pippin
New Rock Pippin.description: Raised at Barnwell, Cambridge, by William Pleasance. It was first exhibited in 1821. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine flesh with a sweet, vinous and aromatic flavour.

Newport Cross.name: Newport Cross
Newport Cross.description: Raised in 1920 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol by G.T. Spinks. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, dry flesh with an insipid flavour.

Newton Wonder.name: Newton Wonder
Newton Wonder.description: Raised by Taylor at King's Newton, Melbourne, Derbyshire, England. Introduced in about 1887 when it also received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have rather coarse-textured, moderately juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks very well.

Newtosh.name: Newtosh
Newtosh.description: Raised by the Horticulture Division, Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. It was selected in 1922. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender, greenish white flesh with a sweetish subacid flavour.

Newtown Pippin.name: Newtown Pippin
Newtown Pippin.description: Originated on the estate of Gersham Moore at Newtown, Long Island, USA. It was well known in 1759. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a trace of richness.

Newtown Spitzenburg.name: Newtown Spitzenburg
Newtown Spitzenburg.description: Originated at Newtown, Long Island, USA. It was recorded in 1817. Fruits have firm, coarse, creamy yellow flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Niagara.name: Niagara
Niagara.description: Originated at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA from a selection made in 1950. It was introduced in 1962. Fruits have fine, crisp, tender white flesh with a subacid to sweet, aromatic flavour.

Nico.name: Nico
Nico.description: Raised by nurseryman Jo Nicolai, Belgium. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1981. Fruits have fairly juicy, crisp flesh with a slightly acid and weak aromatic flavour.

Nonpareil.name: Nonpareil
Nonpareil.description: Thought to be of French origin. It was introduced into England in the mid 1500s. Fruits have greenish white, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a slightly acid and pleasant aromatic flavour.

Nonsuch Park.name: Nonsuch Park
Nonsuch Park.description: Originated in England. It was described in 1831. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish flesh.

Norfolk Beauty.name: Norfolk Beauty
Norfolk Beauty.description: Raised by Mr Allan at Gunton Park, Norwich, England. First recorded in 1901. It was introduced in 1902, in which year it received an Award of Merit and a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have rather soft, somewhat dry, acid flesh. Cooks well.

Norfolk Beefing.name: Norfolk Beefing
Norfolk Beefing.description: Raised in Norfolk, England. It was first recorded in 1807. Fruits have very firm, coarse-textured, juicy flesh which is very acid.

Norfolk Royal.name: Norfolk Royal
Norfolk Royal.description: A chance seedling found in Wright's Nurseries, North Walsham, Norfolk, England in about 1908. It was introduced in 1928 and named in 1930. Fruits have moderately firm, crisp, very juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Norfolk Royal Russet.name: Norfolk Royal Russet
Norfolk Royal Russet.description: A russetted sport of Norfolk Royal. Discovered by Royal Airforce chaplain Rev. C.E. Wright in his garden at Burnham Overy Staithe, Norfolk. Fruits have crisp, firm flesh with a rich, sweet flavour.

Noris.name: Noris
Noris.description: Originated in Lithuania. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1976 from the Pavlovsk Experimental Station of the Vavilov Institute in Russia. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Norman's Pippin.name: Norman's Pippin
Norman's Pippin.description: Thought to have been imported into East Anglia from Flanders. Recorded in 1900. It was awarded the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1900. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a sweet, rich flavour.

Normandie.name: Normandie
Normandie.description: Thought to have originated in France, although received by the National Fruit Trials from Switzerland in 1948. Fruits have soft, dry, greenish white flesh with an insipid flavour.

Northern Greening.name: Northern Greening
Northern Greening.description: Thought to have originated in England. First recorded in 1826. Fruits have moderately firm, a little coarse-textured, juicy flesh with an acid flavour.

Northern Spy.name: Northern Spy
Northern Spy.description: First grown in the seedling orchard of Heman Chapin, at East Bloomfield, New York, USA from seed brought from Salisbury, Connecticut, USA. It was raised in about 1800 and introduced in 1840. Fruits have fairly firm, juicy, sweet flesh with a pleasant flavour. This variety is resistant to woolly aphis and has been used as a parent in the breeding of resistant rootstocks and varieties.

Northland Seedling.name: Northland Seedling
Northland Seedling.description: Raised at Northland Cottage, Tetbury, Gloucestershire by A.P. Kitcat. It was received by the National Fruit Trials in 1930. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Notarisappel.name: Notarisappel
Notarisappel.description: Raised in 1890 by J.H. Th. Van den Ham, The Netherlands. Fruits have soft, coarse, creamy white flesh with a subacid and sweetish flavour.

Nottingham Pippin.name: Nottingham Pippin
Nottingham Pippin.description: Thought to have originated in Nottingham, England. It was known to be in existence in 1815. Fruits have fine, tender, white flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Nova Easygro.name: Nova Easygro
Nova Easygro.description: Raised in 1956 by A.D. Crowe at the Canadian Department Agricultural Research Station, Kentville, Nova Scotia. Introduced in 1971. Fruits have firm, crisp, moderately juicy flesh with a subacid and pleasant flavour.

Nugget.name: Nugget
Nugget.description: Discovered in 1954 by Homer S. Kemp, Bountiful Ridge Nurseries, Princess Anne, Maryland, USA. It was introduced in 1966. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.

Nutmeg Pippin.name: Nutmeg Pippin
Nutmeg Pippin.description: Origin unknown but described in 1920. Fruits have crisp, pale yellow, juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Oaken Pin (of Taylor).name: Oaken Pin (of Taylor)
Oaken Pin (of Taylor).description: Originated in England. It was recorded in about 1876. Fruits have tender, yellowish tinged red flesh with a sweet flavour.

Obelisk.name: Obelisk
Obelisk.description: Raised in 1970 at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits are crisp, juicy and rather brisk, becoming mellow in the New Year. Tendency to biennial bearing.

Odin.name: Odin
Odin.description: Raised in 1953 by A.A. Schaap at the Institute of Horticultural Plant Breeding, Wageningen, the Netherlands. Introduced in 1966. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Ohio Nonpareil.name: Ohio Nonpareil
Ohio Nonpareil.description: Originated in the orchard of Mr Bowman, Massillon, Ohio, USA. It was described in 1848. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Ohm Paul.name: Ohm Paul
Ohm Paul.description: Originated in the 1890s with nurseryman Forckel, Germany. Fruits have fine, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Old Fred.name: Old Fred
Old Fred.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Exhibited in 1944. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Old Pearmain (of Kelsey).name: Old Pearmain (of Kelsey)
Old Pearmain (of Kelsey).description: Believed to have originated either in the UK or France. It was mentioned in both countries in about 1200. Fruits have a pleasant rich flavour.

Ontario.name: Ontario
Ontario.description: Raised by Charles Arnold at Paris, Ontario, Canada in about 1820. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1898. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks well, breaking up completely. Tends to bruise easily.

Opal (Seabrook).name: Opal (Seabrook)
Opal (Seabrook).description: Raised by W.P. Seabrook, Chelmsford, Essex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1936. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Opalescent.name: Opalescent
Opalescent.description: Introduced in 1899 by McNary & Gaines, Xenia, Ohio, USA. Fruits have firm, fairly crisp flesh with a sweet flavour.

Orange Goff.name: Orange Goff
Orange Goff.description: Thought to have originated in Kent, England. Recorded in 1842. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellow flesh with an acid flavour.

Orangenburg.name: Orangenburg
Orangenburg.description: Raised at Max Planck Institute, Cologne, Germany. Introduced in 1973. Fruits are crisp and juicy and slightly acid with little flavour.

Oranje de Sonnaville.name: Oranje de Sonnaville
Oranje de Sonnaville.description: Raised by P. Sonnaville at the Fruit Research Station, Wilhelminadorp, The Netherlands. Introduced in 1971. Fruits have rather coarse-textured, sweet flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Orbai Alma.name: Orbai Alma
Orbai Alma.description: Originated in Hungary. Recorded in 1882. Fruits have soft, coarse, greenish white flesh with a very acid flavour.

Oregon Spur.name: Oregon Spur
Oregon Spur.description: A clone of Red Delicious having more colour. Originated in Milton-Freewater, Ore, USA by Wayne M. Trumbull. Introduced in about 1966. Fruits have firm, very sweet, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Orenco.name: Orenco
Orenco.description: Originated in Orenco, Oregon, USA, by The Oregon Nursery Company, but said by some to be a chance seedling found in Oregon City. It was catalogued in 1903 but said by some to have originated in about 1840. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet subacid and aromatic flavour.

Orin.name: Orin
Orin.description: Triploid. Originated before 1942 by T. Otsuki, an apple grower in Fukushima Prefecture, Japan. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a sweet and aromatic flavour.

Oriole.name: Oriole
Oriole.description: Raised in 1914 in Excelsior, Minnesota, USA by the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm. Introduced in 1949. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a slightly sweet and slightly subacid flavour.

Orleans.name: Orleans
Orleans.description: Raised in 1912 by Richard Wellington at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Introduced in 1923. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp flesh with a sweet flavour.

Orleans Reinette.name: Orleans Reinette
Orleans Reinette.description: Thought to be of French origin. It was first described in 1776. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1914 under the name 'Winter Ribston' and in 1921 as 'Orleans Reinette'. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, little juicy flesh with a pleasant, Blenheim-like flavour.

Ortley.name: Ortley
Ortley.description: Originated in New Jersey, USA in the orchard of Michael Ortley. Described in 1817 as Woolman's Long Pippin. Re-named Ortley in 1825. In 1872, the commercial synonym Cleopatra came into use. Fruits have tender, very juicy flesh with a pleasant mild flavour. Fruits bruise easily. Tree tends to be biennial.

Oslin.name: Oslin
Oslin.description: Thought to have originated either in France or Scotland. It was known in 1815 but believed to be much older. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, rich, aromatic flavour.

Osnabrucker Reinette.name: Osnabrucker Reinette
Osnabrucker Reinette.description: Originated in Osnabruck, Hannover, Germany. It was well established in 1802. Fruits have fine, tender flesh with a sweet and very vinous flavour.

Owen Thomas.name: Owen Thomas
Owen Thomas.description: Raised in 1897 by Laxton Brothers Ltd., at Bedford, England. Introduced in 1920. Fruits have rather soft, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Oxford Beauty.name: Oxford Beauty
Oxford Beauty.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Recorded in 1944. Fruits have fine, crisp, tender flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Oxford Conquest.name: Oxford Conquest
Oxford Conquest.description: Raised in 1927 at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Fruits have rather tough flesh with an acid flavour.

Oxford Hoard.name: Oxford Hoard
Oxford Hoard.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Exhibited in 1943. Fruits have coarse, firm, tough flesh with a sweet and aromatic flavour.

Oxford Sunrise.name: Oxford Sunrise
Oxford Sunrise.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Exhibited in 1942. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Oxford Yeoman.name: Oxford Yeoman
Oxford Yeoman.description: Raised in 1922 at Eynsham, Oxford, by F.W. Wastie. Exhibited in 1942. Fruits have coarse, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Ozark Gold.name: Ozark Gold
Ozark Gold.description: Raised at Mountain Grove Fruit Experiment Station, Missouri, USA. Introduced in 1970. Fruits have firm flesh with a mild, subacid flavour.

P.J. Bergius.name: P.J. Bergius
P.J. Bergius.description: A more highly coloured sport of Savstaholm. Originated in Sweden. Fruits have crisp, pink tinged flesh with a subacid to slightly sweet flavour.

Palmer's Rosey.name: Palmer's Rosey
Palmer's Rosey.description: Originated in the garden of H.T. Palmer, Whyteleafe, Surrey, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1965. Fruits have crisp flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Papirovka.name: Papirovka
Papirovka.description: Originated in Russia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1949 from Switzerland. Fruits have juicy, cream flesh with an acid flavour.

Parker's Pippin.name: Parker's Pippin
Parker's Pippin.description: Thought to be of English origin, but better known on the continent. It was received by Diel from England in the early 1800s. Fruits have fairly crisp, firm flesh with a subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Paroquet.name: Paroquet
Paroquet.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Welford Park, Newbury, Berkshire. First recorded in 1897. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits have tender, yellowish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Patricia.name: Patricia
Patricia.description: Raised in 1898 at Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1921. Fruits have soft, loose-textured, white flesh with a sweet, perfumed flavour.

Patrick.name: Patrick
Patrick.description: Originated in the UK. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have soft, fine, white flesh with an insipid flavour.

Patte de Loup.name: Patte de Loup
Patte de Loup.description: Thought to have originated in the late 1700s in Beaupreau, Marie-et-Loire, France. Fruits have firm flesh with a sweet, subacid, perfumed flavour.

Paulared.name: Paulared
Paulared.description: A chance seedling discovered in 1960 by Lewis Arrends, Sparta, Michigan, USA. Introduced in 1968. Fruits have firm, white, crisp, juicy flesh with a vinous flavour.

Payette.name: Payette
Payette.description: Raised in 1936 by Leif Verner at the Agricultural Experiment Station, Moscow, Idaho, USA. Introduced in 1944. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a slightly sweet and subacid flavour.

Peacemaker.name: Peacemaker
Peacemaker.description: Raised at Welford Park, Newbury, England by Charles Ross. First recorded in 1913. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1913. Fruits have fine, rather soft, creamy white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Pearl.name: Pearl
Pearl.description: Raised in 1933 by W. Seabrook & Sons Ltd., at Boreham, Essex. Introduced in 1938. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, fairly juicy flesh with a sweet, slightly acid and pleasant aromatic flavour.

Peasgood's Nonsuch.name: Peasgood's Nonsuch
Peasgood's Nonsuch.description: Raised by Mrs Peasgood at Stamford, Lincolnshire, England from seed sown in about 1858. Received First Class Certificate from Royal Horticultural Society in 1872. Fruits are a little coarse textured, moderately juicy and a little sweet. Cooks well.

Peche Melba.name: Peche Melba
Peche Melba.description: Brought to England in 1930 from County Kilkenny, Ireland. Fruits have firm, coarse, rather dry flesh with a subacid flavour.

Peck's Pleasant.name: Peck's Pleasant
Peck's Pleasant.description: Thought to have originated in Rhode Island, USA. Recorded in 1832. Fruits have crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Pederstrup.name: Pederstrup
Pederstrup.description: Thought to have originated in either Denmark or Germany. Known to be growing on Fyn, Denmark in 1858. Fruits have fairly crisp, tender, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet and subacid flavour.

Pedro.name: Pedro
Pedro.description: Raised in 1898 by Horticultural Division, Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1913. Fruits have firm, crisp, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Peggy's Pride.name: Peggy's Pride
Peggy's Pride.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W. Wastie. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1944. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Penco.name: Penco
Penco.description: A clone of Golden Delicious having a light brownish orange flush. Originated in Belgium. Introduced by nurseryman Nicolai. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Pepin d'Or de Bovelingen.name: Pepin d'Or de Bovelingen
Pepin d'Or de Bovelingen.description: Thought to have originated in Belgium. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947. Fruits have fine, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Pepin de Bourgueil.name: Pepin de Bourgueil
Pepin de Bourgueil.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have yellowish white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Pepin Shafrannyi.name: Pepin Shafrannyi
Pepin Shafrannyi.description: Dessert. Raised in 1907 by I.V. Michurin at Michurinsk, Russia. Fruits are firm, crisp and juicy. Resistant to scab.

Pepino Jaune.name: Pepino Jaune
Pepino Jaune.description: Originated in Cotes du Nord, France. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with an acid flavour.

Perrine Yellow Transparent.name: Perrine Yellow Transparent
Perrine Yellow Transparent.description: A tetraploid bud mutation of White Transparent, ripening one week earlier. Discovered in about 1930 by D.B. Perrine in Centralia, Illinois, USA. Introduced in 1961. Fruits have white, rather coarse-textured, acid flesh with little flavour.

Perrine York.name: Perrine York
Perrine York.description: Tetraploid. A clone of York Imperial. Found by D.B. Perrine, Centralia, Illinois, USA. Fruits have firm, crisp, moderately tender flesh with a subacid to sweetish, aromatic flavour.

Peter Lock.name: Peter Lock
Peter Lock.description: Discovered in the early 1800s. It was found in Dean Woods, Buckfastleigh, Devon by Peter Lock. Fruits have soft, coarse flesh with a subacid flavour.

Pewaukee.name: Pewaukee
Pewaukee.description: Raised by George P. Peffer, Pewaukee, Wisconsin. First recorded in 1870. Fruits have fairly firm, coarse flesh with a subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Pfirsichroter Sommerapfel.name: Pfirsichroter Sommerapfel
Pfirsichroter Sommerapfel.description: Thought to have originated in Thuringia, Germany. Described in the early 1800s. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet subacid, aromatic flavour.

Pickering's Seedling.name: Pickering's Seedling
Pickering's Seedling.description: Believed to have originated in Nottinghamshire, England. Brought to notice in 1869. Fruits have firm, fine, fairly tender, sweet flesh.

Pig's Nose Pippin.name: Pig's Nose Pippin
Pig's Nose Pippin.description: Thought to have originated in Hereford, England. Described in 1884. Fruits have fine, crisp flesh with a sweet flavour.

Pigeon de Jerusalem.name: Pigeon de Jerusalem
Pigeon de Jerusalem.description: Originated in France. Recorded in the late 1600s. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with a subacid and slightly perfumed flavour.

Pikkolo.name: Pikkolo
Pikkolo.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Fruits have sweet, crisp flesh.

Pilot.name: Pilot
Pilot.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1988. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh. Resistant to fireblight.

Piltsamasskoe Zimnee.name: Piltsamasskoe Zimnee
Piltsamasskoe Zimnee.description: Originated in Estonia. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh.

Pine Apple Russet.name: Pine Apple Russet
Pine Apple Russet.description: Described in 1920 as being grown in Devon and Cornwall. Fruits have hard, dry, yellow flesh with a pineapple flavour.

Pine Golden Pippin.name: Pine Golden Pippin
Pine Golden Pippin.description: Originated in the UK. First recorded in 1861. Fruits have moderately firm, juicy flesh with a fairly sweet, rich, aromatic flavour.

Pinner Seedling.name: Pinner Seedling
Pinner Seedling.description: Raised in 1810 by James Carrell, Pinner, Middlesex. Fruits are sweet.

Pinova.name: Pinova
Pinova.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1986. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Pioneer (1).name: Pioneer (1)
Pioneer (1).description: Raised by Laxton Bros. Ltd., at Bedford, England. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have fine, crisp, fairly tender flesh with a subacid and astringent flavour.

Pirja.name: Pirja
Pirja.description: Raised in 1961 at the Institute of Horticultural and Agricultural Research Centre, Piikki, Finland. Fruits are crisp with a pleasant flavour.

Piros.name: Piros
Piros.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1985. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Pitmaston Pine Apple.name: Pitmaston Pine Apple
Pitmaston Pine Apple.description: Raised by Mr White, steward to Lord Foley at Witley, England in about 1785. Introduced by Williams of Pitmaston, Worcester, England. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a sweet, rich, distinctive flavour.

Pitmaston Russet Nonpareil.name: Pitmaston Russet Nonpareil
Pitmaston Russet Nonpareil.description: Raised at Pitmaston near Worcester, England by John Williams. First fruited in 1814. Fruits have firm flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Pixie.name: Pixie
Pixie.description: Raised in 1947 at the National Fruit Trials, Wisley. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1972. Fruits have crisp, fairly juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Plymouth Cross.name: Plymouth Cross
Plymouth Cross.description: Raised in 1916 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol by G.T. Spinks. Fruits have firm, crisp, cream flesh with a rather acid flavour.

Pobeda Chernenko.name: Pobeda Chernenko
Pobeda Chernenko.description: Raised by Chernenko, Vavilov Institute, St Petersburg, Russia. Known in 1953. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a refreshing flavour.

Polly Prosser.name: Polly Prosser
Polly Prosser.description: Raised in 1946 by J.H. Cooper, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits have firm, coarse, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, subacid, rich flavour.

Pomeroy of Somerset.name: Pomeroy of Somerset
Pomeroy of Somerset.description: Originated in the UK. Described in 1851. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet, rich flavour.

Pomme a Cotes.name: Pomme a Cotes
Pomme a Cotes.description: Originated in France. Described in 1948. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Pomme Crotte.name: Pomme Crotte
Pomme Crotte.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from France. Fruits are sweet and juicy.

Pomme de Choux a Nez Creux.name: Pomme de Choux a Nez Creux

Pomme Royale.name: Pomme Royale
Pomme Royale.description: Believed to have originated in the USA. It was recorded in 1835. Renamed Dyer in about 1850. Fruits have fine, crisp, tender, yellowish white flesh with a rich and subacid flavour.

Ponsford.name: Ponsford
Ponsford.description: Originated in Devon. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have soft, tender, creamy white flesh with an acid flavour.

Ponyik alma.name: Ponyik alma
Ponyik alma.description: Discovered in a wood in Also-Feher called Pojana-mik, Hungary. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, cream tinged green flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Poor Man's Profit.name: Poor Man's Profit
Poor Man's Profit.description: Originated in Somerset, England. Recorded in 1824. Fruits are crisp and juicy with an acid flavour.

Pope's Scarlet Costard.name: Pope's Scarlet Costard
Pope's Scarlet Costard.description: Raised by nurseryman William Pope, Newbury, Berks in the early 1900s. Fruits are good both for dessert and cooking.

Port Allen Russet.name: Port Allen Russet
Port Allen Russet.description: Originated in Port Allen, Errol, Scotland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1958. Fruits have fine, greenish white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Porter.name: Porter
Porter.description: Raised in about 1800 by Rev. Samuel Porter, Sherburne, Massachusetts, USA. Fruits have fine, crisp, tender, yellow flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Potts' Seedling.name: Potts' Seedling
Potts' Seedling.description: Raised by Samuel Potts at Ashton-under-Lyme, Cheshire in about 1849. Fruits have greenish white, rather soft, fine-textured flesh with a very acid flavour.

Prairie Spy.name: Prairie Spy
Prairie Spy.description: Originated at Excelsior, USA by the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Present van Engeland.name: Present van Engeland
Present van Engeland.description: Originated in The Netherlands. It was recorded in 1864. Fruits have somewhat soft, creamy white flesh with an acid flavour.

President Boudewijn.name: President Boudewijn
President Boudewijn.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. It was introduced in 1952. Fruits have greenish white flesh with a subacid, sweet, aromatic flavour.

Prima.name: Prima
Prima.description: Complex parentage involving Malus floribunda. Raised in the USA by the universities Purdue, Rutgers and Illinois. Introduced in 1970. Fruits have deep cream, juicy flesh with a good 'fruity' flavour. Resistant to scab.

Primate.name: Primate
Primate.description: Thought to have originated with Calvin D. Bingham at Camillus, Onondaga County, New York, USA in about 1840. Fruits have crisp, fine, tender, whitish flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Prime Gold.name: Prime Gold
Prime Gold.description: Discovered by B. Hoekman in Zillah, Washington, USA. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Primus.name: Primus
