Primus.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have soft, coarse, creamy white flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Prince Alfred.name: Prince Alfred
Prince Alfred.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1933. Fruits have firm, coarse, crisp flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Prince Charles.name: Prince Charles
Prince Charles.description: Raised between 1940 and 1945 at Victoria Nurseries, Burbage, Leicester, England by Herbert Robinson. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Prince Edward.name: Prince Edward
Prince Edward.description: Raised at Sawbridgeworth, England by Rivers Nurseries. Introduced in 1897. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1897. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Prince Gala.name: Prince Gala
Prince Gala.description: A more highly coloured mutation of Gala. Discovered by Pepinieres Davodeau, Angers, France. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with a good aromatic flavour.
Prince Gala.accession name: Prince Gala/Regal Prince and Regal Prince/Prince Gala

Prince George.name: Prince George
Prince George.description: Thought to have been raised by W.H. Divers, Surrey, England. Fruits have firm, coarse, crisp, yellowish flesh with a very acid flavour.

Prins Bernhard.name: Prins Bernhard
Prins Bernhard.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Prinses Beatrix.name: Prinses Beatrix
Prinses Beatrix.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Fruits have firm, fine, rather tough flesh with a subacid flavour.

Prinses Irene.name: Prinses Irene
Prinses Irene.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Introduced in 1955. Fruits have crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Prinses Margriet.name: Prinses Margriet
Prinses Margriet.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Introduced in 1955. Fruits have cream tinged green flesh with an acid flavour.

Prinses Marijke.name: Prinses Marijke
Prinses Marijke.description: Raised in 1935 at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, The Netherlands. Introduced in 1952. Fruits have fine, firm, tender flesh with a fairly sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Prinz Albrecht von Preussen.name: Prinz Albrecht von Preussen
Prinz Albrecht von Preussen.description: Raised in 1865 by Braun, Kamenz, Schleswig, Germany. Fruits have fine, soft, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Prinzen Apfel.name: Prinzen Apfel
Prinzen Apfel.description: Originated in Germany. Known in the 1700s. Fruits have fairly fine, tender, firm, yellowish-white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Priolov Delises.name: Priolov Delises
Priolov Delises.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Growing, Maribor, Yugoslavia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1972. Fruits are sweet and juicy with softish, yellow flesh.

Priscilla.name: Priscilla
Priscilla.description: Raised in Lafayette, Indiana, USA by three American Universities; Purdue, Rutgers and Illinois. Introduced in 1972. Its name was chosen to honour the wife of the president of Purdue University. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a perfumed flavour. Resistant to scab, mildew and fireblight.

Proctor's Seedling.name: Proctor's Seedling
Proctor's Seedling.description: Originated in Lancashire, England. Known in 1934. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Puckrupt Pippin.name: Puckrupt Pippin
Puckrupt Pippin.description: Originated in the UK. Described in 1872. Fruits have crisp flesh with a rich flavour.

Puffin.name: Puffin
Puffin.description: Originated in Somerset, England. Described in 1883. Fruits have soft, tender flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Pumpkin Sweet.name: Pumpkin Sweet
Pumpkin Sweet.description: Originated in the orchard of S. Lyman, Manchester, Connecticut, USA. Recorded in 1834. Fruits have firm, fairly crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet flavour.

Purpurroter Cousinot.name: Purpurroter Cousinot
Purpurroter Cousinot.description: Originated in either The Netherlands or Germany. Described in 1766. Fruits have firm, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, vinous flavour.

Queen.name: Queen
Queen.description: Raised by W. Bull, a farmer at Billericay, Essex, England from seed sown in 1858. Introduced in 1880 by Saltmarsh of Chelmsford, Essex as 'The Claimant'. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1880. Fruits have white, rather soft, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a distinctly acid flavour.

Queen Alexandra.name: Queen Alexandra
Queen Alexandra.description: Originated in England. First exhibited in 1902. Fruits have rather coarse, crisp, yellowish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Queen Caroline.name: Queen Caroline
Queen Caroline.description: Raised in about 1820 by nurseryman T. Brown at Measham, near Ashby-de-la-Zouche, Leicestershire, England. Fruits have firm, loose-textured, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Queen Cox.name: Queen Cox
Queen Cox.description: A more highly coloured clone of Cox's Orange Pippin. It was discovered at Appleby Fruit Farm, Kingston Bagpuize, Berkshire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1953. Fruits have firm, slightly acid, juicy flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Quindell.name: Quindell
Quindell.description: Discovered in 1934 by Ralph Banta in Green Forest, Arkansas, USA. Introduced in 1965. Fruits have firm, white flesh with a sweet flavour similar to Delicious.

Quinte.name: Quinte
Quinte.description: Raised at the Experimental Farm, Smithfield, Ontario, Canada. Introduced in 1964. Fruits have tender, cream, sweet flesh.

Ralls Janet.name: Ralls Janet
Ralls Janet.description: Originated on the farm of Caleb Ralls in Amherst County, Virginia, USA. First known in about 1800. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet, aromatic flavour.

Rambour Papeleu.name: Rambour Papeleu
Rambour Papeleu.description: Raised by N.A. Hartwiss, Director of the Botanic Gardens at Nikita, Crimea, Russia. Introduced in about 1853 to Belgium by Aldolphe Papeleu, nurseryman of Wetteren. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Rambour Podolskii.name: Rambour Podolskii
Rambour Podolskii.description: Originated in Ukraine, Russia. In existence in 1899. Fruits have moderately firm, moderately coarse, greenish white flesh with a subacid, sweet flavour.

Ranger.name: Ranger
Ranger.description: Raised at the Research Station, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1964. Fruits have tender, white flesh with a mild flavour.

Raritan.name: Raritan
Raritan.description: Raised in 1949 by G.W. Schneider at New Jersey Agricultural Experiment Station, New Brunswick, New Jersey, USA. Named in 1966. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a 'fruity' flavour.

Rathe Ripe.name: Rathe Ripe
Rathe Ripe.description: Originated in England. Described in 1831. Fruits have rather soft, rather dry, whitish flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Reale d'Entraygues.name: Reale d'Entraygues
Reale d'Entraygues.description: Originated in France. Recorded in 1947 but thought to be much older. Fruits have very firm, yellowish white flesh with a very sweet, perfumed flavour.

Reaux.name: Reaux
Reaux.description: Originated in France. Recorded in 1895. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Red Alkmene.name: Red Alkmene
Red Alkmene.description: A clone of Alkmene having a solid red flush. Renamed Red Windsor in 1998. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Red Army.name: Red Army
Red Army.description: Raised at Eynsham, Oxford by F.W.Wastie. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have firm, crisp, creamy white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Red Astrachan.name: Red Astrachan
Red Astrachan.description: Originated from Russia. It first fruited in the UK in 1816. Fruits have firm, crisp, fairly juicy flesh with a sweet and fair flavour.

Red Belle de Boskoop.name: Red Belle de Boskoop
Red Belle de Boskoop.description: Triploid. A more highly coloured sport of Belle de Boskoop. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950 from Denmark. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured flesh with a pleasant aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

Red Benoni.name: Red Benoni
Red Benoni.description: A more highly coloured clone of Benoni. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1969 from the Netherlands. Fruits have tender, juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant, moderately aromatic flavour.

Red Blenheim (Wastie).name: Red Blenheim (Wastie)
Red Blenheim (Wastie).description: Triploid. A more highly coloured clone of Blenheim Orange. Fruits have creamy white, somewhat coarse-textured, rather dry flesh with a rich, characteristic aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

Red Charles Ross.name: Red Charles Ross
Red Charles Ross.description: A more highly coloured clone of Charles Ross. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948 from H. Merifield, Staines, Middlesex, England. Fruits are rather coarse-textured, juicy and sweet with a moderate flavour.

Red Cox.name: Red Cox
Red Cox.description: A clone of Cox's Orange Pippin. Received at Brogdale from the Netherlands.

Red Devil.name: Red Devil
Red Devil.description: Raised in 1975 by Mr Hugh Ermen, Faversham, Kent, England. Fruits are crisp and juicy with pink stained flesh.

Red Dougherty.name: Red Dougherty
Red Dougherty.description: A coloured sport of Dougherty. Originated in Twyford, Hawkes Bay, New Zealand by C.F. Bixley. Introduced in 1930. Fruits have firm, fine, hard, greenish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Red Ellison's Orange.name: Red Ellison's Orange
Red Ellison's Orange.description: A more highly coloured sport of Ellison's Orange. Discovered in 1948 in H.C. Selby's orchard, Walpole St. Peter, Wisbech, Cambridgeshire. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a rich and strong aniseed flavour.

Red Elstar.name: Red Elstar
Red Elstar.description: A coloured sport of Elstar. Originated in the Netherlands. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Red Falstaff.name: Red Falstaff
Red Falstaff.description: A red blushed clone of Falstaff. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Red Fameuse.name: Red Fameuse
Red Fameuse.description: A coloured sport of Fameuse. Received by the National Fruit Trials via Scotland from Yugoslavia. Fruits have rather soft, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a very sweet and vinous flavour similar to McIntosh.

Red Fortune.name: Red Fortune
Red Fortune.description: A more highly coloured clone of Fortune. Fruits have fairly firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Red Geeveston Fanny.name: Red Geeveston Fanny
Red Geeveston Fanny.description: A more highly coloured clone of Geeveston Fanny. Fruits have crisp flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Red Granny Smith.name: Red Granny Smith
Red Granny Smith.description: Raised in Western Australia. Fruits have firm, tender, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Red Jonaprince.name: Red Jonaprince
Red Jonaprince.description: A dark red flushed clone of Jonagold. Discovered in 1994 by Princen Bros, Weert, Netherlands. Fruits have fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good rich flavour.

Red Laxton's Superb.name: Red Laxton's Superb
Red Laxton's Superb.description: A more highly coloured sport of Laxton's Superb. Fruits have firm, very juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant refreshing flavour.

Red Martini.name: Red Martini
Red Martini.description: A more highly coloured clone of Martini. Originated with Mr Peters in Wenzendorf near Hamburg, Germany. Received by the National Fruit Trials in about 1938. Fruits have firm, crisp, creamy white flesh with a subacid, sweet flavour.

Red Melba.name: Red Melba
Red Melba.description: A more highly coloured clone of Melba. Originated at the Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada in about 1936. Introduced in 1940. Fruits have firm, crisp, white, juicy flesh with a refreshing vinous flavour.

Red Miller.name: Red Miller
Red Miller.description: A more highly coloured clone of Millers Seedling. Fruits have white, rather soft, very juicy flesh with a sweet and refreshing flavour.

Red Musk.name: Red Musk
Red Musk.description: Originated in Limpsfield, Surrey, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have soft, coarse, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Red Newton Wonder.name: Red Newton Wonder
Red Newton Wonder.description: A more highly coloured clone of Newton Wonder. Originated on a tree at Hill Top Farm, Ledbury, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1958. Fruits have rather coarse textured, moderately juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks very well.

Red Pixie.name: Red Pixie
Red Pixie.description: A more highly coloured clone of Pixie. Fruits have crisp, fairly juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Red Rome.name: Red Rome
Red Rome.description: Dual purpose. December-April. A more highly coloured clone of Rome Beauty. Originated in Barnley, Australia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950. Fruits have creamy white, rather coarse textured, juicy flesh with little flavour.

Red Saelet.name: Red Saelet
Red Saelet.description: Thought to be a sport of Golden Delicious. Originated with Edwin Saels, Herk-de-Stad, Belgium. Introduced in 1976. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Red Sauce.name: Red Sauce
Red Sauce.description: Raised in 1910 by Richard Wellington at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Introduced in 1926. Fruits have coarse, often red stained flesh, with a subacid flavour.

Red Statesman.name: Red Statesman
Red Statesman.description: A more highly coloured clone of Australian variety 'Statesman'. Discovered in 1914 in New Zealand. Fruits have firm, pale creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid to acid flavour.

Red Sudeley.name: Red Sudeley
Red Sudeley.description: A more highly coloured sport of Lady Sudeley. Received by the National Fruit Trials from Scotland. First fruited in Scotland in 1963.

Red Transparent.name: Red Transparent
Red Transparent.description: Thought to have originated in Russia. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Red Victoria.name: Red Victoria
Red Victoria.description: A chance seedling found in about 1884 near Wisbech, Cambridgeshire. Introduced by Miller. Received the Award of Merit in 1908 and a First Class Certificate in 1910 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Redcoat Grieve.name: Redcoat Grieve
Redcoat Grieve.description: A coloured sport of James Grieve claiming to crop more heavily. Discovered in 1916 on a James Grieve tree at Letchworth by Hal Jones. It was introduced by him in 1921. Fruits have rather soft but very juicy flesh with a good refreshing flavour.

Redfree.name: Redfree
Redfree.description: Raised by Purdue, Rutgers and Illinois Universities, Lafayette, Indiana, USA. Introduced in 1981. Fruits are sweet and crisp with an insipid flavour. Scab resistant.

Redgold.name: Redgold
Redgold.description: Raised in Cashmere, Washington, USA by F.A. Schell. Introduced in 1946. Fruits have tender, yellow flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Redhook.name: Redhook
Redhook.description: Raised in 1923 at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA by R. Wellington. Introduced in 1938. Fruits have soft, fine, white flesh with a highly scented flavour.

Redsleeves.name: Redsleeves
Redsleeves.description: Raised by Dr F. Alston at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Introduced in 1986. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Redstart.name: Redstart
Redstart.description: Originated in about 1950 in an Oxford garden. Fruits have sweet, juicy, softish flesh.

Redwell.name: Redwell
Redwell.description: Raised in about 1911 at University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm, Excelsior, Minnesota, USA. Introduced in 1946. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Redwing.name: Redwing
Redwing.description: Thought to have been raised by Charles Ross. Recorded in 1908. Fruits have soft, mealy, creamy yellow flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Regent.name: Regent
Regent.description: Raised at the University of Minnesota Fruit Breeding Farm, Excelsior, Minnesota, USA. Introduced in 1963. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Reid's Seedling.name: Reid's Seedling
Reid's Seedling.description: Raised around 1880-1890 by Mr Reid of Drumart Jones, Richill, Co. Armagh, Ireland. Fruits have somewhat coarse, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Reinette Clochard.name: Reinette Clochard
Reinette Clochard.description: Originated in France. Known in the mid 1800s. Fruits have fine, yellowish flesh with a sweet, subacid, perfumed flavour.

Reinette Coulon.name: Reinette Coulon
Reinette Coulon.description: Raised by nurseryman Coulon, Liege, Belgium. First fruited in 1856. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, little acid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Reinette d'Anjou.name: Reinette d'Anjou
Reinette d'Anjou.description: Thought to be of either Belgian or German origin. First mentioned in 1817. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet, slightly aromatic flavour.

Reinette d'Anthezieux.name: Reinette d'Anthezieux
Reinette d'Anthezieux.description: Grown at Anthezieux (Demptezieu), Izere, France. Described as old in 1868. Distributed by nurseryman Babout of Thoissey. Fruits have tender, yellowish white flesh with a sweet subacid and perfumed flavour.

Reinette de Bordeaux.name: Reinette de Bordeaux
Reinette de Bordeaux.description: Thought to have originated from France. Recorded c. 1840. Fruits have a rich, sweet, aromatic flavour.

Reinette de Champagne.name: Reinette de Champagne
Reinette de Champagne.description: Originated in about 1770 in Champagne, France. Fruits have firm, crisp, rather dry, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Reinette de Geer.name: Reinette de Geer
Reinette de Geer.description: Raised by Van Mons, Belgium and named after Baron de Geer. First fruited in 1815. Fruits have fine, compact, crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Reinette de Granville.name: Reinette de Granville
Reinette de Granville.description: Thought to have originated in Granville (Manche), France. Recorded in 1842. Fruits have fine, compact, white tinged yellow flesh with a sweet, subacid, rich flavour.

Reinette de Lucas.name: Reinette de Lucas
Reinette de Lucas.description: Thought to have been raised in Belgium by de Jonghe. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine, creamy white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Reinette de Macon.name: Reinette de Macon
Reinette de Macon.description: Originated in France, probably Macon (Seine-et-Loire). First recorded in 1628. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Reinette de Metz.name: Reinette de Metz
Reinette de Metz.description: Thought to have originated in France. Described in 1934. Fruits have fairly fine, tender, white flesh with a sweet, subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Reinette de Versailles.name: Reinette de Versailles
Reinette de Versailles.description: Thought to have originated in about 1730 in Champagne, France. Fruits have rather soft, dry, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Reinette Descardre.name: Reinette Descardre
Reinette Descardre.description: Raised in about 1820 by Benoit Descardre, nurseryman of Chenee, Belgium. Introduced in about 1834. Fruits have tender, pale yellow flesh with a sweet, subacid and perfumed flavour.

Reinette du Canada.name: Reinette du Canada
Reinette du Canada.description: Triploid. Thought to have probably originated in Normandy, France. First mentioned in 1771. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1901. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, somewhat dry flesh with a sweet and moderate fl

Reinette Grise de Portugal.name: Reinette Grise de Portugal
Reinette Grise de Portugal.description: Origin unknown but recorded in 1798. Fruits have very fine, fairly tender, greenish yellow flesh with a sweet, subacid, perfumed flavour.

Reinette Grise du Canada.name: Reinette Grise du Canada
Reinette Grise du Canada.description: A russetted sport of Reinette du Canada. Triploid. Origin unknown but known since the early 1800s. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, somewhat dry flesh with a sweet and moderate flavour.

Reinette Grise de Saintonge.name: Reinette Grise de Saintonge
Reinette Grise de Saintonge.description: A very old variety originating from France. Fruits have firm flesh with a good flavour.

Reinette Marbree.name: Reinette Marbree
Reinette Marbree.description: Originated in the Netherlands. Described in 1760. Fruits have compact, firm, whitish flesh with a very sweet and perfumed flavour.

Reinette Rouge Etoilee.name: Reinette Rouge Etoilee
Reinette Rouge Etoilee.description: Thought to have originated in Belgium or the Netherlands. It was first described in 1830. Widely grown in Europe. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a slightly acid but little flavour.

Reinette Sanguine du Rhin.name: Reinette Sanguine du Rhin
Reinette Sanguine du Rhin.description: Believed to have originated somewhere on the Rhine. Described in about 1840. Fruits have fine, somewhat soft, greenish white flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Reinette Simirenko.name: Reinette Simirenko
Reinette Simirenko.description: Thought to have originated in Russia. Found in the garden of P.F. Simirenko in the Ukraine. Described in 1895. Fruits have tender, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Reinette Thouin.name: Reinette Thouin
Reinette Thouin.description: Originated in the garden of M. Gillet de Laumont, Beaumont, near Montmorency, France and named after Andre Thouin. First fruited in 1822. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Reinette van Ekenstein.name: Reinette van Ekenstein
Reinette van Ekenstein.description: Raised in about 1830 by Jhr. Albarda van Ekenstein, Appingedam, Netherlands. Fruits have firm, yellowish flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Renetta Grigia di Torriana.name: Renetta Grigia di Torriana
Renetta Grigia di Torriana.description: A chance seedling which originated in Torriana di Barge, Cuneo, West Piedmont, Italy. First propagated by Recco Francesco and first distributed in about 1905. Fruits have tender, yellow flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Renora.name: Renora
Renora.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1996. Fruits are crisp and fairly juicy. Resistant to scab.

Renown.name: Renown
Renown.description: Raised at Welford Park, Newbury, by Charles Ross. First described in 1908. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1908. Fruits have firm, pale yellow flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Retina.name: Retina
Retina.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1991. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy. Resistant to scab.

Reverend W. Wilks.name: Reverend W. Wilks
Reverend W. Wilks.description: Raised by Veitch, Chelsea, England. First recorded in 1904. Received the Award of Merit in 1904 and a First Class Certificate in 1910 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Rewena.name: Rewena
Rewena.description: Raised at the Institute of Fruit Research, Dresden-Pillnitz, Germany. Introduced in 1991. Fruits have a pleasant flavour but tend to be rather sour. Resistant to scab, mildew and fireblight.

Rheinischer Krummstiel.name: Rheinischer Krummstiel
Rheinischer Krummstiel.description: Originated in Germany. Described in 1821. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine, white tinged green flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Rhode Island Greening.name: Rhode Island Greening
Rhode Island Greening.description: Triploid. Thought to have originated at Green's End, Newport, Rhode Island, USA. It was already known by 1650. Fruits have rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Ribston Pippin.name: Ribston Pippin
Ribston Pippin.description: Raised at Ribston Hall, Yorkshire, England from seed brought from Rouen, and planted in about 1707. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1962. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, moderately juicy flesh with a rich aromatic flavour.

Richardson (Ireland).name: Richardson (Ireland)
Richardson (Ireland).description: Grafts were taken in about 1900 and brought to England in 1930 from Bessborough, Co. Kilkenny, Ireland by T.E. Tomalin, from the orchard of Richardson. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine, white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Richardson (USA).name: Richardson (USA)
Richardson (USA).description: Discovered in 1956 by L. Richardson at Hammond, New York, USA. Introduced in 1959 by nurseryman F.L. Ashworth, Heuvelton, New York. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh.

Ringer.name: Ringer
Ringer.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1864. Fruits have tender, yellow flesh with an acid flavour.

Ringstad.name: Ringstad
Ringstad.description: Raised in about 1818 by Notary Frans Rundberg at Ringstad near Norrkoping, Sweden. Fruits have fine, loose textured, crisp, white flesh with a sweet, slightly acid and aromatic flavour.

Rival.name: Rival
Rival.description: Raised by Charles Ross at Newbury, Berkshire, England. First recorded in 1900. Introduced by Clibrans of Altrincham. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1900. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a slightly acid

Rivers' Early Peach.name: Rivers' Early Peach
Rivers' Early Peach.description: Raised by Rivers of Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire. Introduced in 1893. Fruits have coarse, rather dry, white flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Rivers' Nonsuch.name: Rivers' Nonsuch
Rivers' Nonsuch.description: Originally selected by Rivers Nurseries, Sawbridgeworth, England as a rootstock. It was known to be in existence in 1875. Fruits have crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, rich, perfumed flavour.

Roanoke.name: Roanoke
Roanoke.description: Raised in 1949 by George D. Oberle, Virginia Polytechnic Institute, Blacksburg, USA. Introduced in 1967. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a mild flavour.

Roba.name: Roba
Roba.description: A more highly coloured clone of Erwin Baur. Fruits have fairly firm flesh with a sweet to subacid, aromatic flavour.

Robert Blatchford.name: Robert Blatchford
Robert Blatchford.description: Raised by F. Chilvers, nurseryman, Hunstanton, Norfolk. Introduced in 1914. Keeps its shape when cooked.

Robin Pippin.name: Robin Pippin
Robin Pippin.description: A chance seedling originating at Gate House Farm, Brenchley, Kent. Fruits have firm, fine, moderately juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Rod Tonnes.name: Rod Tonnes
Rod Tonnes.description: A coloured sport of Tonnes. Originated with Rasmus Roed, Kolbjerk Mark, Denmark. In existence in 1942. Fruits have rather soft, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Rode Wagenaar.name: Rode Wagenaar
Rode Wagenaar.description: Raised at IVT, Wageningen, the Netherlands. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1963. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a refreshing flavour.

Rogers McIntosh.name: Rogers McIntosh
Rogers McIntosh.description: A more highly coloured sport of McIntosh. Originated before 1930 at Densville, New York, USA, with Isaac C. Rogers. Introduced in 1932. Fruits have white, rather soft, fine-textured, very juicy flesh with a sweet, pleasant vinous flavour.

Rokewood.name: Rokewood
Rokewood.description: Originated in Australia, either Victoria or Western Australia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have firm, crisp, greenish white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Rome Beauty.name: Rome Beauty
Rome Beauty.description: Originated with H.N. Gillett in Lawrence County, Ohio, USA. Brought to notice in 1848. Fruits have creamy white, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with very little flavour. Fruits do not mature well in the UK.

Rosa del Caldaro.name: Rosa del Caldaro
Rosa del Caldaro.description: Thought to have originated in the district of Caldaro, Venezia Tridentina, Italy. Described in 1889. Fruits have soft, fine, white flesh with a sweet subacid and slightly perfumed flavour.

Rosa du Perche.name: Rosa du Perche
Rosa du Perche.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have fairly fine, white flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Rosanne.name: Rosanne
Rosanne.description: Originated with Mr Waller of Hobart, Tasmania, Australia. Fruits have soft, juicy, pink stained flesh with a perfumed flavour.

Rose de Benauge.name: Rose de Benauge
Rose de Benauge.description: Thought to have originated in the Bordeaux district of France. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have firm, fairly tender, yellowish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Rosemary Russet.name: Rosemary Russet
Rosemary Russet.description: Raised in England. First described in 1831. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a rather acid and good flavour.

Rosmarina bianca.name: Rosmarina bianca
Rosmarina bianca.description: Originated in the Botzen district of the Tyrol, Italy. Known by the early 1800s. Fruits have fairly fine, tender flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Ross Nonpareil.name: Ross Nonpareil
Ross Nonpareil.description: Originated from Ireland. Recorded in Meath in 1802. Introduced by Robertson to England in 1819. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Rosy Blenheim.name: Rosy Blenheim
Rosy Blenheim.description: Raised by F.W. Thorrington, Hornchurch, Essex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have soft, coarse, whitish flesh with a subacid, perfumed flavour.

Rote Goldparmane.name: Rote Goldparmane
Rote Goldparmane.description: A more highly coloured clone of King of the Pippins. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1967 from Germany. Fruits are firm, juicy and subacid with a brisk and slightly aromatic flavour.

Roter Ananas.name: Roter Ananas
Roter Ananas.description: Found at Sieglitzerberg on the Elbe by Richter, Germany. Described in 1854. Fruits have fine, firm, yellowish white flesh becoming pink stained under the skin with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Roter Eiserapfel.name: Roter Eiserapfel
Roter Eiserapfel.description: Originated in Germany in the early 1700s. Fruits have very hard, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Roter Sauergrauech.name: Roter Sauergrauech
Roter Sauergrauech.description: A more highly coloured sport of Sauergrauech. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1947 from Switzerland. Fruits have fine, soft, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet, vinous, aromatic flavour.

Roter Stettiner.name: Roter Stettiner
Roter Stettiner.description: Originated in Germany. First described in 1598 as Vineuse Rouge and first called Roter Stettiner in 1776. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid, sweet flavour.

Rouget de Born.name: Rouget de Born
Rouget de Born.description: Originated in Lozere, France. Described in 1947. Fruits have fine, rather soft, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Rough Pippin (Cornwall).name: Rough Pippin (Cornwall)
Rough Pippin (Cornwall).description: Originated in Somerset, England. In existence in 1884. Fruits have firm, rather dry flesh with an insipid flavour.

Roundway Magnum Bonum.name: Roundway Magnum Bonum
Roundway Magnum Bonum.description: Raised by Mr Joy, gardener at Roundway Park, Devizes, Wiltshire, England. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1864. Fruits have rather soft, somewhat coarse-textured flesh with a very sweet and pleasant flavour.

Roxbury Russet.name: Roxbury Russet
Roxbury Russet.description: Originated in the early 1600s in Roxbury, Massachusetts. Fruits have firm, somewhat coarse, fairly tender flesh with a subacid flavour.

Royal Gala.name: Royal Gala
Royal Gala.description: A more highly coloured clone of Gala. Discovered in 1971 by H.W. Ten Hove, New Zealand. Introduced in 1974 by D.W. McKenzie, Fruit Research Orchard, Havelock North, New Zealand. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy with an aromatic flavour.

Royal Jubilee.name: Royal Jubilee
Royal Jubilee.description: Raised by Mr John Graham of Hounslow, Middlesex. First recorded in 1888. Introduced by G. Bunyard & Co., Maidstone in 1893. Fruits have firm, yellow flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks well. Late flowering.

Rubens.name: Rubens
Rubens.description: Raised at the Horticultural Laboratory, Wageningen, Netherlands. Recorded in 1954 and introduced in 1955. Fruits have firm, fine flesh with a sweet flavour.

Rubin.name: Rubin
Rubin.description: Raised at the University of Agriculture, Prague, Czechoslovakia. Selected by O. Louda in 1960. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Rubinette.name: Rubinette
Rubinette.description: Raised in 1966 by Plant Breeder Walter Havenstein, Switzerland. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a good, aromatic flavour.

Rubinstar.name: Rubinstar
Rubinstar.description: Triploid. A more highly coloured clone of Jonagold which also matures one week earlier. Originated in 1980 at Gaiberg, Germany. Fruits have creamy white, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good rich flavour.

Ruby (Seabrook).name: Ruby (Seabrook)
Ruby (Seabrook).description: Raised by W. Seabrook & Sons Ltd., Boreham, Essex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1936. Fruits have rather soft, creamy white with pink tinge flesh with a sweet flavour.

Ruby (Thorrington).name: Ruby (Thorrington)
Ruby (Thorrington).description: Raised by F.W. Thorrington, a retired London Customs Officer, Hornchurch, Essex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have firm, sweet flesh with little flavour.

Ruby Rome Beauty.name: Ruby Rome Beauty
Ruby Rome Beauty.description: A more highly coloured clone of Rome Beauty. Discovered in about 1912 by M.F. Hubbs, in Hall Orchard, Milton-Freewater, Oregon, USA. Introduced in 1928. Fruits have creamy white, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with little flavour.

Rushock Pearmain.name: Rushock Pearmain
Rushock Pearmain.description: Raised in about 1821 by Mr Charles Taylor, a blacksmith, at Rushock, Worcestershire. Fruits have creamy white, firm, slightly juicy flesh with a 'nutty' flavour.

Russet Lambourne.name: Russet Lambourne
Russet Lambourne.description: A russetted clone of Lord Lambourne. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1971 from D.R. Atkins, Pulborough, West Sussex. Fruits have slightly coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Russet Superb.name: Russet Superb
Russet Superb.description: A russetted clone of Laxton's Superb. Discovered in 1963 by K. Maclean, Crabtree Fruit Farm, Kingston Bagpuize, Abingdon, Berkshire. Fruits have firm, very juicy flesh with a sweet and refreshing flavour.

S.T. Wright.name: S.T. Wright
S.T. Wright.description: Raised by J. Allgrove when employed by Veitch's nurseries. First recorded in 1913, in which year it received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with an acid flavour.

Sacramentsappel.name: Sacramentsappel
Sacramentsappel.description: Raised at the Plant Breeding Institute, Wageningen, Netherlands. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1955. Fruits have fine, tender, creamy white flesh with a subacid and slightly rich flavour.

Saint Ailred.name: Saint Ailred
Saint Ailred.description: Raised in 1942 at Mount Saint Bernard Abbey, Coalville, Leicestershire. Fruits have rather soft flesh with a sweetish, aromatic flavour.

Saint Albans Pippin.name: Saint Albans Pippin
Saint Albans Pippin.description: Originated in Kent, England. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have fine, tender, yellowish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Saint Cecilia.name: Saint Cecilia
Saint Cecilia.description: Raised by John Basham & Sons at Bassaleg, Monmouthshire, Wales in 1900. Introduced in 1918. Received an Award of Merit in 1918 and a First Class Certificate in 1919 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Saint Edmund's Pippin.name: Saint Edmund's Pippin
Saint Edmund's Pippin.description: Raised by R. Harvey at Bury St. Edmunds, England. Recorded in 1875. It received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1875. Fruits have moderately firm, juicy, slightly acid flesh with good flavour.

Saint Everard.name: Saint Everard
Saint Everard.description: Raised by C. Terry, gardener at Papworth Everard near Cambridge. Introduced in 1910 by Veitch. First recorded in 1900. Received Award of Merit in 1900 and a First Class Certificate in 1909 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have crisp, yellow flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Saint Lawrence.name: Saint Lawrence
Saint Lawrence.description: Originated in Montreal, Canada. It was well known in 1835. Fruits have tender, very white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Saint Martin's.name: Saint Martin's
Saint Martin's.description: Raised by Thomas Rivers, Sawbridgeworth, Herts. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1896. Fruits have sweet, soft flesh.

Saint-Baussan.name: Saint-Baussan
Saint-Baussan.description: Originated in France. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have coarse, sweet flesh.

Salome.name: Salome
Salome.description: Originated in Ottawa, Illinois, USA and introduced in 1884 by Arthur Bryant, Princetown, Illinois. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Saltcote Pippin.name: Saltcote Pippin
Saltcote Pippin.description: Raised by James Hoad at Rye, Sussex. First recorded in 1918. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1928. Fruits have firm, slightly juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Sam Young.name: Sam Young
Sam Young.description: Originated in Ireland. Brought to notice in England in 1818. Fruits have firm, rather tough, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sampion.name: Sampion
Sampion.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1974 from Prague University, Czechoslovakia. Fruits are sweet and juicy with a pleasant flavour.

San Peinte.name: San Peinte
San Peinte.description: Origin unknown. Fruits have fairly firm, crisp, tender flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Sandew.name: Sandew
Sandew.description: Originated in Somerset, England. Grafts from a very old tree were received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950. Fruits have soft, coarse, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sandlin Duchess.name: Sandlin Duchess
Sandlin Duchess.description: Raised in about 1880 at Sandlin, Malvern, England by H. Gabb. Introduced by William Crump. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1914. Fruits have fine, tender, creamy green flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Sandow.name: Sandow
Sandow.description: Selected in 1912 at the Central Experiment Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1935. Fruits have firm, coarse, tender, creamy white flesh with a sweet to fairly acid flavour.

Sandringham.name: Sandringham
Sandringham.description: Raised by gamekeeper Perry at Sandringham. Recorded in 1883 in which year it received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society. Introduced by Veitch. Fruits have soft, coarse, mealy flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sanspareil.name: Sanspareil
Sanspareil.description: Known in England since the late 1800s. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1899. Fruits have crisp, yellow flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Santana.name: Santana
Santana.description: Raised at the Centre for Plant Breeding Research, Wageningen, the Netherlands.

Saturn.name: Saturn
Saturn.description: Raised at East Malling Research Station, Kent by Dr Frank Alston. First selected in 1977. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a pleasant sweet flavour. Scab and mildew resistant.

Savstaholm.name: Savstaholm
Savstaholm.description: A chance seedling found in 1851 by nurseryman C.F. Rydstrom, Savstaholm, Sodermanland, Sweden. Fruits have crisp, tender, rather coarse flesh with a subacid to slightly sweet flavour.

Scarlet Crofton.name: Scarlet Crofton
Scarlet Crofton.description: Taken from England to Ireland in the late 1500s or early 1600s and reintroduced to England in 1819. Fruits have firm, somewhat coarse, white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Scarlet Nonpareil.name: Scarlet Nonpareil
Scarlet Nonpareil.description: Raised in about 1773 in the garden of an inn at Esher, Surrey. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1901. Fruits have fine, creamy white flesh with a subacid and rich flavour.

Scarlet Pearmain.name: Scarlet Pearmain
Scarlet Pearmain.description: Originated in England. Introduced in about 1800 by Bell, land agent at Sion House, Middlesex. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, yellowish flesh with a moderately sweet flavour.

Scarlet Staymared.name: Scarlet Staymared
Scarlet Staymared.description: An earlier colouring sport of Stayman's Winesap. Originated in 1930 with J.H.Dickey in Wenatchee, Washington, USA. Introduced in 1936. Fruits have firm, yellowish white flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet flavour.

Schmidtbergers Rote Reinette.name: Schmidtbergers Rote Reinette
Schmidtbergers Rote Reinette.description: Raised in about 1832 by Liegel at Braunau, Austria. It was named after Schmidtberger, a pomologist at St Florian monastery. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Schoner von Nordhausen.name: Schoner von Nordhausen
Schoner von Nordhausen.description: Raised in the early 1800s in the garden of Kaiser, Nordhausen, Germany. Introduced in 1892. Fruits have fine, moderately firm, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Schoolmaster.name: Schoolmaster
Schoolmaster.description: Said to have been raised from seed of a Canadian apple in Old Stamford Grammar School garden or in Herefordshire. Introduced in about 1880 by Thomas Laxton. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1880. Fruits have tender, coarse, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Schweizer Orange.name: Schweizer Orange
Schweizer Orange.description: Raised in 1935 at Eidg. Versuchsanstalt at Wadenswil, Switzerland. Released in 1955. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Scotch Bridget.name: Scotch Bridget
Scotch Bridget.description: Originated in Scotland. Described in 1851. Fruits have tender, soft, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Scotia.name: Scotia
Scotia.description: Raised at Kentville, Nova Scotia, Canada. Selected in 1948 and introduced in 1961. Fruits have soft, melting, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Seabrook's Red.name: Seabrook's Red
Seabrook's Red.description: Raised by W. Seabrook & Sons Ltd., Boreham, Essex. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have fairly firm, crisp, white flesh with a sweet and slightly aromatic flavour.

Seaton House.name: Seaton House
Seaton House.description: Raised at Seaton House, Arbroath, Scotland. Introduced in 1860. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Sensyu.name: Sensyu
Sensyu.description: Selected in 1984 at the Fruit Tree Experiment Station, Akita Prefecture, Japan. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh of excellent quality.

September Beauty.name: September Beauty
September Beauty.description: Raised by Laxton Bros. at Bedford, England. Recorded in 1885 in which year it received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have coarse, loose, creamy white flesh with a fairly sweet flavour.

Septer.name: Septer
Septer.description: Raised at IVT, Wageningen, Netherlands. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1977. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Sergeant Peggy.name: Sergeant Peggy
Sergeant Peggy.description: Raised in 1922 by F.W. Wastie at Eynsham, Oxford, England. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Serveau.name: Serveau
Serveau.description: Originated in France. Described in 1948. Fruits cook well, keeping shape.

Severn Bank.name: Severn Bank
Severn Bank.description: Originated in the UK. Grown in the valley of the Severn. Described in 1884. Fruits have tender, acid flesh.

Shamrock.name: Shamrock
Shamrock.description: Raised in 1970 by K. Lapins, at the Canadian Department Agricultural Research Station, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in 1986. Fruits have soft, sweet flesh.

Sharleston Pippin.name: Sharleston Pippin
Sharleston Pippin.description: Originated in Yorkshire, England. Recorded in 1888. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Sharon.name: Sharon
Sharon.description: Raised in 1906 by S.A. Beach, Iowa State Agricultural Experiment Station, Ames, USA. Introduced in 1922. Fruits have crisp, fine, tender, whitish green flesh with a sweet flavour.

Sheep's Nose (3).name: Sheep's Nose (3)
Sheep's Nose (3).description: Originated in the UK. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951. Fruits have hard, dry, yellowish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Shenandoah.name: Shenandoah
Shenandoah.description: Raised in 1942 by R.C. Moore, Virginia Polytechnic Institute, Blacksburg, USA. Introduced in 1967. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a slightly perfumed and aromatic flavour.

Shin Indo.name: Shin Indo
Shin Indo.description: Raised in 1930 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Named in 1948. Fruits have firm, dry, cream tinged green flesh with a sweet flavour.

Shinko.name: Shinko
Shinko.description: Raised in 1931 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Fruits have crisp, greenish white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Shinsei.name: Shinsei
Shinsei.description: Raised in 1930 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Named in 1948. Fruits have crisp, white flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Shoesmith.name: Shoesmith
Shoesmith.description: Raised by George Carpenter at Byfleet, Surrey, England. First exhibited in 1930. Fruits have very white, tinged green, soft, very juicy flesh with a subacid flavour. Cooks well.

Shoreditch White.name: Shoreditch White
Shoreditch White.description: Originated in Somerset, England. Described in 1884. Fruits have tender, yellowish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Siddington Russet.name: Siddington Russet
Siddington Russet.description: A russetted sport of Galloway Pippin. Discovered in 1923 by John Jeffries & Sons Ltd., at Siddington, Gloucestershire. Fruits have firm, crisp, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sidney Strake.name: Sidney Strake
Sidney Strake.description: A less highly coloured sport of Tom Putt. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1954 from Cornwall. Fruits have firm, fine, whitish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Signe Tillisch.name: Signe Tillisch
Signe Tillisch.description: Raised in about 1866 by Councillor Tillisch and named after his daughter. First described in 1889. Fruits have loose, soft, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Sikulai-alma.name: Sikulai-alma
Sikulai-alma.description: Originated in Hungary. First recorded in 1875. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white to cream flesh with a subacid flavour.

Silva.name: Silva
Silva.description: Raised in 1945 at Alnarp Agricultural College, Sweden. Introduced in 1970. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet almost strawberry like flavour.

Simonffy Piros.name: Simonffy Piros
Simonffy Piros.description: Originated in Hungary. Recorded in 1876. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a very sweet, subacid, perfumed, strawberry like flavour.

Sinta.name: Sinta
Sinta.description: Raised in 1955 at Canada Department Agricultural Research Station, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada by K.O. Lapins. Fruits have fairly firm, crisp, cream, juicy flesh.

Sir John Thornycroft.name: Sir John Thornycroft
Sir John Thornycroft.description: Raised by Collister, gardener to Sir John Thornycroft, Bembridge, Isle of Wight. Introduced in 1913 by Bunyard of Maidstone. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1911. Fruits have hard, tough, coarse flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Sir Prize.name: Sir Prize
Sir Prize.description: Raised in 1955 by Agricultural Experiment Station, Indiana, Illinois and New Jersey, USA. First fruited in 1961. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy. Resistant to scab.

Sissons's Worksop Newtown.name: Sissons's Worksop Newtown
Sissons's Worksop Newtown.description: Raised in about 1910 by Mr Sissons, Worksop, Nottinghamshire. Fruits have soft, coarse, greenish white flesh with a subacid to acid flavour.

Skinlite.name: Skinlite
Skinlite.description: Raised in 1947 by R. Carlone, University of Turin, Italy. Introduced in 1973. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Skovfoged.name: Skovfoged
Skovfoged.description: Thought to have originated in Denmark. Known in the early 1800s. Fruits have firm, fine, rather dry flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Slavyanka.name: Slavyanka
Slavyanka.description: Raised in 1899 by I.V. Michurin, Russia. First fruited in 1896. Fruits have fine, white flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Sleeping Beauty.name: Sleeping Beauty
Sleeping Beauty.description: Originated in Lincolnshire. Described in 1851. Fruits have crisp, tender, yellowish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Small's Admirable.name: Small's Admirable
Small's Admirable.description: Raised in about 1850 by F. Small, nurseryman, Colnbrook, Slough, Berkshire, England. Fruits have firm, crisp, almost white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Smart's Prince Arthur.name: Smart's Prince Arthur
Smart's Prince Arthur.description: Raised by Smart, near Sittingbourne, Kent. First described in 1883. Fruits have extremely firm, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a fairly sweet, little acid and no distinctive flavour.

Smiler.name: Smiler
Smiler.description: Raised at Clandon, Surrey by A. Simmonds. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have firm, moderately crisp, fine, white tinged green flesh with a moderately sweet, slightly acid, slightly bitter flavour.

Smoothee.name: Smoothee
Smoothee.description: A larger, firmer, less russetted clone of Golden Delicious. Discovered in 1958 growing in the orchard of C. Gibson, Evans City, Pennsylvania, USA. Fruits have crisp, sweet, juicy flesh with a good aromatic flavour.

Snovit.name: Snovit
Snovit.description: Raised in 1936 by Emil Johansson at Alnarp, Sweden. Fruits have very soft, snow-white tinged pink flesh with a sweet and slightly perfumed flavour.

Sops-in-Wine (1).name: Sops-in-Wine (1)
Sops-in-Wine (1).description: A very old English culinary and cider apple.The flesh of the fruits is red as if soaked in red wine and is sweet, juicy and pleasantly flavoured.

South Park.name: South Park
South Park.description: Raised in about 1940 by W. Barkway, gardener at South Park, Penshurst, Kent. Fruits have crisp, cream tinged green flesh with an acid flavour.

Sovari Comun.name: Sovari Comun
Sovari Comun.description: Originated in Romania. Recorded in 1876. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Sovari Nobil (of Romania).name: Sovari Nobil (of Romania)
Sovari Nobil (of Romania).description: Originated in Hungary. Distributed in 1880 when it was already known to be old. Fruits have tender, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sowman's Seedling.name: Sowman's Seedling
Sowman's Seedling.description: Raised in 1914 at the County Horticulture Station, Hutton, Lancashire by Sowman. Introduced and named in 1927 by the Lancashire Agricultural Committee. Acquired by Rivers Nurseries of Sawbridgeworth, Herts. Fruits have fairly firm, fine, yellowish white tinged green flesh with an acid flavour.

Spaanse Keiing.name: Spaanse Keiing
Spaanse Keiing.description: Originated in East Flanders, Belgium. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, whitish flesh with an acid flavour.

Spartan.name: Spartan
Spartan.description: Raised in 1926 by R.C.Palmer at the Dominion Experiment Station, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in 1936. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a refreshing vinous flavour.

Spatbluhender Taffetapfel.name: Spatbluhender Taffetapfel
Spatbluhender Taffetapfel.description: Raised in the nursery of Hohenheim Agricultural Institute, Germany. Introduced by Lucas. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have fine, white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Spencer.name: Spencer
Spencer.description: Raised in 1926 by R.C.Palmer at the Dominion Experiment Station, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in 1959. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet, pleasant and slightly vinous flavour.

Spigold.name: Spigold
Spigold.description: Triploid. Raised at the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Fruits have fine-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Spijon.name: Spijon
Spijon.description: Raised in 1944 at New York Agricultural Experimental Station, Geneva, USA. Introduced in 1968. Fruits have firm, light yellow flesh with a subacid to slightly acid flavour.

Spiza.name: Spiza
Spiza.description: Raised or introduced in 1916 in Ottawa, Canada. Fruits have crisp, coarse, yellowish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Splendour.name: Splendour
Splendour.description: Discovered in 1948 by Charles L. Roberts, Napier, New Zealand. Introduced in 1967. Fruits have firm, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, subacid and a little rich flavour.

Stafner Rosen.name: Stafner Rosen
Stafner Rosen.description: Thought to be of American origin. Described in 1924. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Stanway Seedling.name: Stanway Seedling
Stanway Seedling.description: Originated in Essex, England. Recorded in 1899, in which year it received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have rather soft flesh with an acid flavour.

Star of Devon.name: Star of Devon
Star of Devon.description: Raised by J. Garland, Broadclyst, Devon. Introduced by George Pyne, Topsham. Recorded in 1905 in which year it received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have soft, greenish white flesh with a rather acid and faint aromatic flavour.

Stark EarliBlaze.name: Stark EarliBlaze
Stark EarliBlaze.description: Discovered in 1949 at New Lennox, Illinois, USA by Worth B. Mooney. Introduced in 1957. Fruits have rather soft, coarse, yellow flesh with a subacid flavour.

Stark's Earliest.name: Stark's Earliest
Stark's Earliest.description: Discovered by Douglas Bonner at Orofino, Idaho, USA in 1938. Introduced in 1944. Fruits have crisp, fine-textured, white, fairly juicy flesh with a little sweet and fair flavour.

Stark's Late Delicious.name: Stark's Late Delicious
Stark's Late Delicious.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1967 from Scotland. Fruits have very sweet, cream tinged green flesh.

Starking.name: Starking
Starking.description: A more highly coloured clone of Delicious. Discovered in 1921 by Lewis Mood at Monroeville, New Jersey, USA. Introduced in 1924. Fruits have firm, fine, yellow flesh with a sweet flavour.

Starkrimson Delicious.name: Starkrimson Delicious
Starkrimson Delicious.description: A more highly coloured and taller fruited clone of Starking. Discovered in about 1953 by Roy A. Bisbee, Hood River, Oregon, USA. Introduced in 1956 by Stark Bros. Fruits have firm, very sweet, juicy flesh with a highly aromatic flavour.

Starkspur Golden Delicious.name: Starkspur Golden Delicious
Starkspur Golden Delicious.description: A bud mutation of Golden Delicious producing spur type tree growth. Discovered by Philip J. Jenkins in Yakima, Washington, USA. Fruits have sweet, crisp, juicy flesh with a good flavour.

Starkspur McIntosh.name: Starkspur McIntosh
Starkspur McIntosh.description: A bud mutation of McIntosh producing spur type tree growth. Discovered in 1968 by Bernie Gatzke in Oyama, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in Canada in 1970. Fruits have white, rather soft, fine-textured, very juicy flesh, with a sweet, pleasant vinous flavour.

Starr.name: Starr
Starr.description: Found on the property of Judge White, Woodbury, New Jersey, USA. Propagated by William Parry in 1865. Fruits have crisp, very tender flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

State Fair.name: State Fair
State Fair.description: Raised in 1949 by W.H. Alderman at the University of Minnesota Horticulture Research Centre, Excelsior, USA. Fruits are crisp and juicy with an aromatic flavour. A very hardy variety, trees withstanding winter temperatures of minus 40

Statesman Red Sport.name: Statesman Red Sport
Statesman Red Sport.description: A red sport of Australian variety 'Statesman'. Discovered in New Zealand. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1960. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Stearns.name: Stearns
Stearns.description: Originated with Stearns of North Syracuse, New York, USA. Distributed by Van Dusen of Geneva, New York. Recorded in 1900. Fruits have crisp, tender, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Steirischer Roter Marschansker.name: Steirischer Roter Marschansker
Steirischer Roter Marschansker.description: Appears to be a form of Steirischer Marschansker. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1951 from Germany. Fruits have firm, crisp, slightly coarse, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Stevenson Wealthy.name: Stevenson Wealthy
Stevenson Wealthy.description: A bud mutation of Wealthy producing larger fruit. Discovered in 1934 in Cayuga, New York, USA by J.R. Stevenson. Fruits have rather soft, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and faint vinous flavour.

Steyne Seedling.name: Steyne Seedling
Steyne Seedling.description: Raised in about 1893 at Steyne, Isle of Wight, home of Sir John Thornycroft. Received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912. Fruits have soft, tender, juicy flesh with a subacid flavour.

Stirling Castle.name: Stirling Castle
Stirling Castle.description: Raised by John Christie, nurseryman at Causeyhead, Scotland. Introduced by Drummond of Stirling, Scotland. First recorded in 1831. Fruits have white, very soft, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with an acid flavour.

Stobo Castle.name: Stobo Castle
Stobo Castle.description: Believed to have originated in Scotland. It was introduced in about 1900 by Storrie of Glencarse. Fruits have crisp, white, slightly coarse-textured flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Stoke Edith Pippin.name: Stoke Edith Pippin
Stoke Edith Pippin.description: Thought to have originated at Stoke Edith, Herefordshire. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellow flesh with a subacid, sweet and perfumed flavour.

Stonecrop.name: Stonecrop
Stonecrop.description: Raised at Ottawa Experimental Farm, Canada. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1927. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender, fine flesh with a sweet flavour.

Stonehenge.name: Stonehenge
Stonehenge.description: Raised at Ottawa Experimental Farm, Canada. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1927. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured flesh with a sweet and slightly acid flavour.

Stonetosh.name: Stonetosh
Stonetosh.description: Raised in 1909 by Horticulture Division, Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1923. Fruits have rather soft, white flesh with a moderately sweet and slightly acid flavour.

Storey's Seedling.name: Storey's Seedling
Storey's Seedling.description: Raised in 1927 by R.O.C. Storey, Northolt Park, Middlesex, England. Fruits have somewhat soft, white flesh with a sweet and slightly subacid flavour.

Stowell Cox.name: Stowell Cox
Stowell Cox.description: Raised at CSIRO, Stowell Avenue, Hobart, Tasmania. Fruits have white, fairly juicy flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Strawberry Pippin.name: Strawberry Pippin
Strawberry Pippin.description: Origin unknown. Recorded in 1874. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.

Striped Beefing.name: Striped Beefing
Striped Beefing.description: Found by George Lindley in the garden of William Crowe, Lakenham, Norwich, England in 1794. Distributed in 1847. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured, moderately juicy flesh with a fairly acid flavour.

Strippy.name: Strippy
Strippy.description: Originated in County Armagh, Ireland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1949. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Sturmer Pippin.name: Sturmer Pippin
Sturmer Pippin.description: Raised by nurseryman Dillistone at Sturmer, Suffolk, England. First recorded in 1831. Fruits have very firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a little subacid and rich aromatic flavour.

Summer Broaden.name: Summer Broaden
Summer Broaden.description: Originated in England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have coarse, soft, cream flesh with a subacid flavour.

Summer Golden Pippin.name: Summer Golden Pippin
Summer Golden Pippin.description: Originated in England. Known before 1800. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, subacid, rich flavour.

Summer John.name: Summer John
Summer John.description: Originated in County Fermanagh, Ireland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1949 but thought to be much older than this. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Summer Rose.name: Summer Rose
Summer Rose.description: Originated in New Jersey, USA. Mentioned in 1806. Fruits have tender, fine, white flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

Summer Stibbert.name: Summer Stibbert
Summer Stibbert.description: Originated in the West of England. Recorded in 1831. Fruits have firm, tender, creamy white flesh with a slightly subacid flavour.

SummerGlo.name: SummerGlo
SummerGlo.description: Discovered in 1935 in Calhoun County, Michigan, USA by F.H. McDermid. Introduced by Stark Bros. in 1967. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a pleasant vinous flavour.

Summerland.name: Summerland
Summerland.description: Raised in 1926 by K.O. Lapins, at Canada Department of Agriculture, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Fruits have juicy, melting flesh. Flavour is poor in U.K. ripened fruits.

Summerred.name: Summerred
Summerred.description: Raised by K.O. Lapins at Canada Department of Agriculture, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Named and introduced in 1964. Fruits have rather soft, very juicy and refreshing flesh with a mild vinous flavour.

Sunburn.name: Sunburn
Sunburn.description: Raised at Hornchurch, Essex, by F.W. Thorrington. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1925. Fruits have soft, creamy white flesh with a sweet, subacid, aromatic flavour.

Sungold.name: Sungold
Sungold.description: Found in 1960 by Alfred & Anthony Caggiano at Bridgetown, New Jersey, USA. Resembles Golden Delicious but has little or no russet.

Sunrise.name: Sunrise
Sunrise.description: Thought to have been raised at Welford Park, Berkshire, England. Recorded in 1897. Fruits have soft, tender, whitish flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Sunrise (Canada).name: Sunrise (Canada)
Sunrise (Canada).description: Raised at the Canadian Department Agricultural Research Station, Summerland, British Columbia, Canada. Introduced in 1991. Fruits have crisp flesh with a strawberry like flavour. Some resistance to mildew.

Sunset.name: Sunset
Sunset.description: Raised in about 1918 by G.C.Addy at Ightham, Kent. Named in 1933. It received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1960. Fruits have firm crisp, fine-textured flesh with a good aromatic Cox-like flavour.

Sunset Sport.name: Sunset Sport
Sunset Sport.description: A more highly coloured sport of Sunset. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1963 from Loughgall Horticultural Centre, Armagh, Northern Ireland. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine-textured flesh with a good aromatic Cox-like flavour.

Suntan.name: Suntan
Suntan.description: Triploid. Raised in 1955 by Dr Alston at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Fruits have slightly coarse-textured, moderately juicy flesh with an aromatic but acid flavour. Rather prone to bitter pit.

Sussex Mother.name: Sussex Mother
Sussex Mother.description: Originated in Sussex, England. Described in 1884. Fruits have soft, tender, greenish white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Swaar.name: Swaar
Swaar.description: Said to have been raised by Dutch settlers near Esopus on the Hudson River, USA. Recorded in 1804. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Sweet Caroline.name: Sweet Caroline
Sweet Caroline.description: Raised in 1954 by A.A. Schaap, IVT, Wageningen, Netherlands. Fruits have fairly firm, white, juicy flesh with a very sweet, rather bland flavour.

Sweet Cornelly.name: Sweet Cornelly
Sweet Cornelly.description: Raised in 1954 by A.A. Schaap, IVT, Wageningen, Netherlands. Fruits have white, firm, rather tough flesh with a moderately juicy and sweet flavour.

Sweet Delicious.name: Sweet Delicious
Sweet Delicious.description: Raised in 1911 at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA by R. Wellington. Fruits have firm, fine, creamy white flesh with a sweet, aromatic flavour.

Sweet-Tart.name: Sweet-Tart
Sweet-Tart.description: A seedling of unknown parentage raised by Robert Gordon, Gordon Apple Trees, Whittier, California, USA. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a very sweet flavour.

Sylvia.name: Sylvia
Sylvia.description: Raised at Balsgard Agricultural College, Sweden. Fruits have crisp, juicy flesh with an aromatic flavour.

Szacsvay Tafota.name: Szacsvay Tafota
Szacsvay Tafota.description: Originated in Transylvania, Hungary. Recorded in 1876. Fruits have crisp, somewhat coarse flesh with a slightly sweet and subacid flavour.

Szaszpap alma.name: Szaszpap alma
Szaszpap alma.description: Originated in Hungary. Described in 1909. Fruits have crisp, fine, white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Szechenyi Renet.name: Szechenyi Renet
Szechenyi Renet.description: Originated in Hungary. Recorded in 1876. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Tare de Ghinda.name: Tare de Ghinda
Tare de Ghinda.description: Originated in Ghinda, Bistrita, Romania. Known to be very old. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with a sweet to subacid flavour.

Tasman Pride.name: Tasman Pride
Tasman Pride.description: Originated in the late 1800s on the farm of Thomas Young, Margate, Tasmania, Australia. Fruits have crisp, sweet flesh.

Taunton Cross.name: Taunton Cross
Taunton Cross.description: Raised in 1919 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. Fruits have firm, crisp, somewhat coarse, white flesh with a moderately sweet, slightly acid flavour.

Teint Frais.name: Teint Frais
Teint Frais.description: Originated in Brittany, France. Known since the late 1700s. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with an acid flavour.

Telamon.name: Telamon
Telamon.description: Raised in 1976 at East Malling Research Station, East Malling, Kent. Introduced in 1989. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Tellisaare.name: Tellisaare
Tellisaare.description: Raised at Pavlovsk Experimental Station, Russia. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1976 from the Vavilov Institute. Fruits have soft, white flesh.

Telstar.name: Telstar
Telstar.description: Raised in 1934 at Greytown, Wairarapa, New Zealand by J.H. Kidd. Named in 1965. Fruits have firm, coarse flesh with a sweet, slightly acid and rich flavour.

Testerspur Golden Delicious.name: Testerspur Golden Delicious
Testerspur Golden Delicious.description: Dessert. November-February. A spur type clone of Golden Delicious. Received by the National Fruit Trials from Wilhelminadorp, Netherlands. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Teton de Demoiselle.name: Teton de Demoiselle
Teton de Demoiselle.description: Thought to have originated in France. Recorded in 1872. Fruits have rather soft, dry, yellowish white tinged red flesh with a subacid flavour.

Tewkesbury Baron.name: Tewkesbury Baron
Tewkesbury Baron.description: Thought to have originated in Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have a little coarse, dry, white flesh with an insipid flavour.

Texola.name: Texola
Texola.description: Raised by Mr Broome, Utah, USA. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1930. Fruits have soft, white tinged green flesh with a subacid flavour.

Thoday's Quarrenden.name: Thoday's Quarrenden
Thoday's Quarrenden.description: Found in 1949 by R.E.Thoday at Reedground Farm, Willingham, Cambridge. Fruits have tender, creamy white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Thomas Jeffrey.name: Thomas Jeffrey
Thomas Jeffrey.description: Raised by D.W. Thomson, Edinburgh, Scotland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1923. Received an award from the Royal Caledonian Society some years before 1923. Fruits have tender, greenish white flesh with a subacid and a little bitter flavour.

Thomas Rivers.name: Thomas Rivers
Thomas Rivers.description: Raised by Rivers of Sawbridgeworth, England and named Rivers' Codlin. Recorded in 1892 in which year it received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society. Introduced in 1894. Name changed to Thomas Rivers, the raiser of the apple, in 1897. Fruits have firm, crisp, creamy yellow flesh with an acid flavour.

Thompson's Apple.name: Thompson's Apple
Thompson's Apple.description: Originated in Ireland. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1950. Fruits have fine, crisp, firm, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Thorle Pippin.name: Thorle Pippin
Thorle Pippin.description: Originated in Scotland. Described in 1831. Fruits have soft, dry, yellowish white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Thorpe's Peach.name: Thorpe's Peach
Thorpe's Peach.description: Raised in 1899 by Miss Goodwin at the nurseries of E.J. Thorpe, Brackley, Northamptonshire. Introduced in 1927. Fruits have firm, moderately crisp, fine, white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Thurgauer Weinapfel.name: Thurgauer Weinapfel
Thurgauer Weinapfel.description: Originated in Thurgau, Switzerland. Known in Thurgau since the 1860's. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, yellowish flesh with a sweet-sour, aromatic flavour.

Thurso.name: Thurso
Thurso.description: Raised in 1898 at Central Experimental Farm, Ottawa, Canada. Introduced in 1908.

Tiffen.name: Tiffen
Tiffen.description: Originated in the North West of England. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have somewhat soft, coarse, white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Titovka.name: Titovka
Titovka.description: Originated in Ukraine, Russia. Recorded in 1876 but said to be older. Fruits have coarse, tender, yellowish white flesh with a vinous, subacid flavour.

Tobiasler.name: Tobiasler
Tobiasler.description: Originated with Tobias Schmidheini, in Canton of Baselland, Switzerland. Known in 1805. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, greenish flesh with a very acid and aromatic flavour.

Tom Putt.name: Tom Putt
Tom Putt.description: A culinary and cider apple. Raised by Rev. Tom Putt, Rector of Trent, Somerset in the late 1700s. In use from September to November. Fruits have crisp, juicy, acid flesh. Cooks well. Produces a sharp cider.

Tommy Knight.name: Tommy Knight
Tommy Knight.description: Originated in St. Angus, Cornwall. Recorded in 1861. Fruits have hard, crisp flesh with a sweet flavour.

Tonino.name: Tonino
Tonino.description: Raised at the Centre for Plant Breeding Research, Wageningen, the Netherlands.

Totem.name: Totem
Totem.description: Ornamental columnar apple.Raised in 1983 by Mr K. Tobutt, East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent.

Tower of Glamis (Scott).name: Tower of Glamis (Scott)
Tower of Glamis (Scott).description: Originated in Scotland. Known before 1800. Fruits have crisp, fairly fine, firm, greenish white flesh with an acid and perfumed flavour.

Toyo.name: Toyo
Toyo.description: Raised by Junichiro, Nishiya, Aomori Prefecture, Japan and introduced by them in 1935. Fruits have medium textured flesh with a moderately sweet, subacid and perfumed flavour.

Trajan.name: Trajan
Trajan.description: Raised in 1976 at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Introduced in 1989. Fruits are sweet, crisp and juicy.

Transparente de Croncels.name: Transparente de Croncels
Transparente de Croncels.description: Raised by Ernest Baltet and introduced in 1869 by Baltet FrFres, Croncels, Troyes, France. Fruits have soft, rather coarse, dry, creamy white flesh with a sweetish and slightly aromatic flavour.

Trelage.name: Trelage
Trelage.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm, crisp, fine, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Tropical Beauty.name: Tropical Beauty
Tropical Beauty.description: Raised in about 1930 by Meredith B. Strapp, Maidstone, South Africa. First distributed in 1953 by F.B. Harrington. Named and introduced in Australia in 1958 by Longbecker Nurseries, Bunderburg. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, yellowish white flesh with a sweetish flavour.

Trotuse.name: Trotuse
Trotuse.description: Originated in the Trotuse Valley, Romania. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1948. Fruits have spongy, dry, greenish white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Tsugaru.name: Tsugaru
Tsugaru.description: Raised in 1930 at Aomori Apple Experiment Station, Japan. Introduced in 1975. Fruits have firm, juicy flesh with a mild, sweet flavour.

Tukker.name: Tukker
Tukker.description: Raised by N. Hubbeling, Wageningen, Netherlands. Received at Brogdale in 1994. Fruits have firm, crisp flesh. Resistant to scab and mildew.

Tupstones.name: Tupstones
Tupstones.description: Originated in Worcestershire, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1945. Fruits have firm, fine, yellowish white flesh with a subacid and nutty flavour.

Tuscan.name: Tuscan
Tuscan.description: Raised in 1976 at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent. Introduced in 1989. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Twenty Ounce.name: Twenty Ounce
Twenty Ounce.description: Thought to have originated in either New York or Connecticut, USA. Brought to notice in about 1844. Fruits have coarse, moderately tender flesh with a subacid flavour.

Tydeman's Early Worcester.name: Tydeman's Early Worcester
Tydeman's Early Worcester.description: Raised in 1929 by H.M. Tydeman at East Malling Research Station, Kent. Introduced in 1945. Fruits have white, crisp, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a good vinous flavour.

Tydeman's Harvest.name: Tydeman's Harvest
Tydeman's Harvest.description: Raised in 1930 at East Malling Research Station, Maidstone, Kent by H.M. Tydeman. Fruits are sweet.

Tydeman's Late Orange.name: Tydeman's Late Orange
Tydeman's Late Orange.description: Raised in 1930 by H.M. Tydeman at East Malling Research Station, Kent. Introduced in 1949. Fruits have very firm, crisp, fairly juicy, cream flesh with a rich, aromatic flavour.

Tydeman's Michaelmas Red.name: Tydeman's Michaelmas Red
Tydeman's Michaelmas Red.description: Raised in 1929 by H.M. Tydeman at East Malling Research Station, Kent. Fruits have greenish white, rather soft, very juicy flesh with a sweet refreshing vinous flavour.

Tyler's Kernel.name: Tyler's Kernel
Tyler's Kernel.description: Brought to notice in 1883 by Mr Tyler of Hereford, England. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1883. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender, yellowish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Uland.name: Uland
Uland.description: Raised by William Ingall, Grimoldby, Lincolnshire, England. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1922. Fruits have firm, fine, greenish white flesh with a very acid flavour.

Undine.name: Undine
Undine.description: Raised by Professor M. Schmidt, Agricultural Research Station, Muncheberg, Germany. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1977. Fruits have soft flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Woodford.name: Woodford
Woodford.description: Originated in Essex, England. Known in about 1900. Fruits have coarse, soft, pale cream flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet and slightly perfumed flavour.

Upton Pyne.name: Upton Pyne
Upton Pyne.description: Raised by Pyne of Topsham, Devon. Introduced in 1910. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a somewhat acid and fair flavour.

Vanda.name: Vanda
Vanda.description: Raised at the Experimental Botany Station, Strizovice, Czechoslovakia. Fruited in 1983. Fruits have juicy, soft flesh. Resistant to scab and mildew.

Vegi Cox.name: Vegi Cox
Vegi Cox.description: A clone of Cox's Orange Pippin. Received at Brogdale from nurseryman, J. Nicolai, Belgium.

Venus Pippin.name: Venus Pippin
Venus Pippin.description: Thought to have been raised in about 1800 in Devon, England. Fruits have tender, soft, coarse, creamy white flesh with a slightly sweet, slightly acid flavour.

Verite.name: Verite
Verite.description: Originated in France. Recorded in 1876. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with a slightly sweet, subacid flavour.

Vernade.name: Vernade
Vernade.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm, fine, yellowish white flesh with a very acid flavour.

Vernajoux.name: Vernajoux
Vernajoux.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm, tough, white tinged green flesh with a slightly sweet flavour.

Vicar of Beighton.name: Vicar of Beighton
Vicar of Beighton.description: Said to have been raised at Beighton, near Norwich, England. Recorded in 1894. Fruits have soft, fine, pale greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Vicking.name: Vicking
Vicking.description: Parentage includes Jonathan, Delicious, Williams Early Red, Early McIntosh and Starr. Raised by nurseryman G.W. Gurney, Yankton, South Dakota, USA. Introduced in 1925. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh.

Victory (Carpenter).name: Victory (Carpenter)
Victory (Carpenter).description: Raised at Byfleet, England by George Carpenter. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1923. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh with an acid flavour.

Victory (USA).name: Victory (USA)
Victory (USA).description: Raised by C. Haralson, Minnesota Agricultural Experimental Station, Excelsior, USA. Introduced in 1943. Fruits have crisp, juicy sweet flesh with a strawberry like flavour.

Vincent.name: Vincent
Vincent.description: Originated in France. Described in 1947. Fruits have firm, crisp, creamy white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Violette.name: Violette
Violette.description: Originated in France. Known in the early 1600s. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh with a subacid and slightly aromatic flavour.

Vista Bella.name: Vista Bella
Vista Bella.description: Complex parentage involving Julyred, Williams Early Red and Starr. Raised in 1956 at New Jersey Agricultural Experiment Station, New Brunswick, New Jersey, USA. Named because of its exceptional behaviour in the Guatemalan highlands. Fruits have creamy white, juicy flesh with a McIntosh type flavour.

Vitgylling.name: Vitgylling
Vitgylling.description: Originated in Northern Europe. Described in 1816. Fruits have crisp, yellowish flesh with an acid flavour.

Von Zuccalmaglios Renette.name: Von Zuccalmaglios Renette
