Von Zuccalmaglios Renette.description: Raised in 1878 at Grevenbroich, Germany by Diedrich Uhlhorm junior. Fruits have fine, firm, rather dry, yellowish white flesh with a sweet subacid flavour.

Voyager.name: Voyager
Voyager.description: Raised in 1952 by Mr A.R. King, Barnet, Hertfordshire. Fruits have soft, sweet flesh.

Wadey's Seedling.name: Wadey's Seedling
Wadey's Seedling.description: Raised in 1919 at Caterham, Surrey, by W.J. Wadey. Fruits have firm, creamy white flesh.

Wadhurst Pippin.name: Wadhurst Pippin
Wadhurst Pippin.description: Originated in the early 1800s at Wadhurst, Sussex. Fruits have crisp, yellowish flesh with a subacid flavour.

Wagener.name: Wagener
Wagener.description: Raised by George Wheeler at Penn Yann, New York, USA in 1791 and taken over by Abraham Wagener. Fruits have firm, moderately juicy flesh with a pleasant flavour.

Wang Young.name: Wang Young
Wang Young.description: Originated in South Korea. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1967. Fruits have soft, juicy, sweet flesh.

Wardington Seedling.name: Wardington Seedling
Wardington Seedling.description: Raised at Banbury, Oxfordshire by D. Burchnell, gardener to Lady Wardington. First fruited in about 1938. Fruits have crisp, tender, fine flesh with a subacid flavour.

Warner's King.name: Warner's King
Warner's King.description: Believed to have originated in Kent. Known since the late 1700s (prior name King Apple). It was sent by Warner to Rivers Nursery who gave it the distinguishing prefix. Fruits have rather soft, a little coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a very acid flavour. Cooks well.

Warren's Seedling.name: Warren's Seedling
Warren's Seedling.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1934. Fruits have somewhat coarse, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Washington Strawberry.name: Washington Strawberry
Washington Strawberry.description: Raised on the farm of Job Whipple at Union Springs, Washington County, New York, USA. First exhibited in 1849. Fruits have rather soft, coarse-textured, juicy flesh with a little sweet and very little flavour.

Wayne.name: Wayne
Wayne.description: Raised at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Selected in 1951 and introduced in 1962. Fruits have soft, cream flesh.

Wayside.name: Wayside
Wayside.description: Raised in 1930 by Miss Cunningham at Cambridge. Fruits have white, tinged green flesh with a sweet flavour.

Wealthy.name: Wealthy
Wealthy.description: Raised by Peter M. Gideon at Excelsior, Minnesota, USA from Cherry Crab open-pollinated. First recorded in 1860. Received an Award of Merit from Royal Horticultural Society in 1893. Fruits have rather soft, coarse-textured, juicy, sweet flesh with a faint vinous flavour.

Webster.name: Webster
Webster.description: Raised in 1912 by R. Wellington at New York State Agricultural Experiment Station, Geneva, USA. Introduced in 1938. Fruits have soft, coarse, greenish white flesh with a slightly acid flavour.

Weidners Goldreinette.name: Weidners Goldreinette
Weidners Goldreinette.description: Raised in 1844 by Weidner, Gerasmuhle, near Nurnberg, Germany. Fruits have fine, tender, crisp, yellowish flesh with a rich, sweet, subacid flavour.

Weisser Winter Taffetapfel.name: Weisser Winter Taffetapfel
Weisser Winter Taffetapfel.description: Originated in Germany. Recorded in 1800. Fruits have tender, fine, white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Weisses Seidenhemdchen.name: Weisses Seidenhemdchen
Weisses Seidenhemdchen.description: Originated in Europe. Described in 1598. Fruits have rather soft, fine, white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Wellspur Delicious.name: Wellspur Delicious
Wellspur Delicious.description: A sport of Starking having a more solid red flush. Discovered in 1952 by Lester Green and Clifford Nelson in the Azwell Orchard of the Wells and Wade Fruit Company, Wenatchee, Washington, USA. Introduced in 1958. Fruits have very firm, very sweet, juicy flesh with a highly aromatic flavour.

Welschisner.name: Welschisner
Welschisner.description: Originated in Germany. Recorded in 1889. Fruits have firm, greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

West View Seedling.name: West View Seedling
West View Seedling.description: Discovered in 1932 in Billericay, Essex, England by F.W. Rainbird. Fruits have firm, rather dry, greenish white flesh with an insipid flavour.

Westfield Seek-no-Further.name: Westfield Seek-no-Further
Westfield Seek-no-Further.description: Originated in Westfield, Massachusetts, USA. Known in 1796. Fruits have a little soft, fine, yellowish white flesh with a sweet and slightly aromatic flavour.

Wheeler's Russet.name: Wheeler's Russet
Wheeler's Russet.description: Originated in England. Known in 1717. Fruits have a little soft, greenish white flesh with a subacid, slightly sweet and slightly aromatic flavour.

White Quarrenden.name: White Quarrenden
White Quarrenden.description: Exhibited by Veitch, Exeter, Devon. Recorded in 1831. Fruits have soft, sweetish flesh.

White Transparent.name: White Transparent
White Transparent.description: Introduced to Western Europe in the mid 1800s from Russia or the Baltic States. Fruits have white, rather coarse-textured flesh with an acid and a little sweet flavour. Soon becomes woolly and dry.

White Winter Pearmain (Graaf).name: White Winter Pearmain (Graaf)
White Winter Pearmain (Graaf).description: Thought to have originated in the eastern states, USA. Recorded in 1849. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender, fine flesh with a subacid and aromatic flavour.

Wickham Green.name: Wickham Green
Wickham Green.description: Grafts were taken in 1913 from a tree in Wickham, Berkshire, by Pope of Wokingham. This tree is thought to have been in existence in about 1860. Fruits have fine, firm, white flesh with a little acid flavour.

Widdup.name: Widdup
Widdup.description: Originated in New Zealand. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1961. Fruits have firm, fine, crisp, greenish white flesh with a subacid and slightly sweet flavour.

Wijcik.name: Wijcik
Wijcik.description: A bud mutation of McIntosh producing a more compact, erect and rigid tree. Originated in Kelowna, British Columbia, Canada by Anthony Wijcik. Fruits have rather soft, very juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant vinous flavour.

Wilhelm Ley.name: Wilhelm Ley
Wilhelm Ley.description: A more highly coloured sport of Belle de Boskoop. Originated in Wilhelm Ley, Germany. Fruits have firm, coarse-textured flesh with a pleasant aromatic flavour. Cooks well.

William Crump.name: William Crump
William Crump.description: Raised by Carless, foreman at Rowe's Nurseries, Worcester and introduced by them. Received an Award of Merit in 1908 and a First Class Certificate in 1910 from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and rich, aromatic flavour.

William Peters.name: William Peters
William Peters.description: Raised by Peters of Leatherhead, Surrey, England. Recorded in 1917 in which year it received the Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society. Fruits have soft, very tender, rather coarse, yellowish white flesh with a sweet flavour.

Williams Favourite.name: Williams Favourite
Williams Favourite.description: Originated in about 1750 in Roxbury, Massachusetts, USA. Brought to notice in 1830. Fruits have tender, greenish white flesh with a subacid, aromatic flavour.

Wilmuta.name: Wilmuta
Wilmuta.description: A clone of Jonagold. Originated at Proefstation voor Fruitteelt, Wilhelminadorp, the Netherlands. Fruits have creamy white, juicy flesh with a sweet and good rich flavour.

Winesap.name: Winesap
Winesap.description: Originated in the U.S.A. First described in 1817. Fruits have firm, tender, coarse, yellowish white flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Winston.name: Winston
Winston.description: Raised in 1920 by William Pope at Welford Park, Berkshire, England. Introduced (as Winter King) in 1935. Renamed Winston in 1944. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Winston coloured sport.name: Winston coloured sport
Winston coloured sport.description: A sport of Winston having a more solid deep red flush. Originated at the Horticultural Centre, Loughgall, Northern Ireland. First planted in 1952. Fruits have firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Winter Banana.name: Winter Banana
Winter Banana.description: Raised in 1876 on the farm of David Flory near Adamsboro, Cross County, Indiana, USA. Introduced in 1890. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912. Fruits have rather soft, rather coarse-textured,moderately juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant aromatic flavour.

Winter Gem.name: Winter Gem
Winter Gem.description: Raised in 1975 by Mr Hugh Ermen, Faversham, Kent. Introduced in 1993 by Frank P. Matthews Ltd., Tenbury Wells, Worcestershire. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a good, rich flavour.

Winter Lemon.name: Winter Lemon
Winter Lemon.description: Received by the National Fruit Trials from the Ukrainian Scientific Institute of Horticulture, Kiev, Russia in 1969, via Mr B. Tompsett, Tonbridge, Kent. Fruits are crisp and juicy.

Winter Majetin.name: Winter Majetin
Winter Majetin.description: Originated in Norfolk, England. Recorded in 1820. Fruits have crisp, rather coarse, greenish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Winter Marigold.name: Winter Marigold
Winter Marigold.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1865. Fruits have fairly tender, whitish flesh with a sweet and perfumed flavour.

Winter Peach.name: Winter Peach
Winter Peach.description: Thought to have originated in the U.S.A. Known in England in 1853. Fruits have crisp, tender, yellowish flesh with an acid and slightly spicy flavour.

Winter Pearmain.name: Winter Pearmain
Winter Pearmain.description: Thought to be a very old English variety. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellowish flesh with a sweet, subacid flavour.

Winter Quarrenden.name: Winter Quarrenden
Winter Quarrenden.description: Originated in the UK. Introduced by Pearson of Nottingham. Recorded in 1896. Fruits have crisp, tender, greenish yellow flesh with a slightly sweet and perfumed flavour.

Winter Stubbard.name: Winter Stubbard
Winter Stubbard.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have firm, rather coarse, yellowish white flesh with a subacid flavour.

Withington Fillbasket.name: Withington Fillbasket
Withington Fillbasket.description: Originated in the UK. Recorded in 1883. Fruits have firm, crisp, pale yellow flesh with an acid flavour.

Wolf River.name: Wolf River
Wolf River.description: Raised by W.A. Springer near Wolf River, Fremont County, Wisconsin, USA. First recorded in 1875. Fruits have white, tinged green, fine-textured, rather dry flesh with a moderately acid flavour.

Woolbrook Pippin.name: Woolbrook Pippin
Woolbrook Pippin.description: Raised in 1903 by Stevens & Son, Woolbrook Nursery, Sidmouth, Devon. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1929. Fruits have firm, crisp, tender flesh with a sweet, slightly acid, slightly aromatic flavour.

Woolbrook Russet.name: Woolbrook Russet
Woolbrook Russet.description: Raised in 1903 by J.H.Stevens & Son, Woolbrook Nursery, Sidmouth, Devon, England and introduced by them. First fruited in 1912. Received an Award of Merit from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1930. Fruits have rather coarse-textured, juicy flesh with an acid flavour.

Worcester Cross.name: Worcester Cross
Worcester Cross.description: Raised in 1920 at Long Ashton Research Station, Bristol. Introduced in 1932. Fruits have firm, moderately crisp flesh with a moderately sweet flavour.

Worcester Pearmain.name: Worcester Pearmain
Worcester Pearmain.description: Raised by Mr Hale of Swan Pool, near Worcester, England. Introduced by Smith of Worcester in 1874. Received a First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in 1875. Fruits have firm, white, a little juicy flesh with a sweet and pleasant flavour.

Worcester Woodsil.name: Worcester Woodsil
Worcester Woodsil.description: Originated in the UK. Thought to have been raised in the late 19th century. Received at Brogdale in 1992. Fruits are crisp and juicy with a good flavour.

Wrixparent.name: Wrixparent
Wrixparent.description: Thought to be a sport of Yellow Transparent. Discovered in 1920 in Magnolia, Kent County, Delaware, U.S.A. by Wrixham McIlvaine. Introduced in 1940. Fruits have crisp, coarse, juicy flesh.

Wyken Pippin.name: Wyken Pippin
Wyken Pippin.description: Said to have been raised by Lord Craven from seed of a continental apple and planted at Wyken near Coventry. It is also said to have been brought to the UK from Holland in the early 1700s. Fruits have creamy white, moderately firm, fine-textured, juicy flesh with a sweet and good aromatic flavour.

Yamborka.name: Yamborka
Yamborka.description: Thought to have been raised at the State Research Station for Pomology, Kustendil, Bulgaria. It was new in 1957. Fruits have firm, fine, white flesh which browns very quickly when cut. It has a very acid flavour.

Ye Old Peasgood.name: Ye Old Peasgood
Ye Old Peasgood.description: Thought to have been raised by George Carpenter, West Hall Gardens, Byfleet, Surrey. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1932. Fruits have soft, coarse, white to greenish white flesh with an acid flavour.

Yellow Bellflower.name: Yellow Bellflower
Yellow Bellflower.description: Originated near Crosswicks, Burlington County, New Jersey, U.S.A. It was old in 1817. Fruits have moderately firm, crisp, creamy white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Yellow Ingestrie.name: Yellow Ingestrie
Yellow Ingestrie.description: Raised in about 1800 by Thomas Andrew Knight at Wormsley Grange, Herefordshire, England. Fruits have fine, tender, greenish yellow flesh with a rich and subacid flavour.

Yellow Newtown Pippin.name: Yellow Newtown Pippin
Yellow Newtown Pippin.description: Thought to be a sport of Newtown Pippin. Originated at Newtown, Long Island, U.S.A. Well known in 1759. Fruits are less acid than Newtown Pippin and have a more aromatic flavour.

Yellow Pitcher.name: Yellow Pitcher
Yellow Pitcher.description: Originated in Ireland. Described in 1951. Fruits have firm, very white flesh with an insipid flavour.

York-a-Red.name: York-a-Red
York-a-Red.description: A more highly coloured sport of York Imperial. Discovered in 1931 at Hedgesville, West Virginia, U.S.A. by Paul Lingamfelter. Introduced in 1937 by Stark Bros. Nurseries. Fruits have firm, crisp, yellowish flesh with a subacid to sweetish, aromatic flavour.

Yorkshire Greening.name: Yorkshire Greening
Yorkshire Greening.description: Assumed to have originated in Yorkshire, England. It was first recorded in 1803. Fruits have firm, rather coarse-textured, somewhat dry flesh with a very acid flavour.

Young America.name: Young America
Young America.description: Originated in New York, U.S.A. Introduced in the 1800s. Fruits have an acid and astringent flavour.

Young's Pinello.name: Young's Pinello
Young's Pinello.description: Raised by Miss E.L. Young, Letchworth, Hertfordshire. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1935. Fruits have firm, fairly tender, white flesh with a subacid to sweet, slightly aromatic flavour.

Zabergau Renette.name: Zabergau Renette
Zabergau Renette.description: Raised at Hausen on the Zaber, Wurttemberg, Germany from seed sown in 1885. Fruits have firm, moderately fine-textured, fairly juicy flesh with a rich, nutty flavour.

Zelyonka Kharkovskaya.name: Zelyonka Kharkovskaya
Zelyonka Kharkovskaya.description: Originated in the first half of the 1800's in Russia. Fruits have rather soft, greenish white flesh.

Zoete Ermgaard.name: Zoete Ermgaard
Zoete Ermgaard.description: Originated in the Netherlands. Known since 1864. Fruits have firm, crisp, coarse, dry, creamy white flesh with a sweet, slightly subacid flavour.

Zomer Delicious.name: Zomer Delicious
Zomer Delicious.description: Raised at IVT, Wageningen, the Netherlands. Received by the National Fruit Trials in 1966. Fruits have soft, juicy flesh with a sweet flavour.
